-- Eprad eCNA Cinema Automation Interface (CAI) Plugin
-- Protocol: CAI ASCII over TCP, plus HTTP scrape/control for I/O flags,
-- user-defined names, (v1.2+) Eprad QDC-400 dimmer lighting, and (v1.3+)
-- Eprad nanoHost POS management data.
-- Reference: eCNA Operation and Installation Manual, Section 6
--
-- v1.2: Adds monitoring and control of the Eprad QDC-400 dimmer lighting
-- system (Status: Light Control web page, manual Section 5.9). The CAI
-- serial protocol (port 13002) has NO commands for Zone 3-16 lights,
-- individual channel levels, or light level offset -- only House/Stage
-- lights are reachable via CAI OUT codes. QDC monitoring/control is only
-- possible via the eCNA's HTTP web interface (rtLights.xml), so this
-- feature is implemented entirely through the existing single-connection
-- HTTP scrape/queue architecture from v1.1, not the CAI socket.
--
-- v1.3 (in progress): Adds read-only support for the Eprad nanoHost POS
-- Management Data screen (manual Section 5.10, "Status: Management Data").
-- This is a SEPARATE physical Eprad device; the eCNA merely relays what the
-- nanoHost last reported (updates no faster than every 5 minutes per Steve,
-- so this feature is deliberately polled far slower than scrape/lightpoll --
-- see NANO_POLL_RATE below). Nothing on this page causes any action; it is
-- purely informational.
--
-- v1.3.0.32: two timing changes, per Steve. (1) NANO_POLL_RATE reduced from
-- 150s (2.5 min) to 120s (2 min). (2) forceEarlyNanoHostRefresh's delay
-- reduced from 4s to 3s.
--
-- v1.3.0.31: word-wrap confirmed working (Steve). Both paragraph-break
-- gaps (Cyan->Yellow, Yellow->help sentence) halved from 16px to 8px --
-- Steve reported they were reading as roughly double the Key-header-to-
-- Cyan-paragraph gap, which he confirmed was the correct amount. Some
-- visible separation kept (not removed entirely), since that spacing was
-- explicitly requested in 1.3.0.29.
--
-- v1.3.0.30: Key section reformatted, per Steve. The Cyan LED explanation
-- is now ONE paragraph (both sentences combined into a single, taller
-- Label sized for 2 lines) allowed to word-wrap, rather than split into
-- two explicit lines -- Steve explicitly asked for wrapping here (unlike
-- the top instructions paragraph, where wrapping was avoided out of
-- caution) since he expects it's likely needed given the combined length.
-- NOT fully confirmed this Label type wraps rather than clips -- worth
-- checking once visible in Designer. Added a blank-line paragraph break
-- before the Yellow LED paragraph and again before the help-file sentence.
--
-- v1.3.0.29: three changes, per Steve. (1) Key section's old single "Show
-- Start/End..." sentence replaced with four separate lines explaining the
-- Cyan/Yellow highlight LEDs and their relationship to the Status Flags,
-- plus a pointer to the help file -- kept as explicit separate Labels
-- (not one long line relying on text-wrap), same reasoning as the top
-- instructions paragraph split in 1.3.0.16. Page height grows naturally to
-- fit (no explicit page-size constant exists in this file to adjust).
-- (2) Both refresh-trigger delays (Time Before Feature Start/End reaching
-- 0:01) reduced from 5 seconds to 4.
--
-- v1.3.0.28 BUG FIX (real field report: "POS Ticket Sold... is staying
-- true"): xmlTag() finds the FIRST occurrence of "<tag>" anywhere in
-- whatever string it's given. Every top-level Stat flag/timer/marker read
-- used the FULL response body -- but <Screen> (which comes BEFORE <Stat>
-- in the document) contains its own per-show <Sold> and <Cancel> tags
-- inside each <StartTime> block, same tag names as the top-level Stat
-- flags. So the top-level "Sold" lookup was silently picking up the FIRST
-- show's own per-show Sold value instead of the real Stat/Sold flag -- and
-- since a day's first performance is very often already sold by the time
-- you're checking status later on, POS Ticket Sold ended up pinned true
-- regardless of the actual live flag. NanoHost_Cancel has the identical
-- latent bug (Stat and per-show both have a <Cancel> tag) -- purely masked
-- in every test/capture used so far because both happened to be 0
-- together every time. No other Stat field collides with a per-show tag
-- name (RunTim vs RunTime, Start vs StartTime, etc. differ enough that the
-- substring search doesn't cross-match) -- confirmed by checking every
-- Stat tag against the full per-show field set, not just assumed. Fixed
-- by scoping every top-level lookup to the <Stat>...</Stat> substring
-- specifically. Verified two ways: an isolated test proving the OLD code
-- really would have returned the wrong value for this exact bug (not just
-- that the new code returns the right one), and a true end-to-end test
-- through the real parseNanoHost function confirming both the top-level
-- flags and the independently-correct per-show values.
--
-- v1.3.0.27: two changes, per Steve. (1) Time Before Feature End now also
-- triggers an early nanoHost refresh when it reaches 0:01, same one-shot-
-- per-countdown mechanism as Time Before Feature Start's trigger from
-- 1.3.0.26. Both now share a unified 5-second delay (was 2s for Start-only
-- in 1.3.0.26) via a new shared forceEarlyNanoHostRefresh() helper.
-- (2) Sentinel-freeze: per Steve, 255:59 (NANO_TIME_MAX) on a "before"
-- counter means the eCNA has no real countdown data yet, not a genuine
-- 255-minute-59-second duration -- BSTim/BETim now freeze instead of
-- ticking down whenever already AT the sentinel, only resuming a real
-- countdown once an actual poll provides a value below it. This also
-- correctly keeps ASTim/AETim from starting either, since their gating
-- already depends on BSTim/BETim reaching exactly 0, which can't happen
-- from a frozen sentinel. The up-counters themselves are unchanged --
-- still count up and cap AT the sentinel as their normal ceiling (already
-- true of all four timers via clampNanoSec since 1.3.0.3, confirmed still
-- correct here, not a new change). Verified with dedicated tests: BETim's
-- trigger fires exactly once with the new 5s delay; BSTim/BETim seeded at
-- the sentinel stay frozen across 20 ticks with ASTim/AETim correctly
-- never starting; a subsequent real poll with an actual value correctly
-- overrides the freeze and resumes normal countdown.
--
-- v1.3.0.26: two changes, per Steve. (1) When Time Before Start reaches
-- 0:01 (one tick before its real 0:00 crossover), force an early nanoHost
-- flag refresh 2 seconds later, giving the eCNA time to update its own
-- flags around show start rather than waiting up to NANO_POLL_RATE (150s)
-- for the next routine poll. Triggered on "==1" rather than "==0"
-- specifically because BSTim floors at 0 and stays there (checking "==0"
-- would refire every tick indefinitely); a strictly-decreasing count can
-- only equal 1 once per countdown, so no separate one-shot guard is
-- needed. Implemented by forcing nanoTicks to nanoPollEveryNTicks, reusing
-- httpRequest()'s existing NANOHOST poll tier rather than adding a new
-- one. Verified with a dedicated test: fires exactly once per countdown,
-- the forced fetch is genuinely delayed 2 seconds (not immediate), and it
-- results in a real second /rtmandata.xml fetch. (2) Six Show Timer labels
-- renamed to include "Feature" (Feature Run Time / Time Between Features /
-- Time Before Feature Start / Time After Feature Start / Time Before
-- Feature End / Time After Feature End) -- control names and pins
-- unchanged, only the on-screen labels/PrettyNames and GetControls
-- Description strings changed.
--
-- v1.3.0.25: "darkgray" swapped for "dimgray" for the marker off-color --
-- despite the names, "dimgray" (rgb 105,105,105) is actually darker/more
-- muted than "darkgray" (rgb 169,169,169), a CSS naming quirk analogous to
-- lime being brighter than green (v1.3.0.23). Applied to both the runtime
-- (setMarkerLed) and the layout-time pre-poll defaults.
--
-- v1.3.0.24: per Steve, all four markers' inactive/off color switched to a
-- uniform "darkgray" -- active colors (pink/lime/chocolate/orange)
-- unchanged, already confirmed correct against real hardware. Supersedes
-- 1.3.0.23's FE-specific green fix with a simpler, uniform "off is off"
-- convention across the whole marker cluster. Applied to both the runtime
-- (setMarkerLed) and the layout-time pre-poll defaults. "darkgray" is a new
-- string not yet confirmed on real hardware -- same pcall-protected
-- safe-fallback-to-green pattern as every other named color in this file
-- covers it if it somehow isn't valid.
--
-- v1.3.0.23: FE's inactive color split off from its active color, per
-- Steve's field feedback. He confirmed the ACTIVE lime is correct (matches
-- the real page), but the INACTIVE/dimmed lime still looked "almost on" --
-- vibrant rather than dull -- compared to Cancel's correctly-dull green in
-- the same screenshot. CSS-style "lime" (rgb(0,255,0), maximal saturation)
-- apparently doesn't dim as visibly as "green" (rgb(0,128,0), already a
-- darker shade) -- Cancel already proves "green" dims correctly. FS/LS/LE
-- (pink/chocolate/orange) weren't flagged as a problem and are unchanged --
-- narrow, targeted fix for FE specifically: lime when active, green when
-- inactive (both layout-time default and runtime). Verified with a
-- dedicated test confirming FE flips lime/green correctly across the
-- active/inactive transition while FS (and by the same logic LS/LE) keeps
-- the same color in both states, unaffected.
--
-- v1.3.0.22: two changes on top of the 1.3.0.21 baseline. (1) Screen_Id
-- replaces the old NanoHost_Screen -- confirmed directly in the eCNA-10
-- manual's own RID documentation that the RSP,RID response's record
-- contains Device Name, Software Version, AND Screen Id as its three codes
-- (worked example: "RSP,RID,0,0,eCNA-10,1007,27,1630" -> field 7="27" is
-- Screen Id), the exact same response Model/Firmware Version already come
-- from. Screen_Id is now unconditional -- no longer gated behind
-- Enable_NanoHost at all, since screen identity is a general eCNA
-- property, not a nanoHost-specific one -- moved to the Setup page right
-- alongside Model/Firmware. Verified with a true end-to-end test driving
-- the manual's own example through the real CAI socket -> processLine ->
-- parseRID path (not just isolated logic), confirming Model/Firmware/
-- Screen_Id all populate correctly even with Enable_NanoHost=false. (2)
-- The off-color fix (markers keep their own hue when inactive, instead of
-- resetting to green) reintroduced as the ONE isolated feature Steve asked
-- to test on top of the 1.3.0.21 reset -- deliberately nothing else from
-- the 1.3.0.18-20 lineage carried forward alongside it, so if this
-- specific change turns out to cause a problem, it'll be unambiguous which
-- one did it.
--
-- v1.3.0.21: DELIBERATE RESET, per Steve. Builds 1.3.0.18 through 1.3.0.20
-- introduced a real, still-unresolved bug -- enabling Enable_NanoHost makes
-- Q-SYS Designer's Script Programmer Mode show ONLY a generic "Disable"
-- pin instead of the plugin's real Input/Output pins, and the same thing
-- happens to every other page's non-text controls too. This happens before
-- any compile or emulation -- purely from GetControls being invoked by
-- Designer's UI -- confirming it's a design-time GetControls failure, not
-- a runtime issue. Two reasoned, evidence-based fix attempts (1.3.0.19's
-- ButtonType/ButtonStyle correction, 1.3.0.20's restored numeric-property
-- coercion) did NOT resolve it, and a full diff against this confirmed-
-- working 1.3.0.17 baseline didn't turn up anything else obviously wrong.
-- Rather than keep guessing on top of an already-murky base, this build
-- starts CLEAN from 1.3.0.17 (the last version Steve explicitly confirmed
-- working, with screenshots) plus only two additional, narrow, low-risk
-- changes: (1) IsBold=true on the "Show Timers"/"Status Flags" headers,
-- replacing the confirmed-ineffective FontStyle="Bold" (FontSize kept at
-- 13, unchanged from 1.3.0.17 -- the FontSize=17 bump from 1.3.0.18 was
-- NOT carried forward, since it wasn't part of what was asked for here);
-- (2) Cancel LED shifted 4px left. Everything else from 1.3.0.18-20 --
-- the off-color fix, NanoHost_HideEmptyRows toggle, the numeric-coercion
-- restoration, the ButtonType lesson -- is INTENTIONALLY not present in
-- this build. This is the new baseline for any further changes; the
-- disappearing-pins bug itself is still open and unresolved, to be
-- revisited once this baseline is confirmed solid.
--
-- v1.3.0.17: (1) FS/FE/LS/LE restored to the real palette (pink/lime/
-- chocolate/orange) now that named strings are confirmed to work broadly,
-- not just "green"/"red" -- same safe-baseline-then-pcall-upgrade pattern
-- as the Now Playing highlight. (2) Instructions paragraph above "Status"
-- removed entirely, reclaiming the space, per Steve. (3) Row number is now
-- a real control (NanoHost_Show_RowNum, was static graphics) specifically
-- so an entire row -- LEDs, text boxes, and its number -- can be hidden
-- together when there's no scheduled performance there, rather than
-- leaving unused controls visible. BUG CAUGHT BY OWN TEST SUITE before
-- shipping: the row-visibility helper initially also forced
-- NanoHost_Show_Start/End (the Now Playing highlight LEDs) visible
-- whenever a row had data, overwriting their own separate "is this
-- actually the currently-airing performance" logic -- fixed by excluding
-- those two from the blanket row-visibility toggle, since they're governed
-- by a different, more granular concept.
--
-- v1.3.0.16: field confirmation from Steve that named string colors (not
-- just "green"/"red") work fine for BOTH LED colors and Text control fill
-- -- cyan/yellow/black all rendered correctly on real hardware; it's
-- specifically RGB tables that don't work, not named strings generally.
-- UI polish round: (1) NanoHost_Screen relocated to the Setup page's Device
-- Info section (still gated on Enable_NanoHost) -- per Steve, useful for
-- "most any system" and will have a specific use in v1.4. (2) PerfNum
-- column widened (was clipped). (3) Sold/Cancel LEDs now centered under
-- their headers instead of left-aligned at the header box's start x.
-- (4) Row numbers vertically centered (+3, matching the LEDs) instead of
-- sitting at the row's top edge. (5) The top instructions paragraph and the
-- Key legend were both split into multiple explicit shorter lines with
-- their own fixed heights, instead of one long line relying on unconfirmed
-- text-wrap behavior -- per Steve, both were getting clipped/hard to read.
--
-- v1.3.0.15: "Now Playing" highlight recreated closer to the real page's
-- own StartTime/RunTime cell-highlight approach, per Steve. Two parts:
-- (1) EXPERIMENTAL, pcall-protected attempt to color the StartTime/RunTime
-- TEXT controls themselves (cyan/yellow) -- genuinely unverified whether
-- Q-SYS's Text-style Color is even runtime-settable or what it affects;
-- can never crash the plugin even if unsupported, since it's fully
-- pcall-wrapped. (2) Guaranteed-safe fallback: the existing
-- NanoHost_Show_Start/NanoHost_Show_End marker LEDs (same controls, no
-- renaming) moved out of the FS/FE/LS/LE cluster to sit immediately next to
-- StartTime/RunTime, now using IsInvisible toggling (hidden when not the
-- currently-airing performance, visible when it is) instead of the small
-- always-visible dot used for FS/FE/LS/LE. Color is set to "green" first
-- (known-safe, always succeeds) then pcall-upgraded to cyan/yellow --
-- degrades gracefully to green if those specific strings aren't valid on
-- real hardware, same lesson as the v1.3.0.13 crash fix.
--
-- v1.3.0.14: widened the Show Schedule's "Cancel" column header (was
-- clipping the word at 25px wide) -- confirmed against a real screenshot.
--
-- v1.3.0.13 BUG FIX (real hardware crash, field report): "3114: bad
-- argument #2 to '__newindex' (string expected, got table)" -- crashing at
-- plugin STARTUP, before any poll ever ran, since blankShowSchedule() runs
-- unconditionally at startup. Root cause: Controls.X.Color only accepts a
-- STRING on real Q-SYS hardware, not an RGB table -- the opposite of what
-- was assumed when v1.3.0.12 picked RGB triples to exactly match the real
-- page's pink/lime/cyan/yellow/chocolate/orange marker colors. This was the
-- one place in the whole file that broke from the "Color is always a plain
-- string" pattern used everywhere else since v1.2, without having verified
-- it against real hardware first. Fixed by using "green" (one of only two
-- string values -- "green"/"red" -- confirmed extensively safe across this
-- entire project) for every active Show Schedule marker instead. The marker
-- LOGIC (which row/column lights up) is unaffected and still matches
-- Steve's real XML capture exactly -- only the color richness is reduced,
-- pending confirmation of which other named-color strings Q-SYS actually
-- accepts.
--
-- v1.3.0.12: Show Schedule (the nanoHost page's lower section) implemented
-- for the first time, confirmed against a real rtmandata.xml capture from
-- Steve. Provisioned for MAX_SHOWS=10 rows (fixed, per Steve). Each row:
-- StartTime/RunTime/PerfNum/Title (text), Sold (Led, Green=1/Red=0), Cancel
-- (Led, reverse logic Green=0/Red=1), and six independent row markers
-- (FS/FE/Start/End/LS/LE) colored to match the real page's own Key legend
-- exactly (pink/lime/cyan/yellow/chocolate/orange). A Screen readout was
-- also added (the bare number under <Screen> in the XML) since Steve noted
-- this specific site is "Screen 1," worth carrying forward for future
-- multi-screen sites even though it's a single fixed value today. Rows
-- beyond the actual show count, and the whole section whenever HostUp is
-- false, are blanked (same principle as the Show Timers section). Verified
-- with a full runtime test replaying Steve's actual XML capture end to end
-- -- every field and every marker color matches his screenshot exactly
-- (row 1: FS+FE; row 4: LS; no row: LE, since LE=255 is the "not
-- applicable" sentinel).
--
-- v1.3.0.11: NanoHost column headers ("Show Timers"/"Status Flags") are now
-- Bold and black (previously regular-weight via textlbl(), which didn't
-- differentiate them enough from the row labels below). Also recentered:
-- the MIDDLE of each header now sits on the demising line between that
-- column's labels and its value element (field start x for Show Timers,
-- LED start x for Status Flags), rather than centered over the column's
-- full span as in 1.3.0.10.
--
-- v1.3.0.10: NanoHost page tweaks -- (1) timer labels shifted 5px left
-- (were overlapping the field start by 5px: 170-wide label box at LX=10 has
-- a right edge of 180, but the field starts at FX+45=175); (2) timer fields
-- widened from 80 to 100px (80 was too narrow, particularly for Time of
-- Day's date+time string); (3) both "Show Timers"/"Status Flags" column
-- headers now centered over their actual column spans (label-box-start to
-- field/LED-right-edge) instead of left-aligned at the column's start x.
--
-- v1.3.0.9: NanoHost page UI rework -- working forward from the confirmed-
-- good 1.3.0.4 baseline (see REVERTED note above; 1.3.0.5-1.3.0.8 stay
-- scrapped). Show Timers and Status Flags are now one combined side-by-side
-- section instead of two stacked ones, per Steve, recreating (to a degree)
-- the real nanoHost web page's own paired-column "Control Data" table:
-- Show Timers on the left (unchanged row layout), Status Flags moved to the
-- right with labels now to the LEFT of their LEDs (reversed from before)
-- and every LED at one fixed x position so they line up in a single
-- vertical column regardless of label text length.
--
-- v1.3.0.4: fixed ASTim/AETim ticking up independently of whether their own
-- BSTim/BETim counterpart had reached 0 -- confirmed via a real side-by-side
-- capture that the device holds "after" at 0:00 until "before" reaches 0.
-- Each up-counter is now gated on its own down-counter having hit exactly 0.
--
-- v1.3.0.3: (1) the four extrapolated timers (Time Before/After Start,
-- Time Before/After End) are now clamped to NANO_TIME_MAX (255:59) --
-- confirmed via field capture that a locally-ticked up-counter could
-- otherwise walk past the device's own observed ceiling for that field.
-- (2) Time of Day is no longer read from the nanoHost at all -- per Steve,
-- it was awkward for it to sit stale for minutes at a time, so it's now
-- generated directly from the Q-SYS Core's own clock (os.date), ticked
-- every second, independent of nanoHost connectivity/HostUp/nanoValid.
--
-- v1.3.0.2: (1) nanoHost's initial /rtmandata.xml fetch now happens in the
-- same top-priority bootstrap burst as input/output names, dimmer setup,
-- and LIN scan while "Initializing" -- no longer waiting up to
-- NANO_POLL_RATE seconds for the first slow routine poll turn. (2) The four
-- fields that behave as genuine live counters (Time Before/After Start,
-- Time Before/After End) are now extrapolated locally once per second
-- between the infrequent real polls, corrected back to ground truth by each
-- new poll -- see the state-block comment near `populated`/`nanoValid` for
-- the full anti-faking design (never extrapolate before a real poll has
-- landed; blank everything whenever HostUp is false, per Steve: "any time
-- the Host Up is not true, the Time counters are not true either").
--
-- IMPORTANT: the eCNA-10 manual documents only the rendered screen, not the
-- underlying XML. The endpoint name (/rtmandata.xml) and field tags below
-- (HostUp/PosEna/PosOk/InSho/Sold/Cancel/RunTim/BtwTim/BSTim/ASTim/BETim/
-- AETim/Tod) are taken from a real eCNA-5 unit's own web client source
-- (statManData.htm/statManDataJs.js) for the equivalent "Management Data"
-- screen. Per Steve: the eCNA-5 and eCNA-10 use the same CPU and the same
-- command set, so this is treated as confirmed for eCNA-10 too, not merely
-- a hint -- no separate eCNA-10 capture needed for the upper (flags/timers)
-- section. The lower "shows schedule" table (PosData/Screen, variable row
-- count) still isn't implemented yet -- its structure wasn't fully spelled
-- out by the reference source (generic/dynamic column-building), so that
-- part still benefits from a real sample page once available, per Steve.

PluginInfo = {
  Name         = "Eprad~eCNA v1.3.0.32",
  Manufacturer = "STG",
  Version      = "1.3.0.32",
  Id           = "8cd1a925-90ba-4640-8de9-886632d1e242",
  Description  = "Controls the Eprad eCNA Cinema Automation system via the CAI ASCII TCP interface, with optional Eprad QDC dimmer lighting monitoring/control and optional Eprad nanoHost POS management data display.",
  ShowDebug    = true,
  Author       = "Based on HTTP script 1.3.1 by Jay Wyatt and Steve Guttag."
}

function GetColor(props)
  return { 72, 147, 217 }
end

-- v1.3.0.12: fixed max provisioned NanoHost Show Schedule rows -- per Steve
-- ("I would have a provision for 10 rows"), not a property, since he gave a
-- specific number directly rather than asking for user-tunability. Shared
-- by GetControls/GetControlLayout (control declarations/positions) and the
-- runtime parser (which populates rows 1..#shows and blanks the rest).
local MAX_SHOWS = 10

-- ============================================================
-- PAGE LIST: builds the list of visible tabs based on properties
-- Debug tab visibility controlled by Show_Debug property
-- ============================================================
local function buildPageList(props)
  local pages = {"Setup", "Outputs"}
  local enableQDC = props["Enable_QDC_Lighting"] and props["Enable_QDC_Lighting"].Value or false
  if enableQDC then table.insert(pages, "Dimmer Control") end
  table.insert(pages, "Inputs")
  local numMacros  = props["Num_Macros"]  and props["Num_Macros"].Value  or 50
  local numRDI     = props["Num_RDI"]     and props["Num_RDI"].Value     or 5
  if numMacros > 0 then table.insert(pages, "Macros") end
  if numRDI    > 0 then table.insert(pages, "RDI")    end
  table.insert(pages, "Program")
  -- v1.3: nanoHost Management Data page, appended after Program per Steve.
  -- Purely a Yes/No reveal -- no dependent sub-properties like QDC_Zones/
  -- QDC_Channels, so unlike those it's fine for this one to actually be
  -- absent from the property set's effect on the page list (nothing else
  -- needs to stay "always visible" for reactive-redraw reasons).
  local enableNanoHost = props["Enable_NanoHost"] and props["Enable_NanoHost"].Value or false
  if enableNanoHost then table.insert(pages, "NanoHost") end
  return pages
end

-- ============================================================
-- QDC LIGHTING CONFIG: shared helper for design-time functions
-- (GetControls / GetProperties / GetControlLayout / GetPages all
-- receive their own `props` snapshot -- this is NOT the runtime
-- Properties table used inside "if Controls then").
-- ============================================================
local function qdcConfig(props)
  local enabled = props["Enable_QDC_Lighting"] and props["Enable_QDC_Lighting"].Value or false
  local zones    = enabled and (props["QDC_Zones"]    and props["QDC_Zones"].Value    or 2) or 0
  local channels = enabled and (props["QDC_Channels"] and props["QDC_Channels"].Value or 2) or 0
  return enabled, zones, channels
end

-- ============================================================
-- CONTROLS DEFINITION
-- All plugin controls are declared here with type, pin style, etc.
-- ============================================================
function GetControls(props)
  local ctrls = {}
  local numMacros = props["Num_Macros"] and props["Num_Macros"].Value or 50
  local numRDI    = props["Num_RDI"]    and props["Num_RDI"].Value    or 5
  local enableQDC, qZones, qChannels = qdcConfig(props)

  -- Setup / Connection
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="IP_ADDRESS",       ControlType="Text",   Count=1, UserPin=true,  PinStyle="Input",  Description="eCNA IP Address" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="TCP_PORT",         ControlType="Text",   Count=1, UserPin=true,  PinStyle="Input",  Description="TCP Port (default 13002)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, {
    Name="Status", ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Status",
    PinStyle="Output", UserPin=true, Count=1
  })
  table.insert(ctrls, {
    Name="Status_LED", ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Status",
    PinStyle="Output", UserPin=true, Count=1
  })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Reconnect",        ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true,  PinStyle="Input",  ButtonType="Momentary", Description="Force reconnect" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Model",            ControlType="Text",   Count=1, UserPin=true,  PinStyle="Output", Description="Device model (from RID)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Firmware_Version", ControlType="Text",   Count=1, UserPin=true,  PinStyle="Output", Description="Firmware version (from RID)" })
  -- v1.3.0.22: confirmed in the eCNA-10 manual's own RID documentation --
  -- the RSP,RID record contains Device Name, Software Version, AND Screen
  -- Id as its three codes (code 3 = "Screen Id. Decimal number: 0 to 63"),
  -- same response we already parse Model/Firmware Version from. Always
  -- available, independent of Enable_NanoHost -- unlike the old nanoHost-
  -- sourced Screen control this replaces.
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Screen_Id",        ControlType="Text",   Count=1, UserPin=true,  PinStyle="Output", Description="Screen Id, 0-63 (from RID)" })

  -- Program state (all text outputs from RST polling)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Control_State",  ControlType="Text",  Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="IDL=Idle / RUN=Running" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Stopped_State",  ControlType="Text",  Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="OK / STP / FLT / FIR" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cue_Number",     ControlType="Text",  Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Current cue number" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Program_Number", ControlType="Text",  Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Active program number" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Segment_Name",   ControlType="Text",  Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Current segment name" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Segment_Index",  ControlType="Text",  Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Current segment index" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="CAI_CMD_Access", ControlType="Text",  Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="OK=Full access / BLK=Blocked" })

  -- EVT Transport Commands (Trigger type - fire on press, no toggle state)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Start",        ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger",   Description="Start/Resume (EVT STA)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Stop",         ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger",   Description="Stop (EVT STP)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Cue",          ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger",   Description="Cue (EVT CUE)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Abort",        ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger",   Description="Abort (EVT ABT)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Fault",        ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger",   Description="Set Fault (EVT FLT)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Clear_Fault",  ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger",   Description="Clear Fault (EVT CLR)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Reset",        ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger",   Description="Reset Fault (EVT RES)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Cancel_Alarm", ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger",   Description="Cancel Alarm (EVT CNL)" })

  -- Program selection (ComboBox for program number, Trigger for execute)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Set_Program",     ControlType="Text",   Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input",  Description="Program number to set" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Set_Program", ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input",  ButtonType="Trigger", Description="Set Program (EVT PGM,d)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Cmd_Set_And_Run", ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input",  ButtonType="Trigger", Description="Set & Run (EVT SPR,d)" })

  -- Macros (Trigger type - fire and forget, count set by property)
  if numMacros > 0 then
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Macros", ControlType="Button", Count=numMacros, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger", Description="Trigger macro 1-N (EVT MAC,n)" })
  end

  -- RDI Remote Device Interface (Trigger type, up to 5 devices x 16 commands)
  if numRDI > 0 then
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="RDI", ControlType="Button", Count=numRDI*16, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger", Description="RDI device commands (EVT RDI,dev,cmd)" })
  end

  -- OUT: Lights (mutually exclusive Toggle arrays - scrape drives state)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="House_Lights", ControlType="Button", Count=5, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="House Lights: 1=None 2=Down 3=Mid1 4=Mid2 5=Up" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Stage_Lights", ControlType="Button", Count=3, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Stage Lights: 1=None 2=Down 3=Up" })

  -- OUT: Curtain / Masking / Lens (mutually exclusive Toggle)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Curtain", ControlType="Button", Count=3, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Curtain: 1=None 2=Close 3=Open" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Masking", ControlType="Button", Count=4, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Masking: 1=None 2=Flat 3=Scope 4=Special" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Lens",    ControlType="Button", Count=4, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Lens: 1=None 2=Flat 3=Scope 4=Special" })

  -- OUT: Sound (mutually exclusive Toggle) + Mute (independent Toggle)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Sound", ControlType="Button", Count=9, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Sound: 1=None 2=Aux1 3=Aux2 4=Dig1 5=Dig2 6=Mono 7=NonSync 8=SR 9=SVA" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Mute",  ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Sound Mute" })

  -- OUT: Digital Projectors (Toggle - state driven by RST polling)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Dig1_Power",    ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Dig Proj1 Power" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Dig1_Video",    ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Dig Proj1 Video" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Dig2_Power",    ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Dig Proj2 Power" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Dig2_Video",    ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Dig Proj2 Video" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Aux_Projector", ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Slide Projector" })

  -- Aux digital outputs 1-16 (Toggle - state driven by scrape)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Aux_Out", ControlType="Button", Count=16, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both", ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Aux Outputs 1-16" })

  -- User-defined names fetched from eCNA on connect (Setup.xml)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="In_Names",  ControlType="Text", Count=16, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="User-defined Input names (In1-In16)" })
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Out_Names", ControlType="Text", Count=16, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="User-defined Aux Output names (Out1-Out16)" })

  -- Web scrape output/input flag indicators (LED indicators, driven by scrape)
  -- (Outputs 1-44 removed in v1.2.0.20 -- it was a write-only internal
  -- mirror with no PrettyName/layout and nothing ever read it back;
  -- flagActive() derives directly from the parsed flag list instead. Kept
  -- as a Control it only produced 88 permanent plugin-checker complaints
  -- for zero functional benefit.)
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Inputs",  ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=31, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Input flags (web scrape)" })

  -- Name refresh trigger buttons
  table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Refresh_Setup", ControlType="Button", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Input", ButtonType="Trigger", Description="Re-fetch everything normally only fetched once at connect: input/output names, and (if QDC lighting is enabled) zone names, dimmer level/fade settings, and QDC-400 board count. Use after changing any of these at the eCNA." })

  -- ── QDC-400 Dimmer Lighting (v1.2, only when Enable_QDC_Lighting=Yes) ──
  -- Zone rows: fixed House(1)/Stage(2), user-defined Zone3-N via Setup.xml PgIdx=13
  -- Channel bars: output level per channel via rtLights.xml <cact>
  if enableQDC then
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Zone_Name",           ControlType="Text",   Count=qZones,     UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Zone name: House, Stage, or user-defined (Zone 3-16)" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Zone_Preset",         ControlType="Button", Count=qZones*5,   UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both",   ButtonType="Toggle", Description="Zone light preset, 5 per zone in order Up/Down/Mid1/Mid2/None" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Zone_Offset",         ControlType="Knob",   ControlUnit="Percent", Count=qZones,     UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both",   Min=-100, Max=100, Description="Zone light level offset %, -100 to +100" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Zone_Offset_Text",    ControlType="Text",   Count=qZones,     UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both",   Description="Zone light level offset % (editable), -100 to +100" })
    -- v1.2.0.41: momentary step buttons beside the offset readout. A quick
    -- press/release nudges the offset by 1; holding past 2s repeats at 1
    -- unit per 0.5s until released. ButtonType="Momentary" (not "Toggle" or
    -- "Trigger") so Boolean genuinely tracks pressed/held/released, which
    -- the hold-to-repeat timer logic below depends on.
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Zone_Offset_Dec",     ControlType="Button", Count=qZones,     UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both",   ButtonType="Momentary", Description="Decrease zone offset by 1; hold to repeat at 1 per 0.5s after 2s" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Zone_Offset_Inc",     ControlType="Button", Count=qZones,     UserPin=true, PinStyle="Both",   ButtonType="Momentary", Description="Increase zone offset by 1; hold to repeat at 1 per 0.5s after 2s" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Channel_Level",       ControlType="Knob",   ControlUnit="Percent", Count=qChannels,  UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Min=0, Max=100, Description="Dimmer channel output level %, 0 to 100" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Channel_Level_Text",  ControlType="Text",   Count=qChannels,  UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Dimmer channel output level % (text)" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Channel_Zone",        ControlType="Text",   Count=qChannels,  UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Zone name assigned to this dimmer channel" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="Channel_Present",     ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=qChannels, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Lit when this channel has reported a non-zero level at least once; goes dark after 2 consecutive 0% polls where a non-zero level was expected (likely no dimmer/power present)" })
    -- Refresh_Dimmer_Setup and Refresh_LIN_Network consolidated into the
    -- single Refresh_Setup control above (v1.2.0.11).
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="QDC_Board_Count",       ControlType="Text",   Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Number of active QDC-400 boards found on the Local I/O (LIN) Network at last check" })
  end

  -- (Last_Tx/Last_Rx/Last_Error and the Debug tab that displayed them were
  -- removed entirely in v1.2.0.21 -- every value they ever showed was
  -- already duplicated to the Q-SYS Debug window via dbg()/print(), which
  -- is unconditionally active and is what's actually used for
  -- troubleshooting in practice. See the help file for the full note.)

  -- ── nanoHost POS Management Data (v1.3, only when Enable_NanoHost=Yes) ──
  -- Informational only -- nothing here causes any action. The six status
  -- flags are Indicator/Led controls so they get BOTH a colored LED on the
  -- page AND a true/false output pin per Steve's spec, same pattern as
  -- Channel_Present above. Green=1/Red=0 for all except NanoHost_Cancel,
  -- which is reverse logic (Green=0/not cancelled, Red=1/cancelled) -- see
  -- setNanoFlag()/setNanoFlagRev() in the runtime section.
  local enableNanoHost = props["Enable_NanoHost"] and props["Enable_NanoHost"].Value or false
  if enableNanoHost then
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_TicketSold", ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="POS Ticket Sold (highest-priority nanoHost flag)" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_InShow",      ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="POS In Show" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_PosOk",       ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="POS Ok" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_PosEnabled",  ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="POS Enabled" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_HostUp",      ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="nanoHost Up" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Cancel",      ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="POS Cancel (reverse logic: Green=0/not cancelled, Red=1/cancelled)" })

    -- Timers, MM:SS text (same six shown alongside the flags on the real
    -- nanoHost screen). Read-only outputs, not pinned as separately
    -- actionable controls beyond visibility -- but still UserPin so they
    -- can be watched/logged externally like everything else in this plugin.
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_TimeOfDay",         ControlType="Text", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Current time of day, generated locally by this plugin (not read from the nanoHost) -- always live" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_TimeOfShow",        ControlType="Text", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Feature Run Time, MM:SS" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_TimeBetweenShows",  ControlType="Text", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Time Between Features, MM:SS" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_TimeBeforeStart",   ControlType="Text", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Time Before Feature Start, MM:SS" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_TimeAfterStart",    ControlType="Text", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Time After Feature Start, MM:SS" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_TimeBeforeEnd",     ControlType="Text", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Time Before Feature End, MM:SS" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_TimeAfterEnd",      ControlType="Text", Count=1, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Time After Feature End, MM:SS" })

    -- ── Show Schedule (v1.3.0.12) ──────────────────────────────────
    -- Confirmed against a real rtmandata.xml capture: <Screen> carries a
    -- bare screen number before its <StartTime> children. Each <StartTime>
    -- element carries both its own text (the date/time) AND child elements
    -- (RunTime/PerfNum/Sold/Cancel/Title) -- confirmed structure, not a
    -- guess. Provisioned for MAX_SHOWS=10 rows per Steve; rows beyond the
    -- actual show count for the day are blanked at runtime.
    --
    -- v1.3.0.22: the Screen control that used to live here (sourced from
    -- <Screen> in nanoHost's own rtmandata.xml, gated behind Enable_
    -- NanoHost) is GONE -- per Steve, screen identity is a general eCNA
    -- property, not a nanoHost-specific one, and it's redundant to depend
    -- on nanoHost being enabled just to know which screen this is. It's
    -- now Screen_Id, sourced from the CAI CMD,RID response (see parseRID)
    -- alongside Model/Firmware Version -- confirmed in the eCNA-10 manual's
    -- own RID documentation (code 3 of the record is explicitly "Screen
    -- Id. Decimal number: 0 to 63"), not a guess. Always available,
    -- completely independent of Enable_NanoHost -- declared unconditionally
    -- near Model/Firmware Version above.
    -- v1.3.0.17: row number is now a real control (was static graphics
    -- text) specifically so it can be hidden along with everything else in
    -- a row that has no associated performance -- per Steve, "it would be a
    -- lot cleaner if all of the unused LEDs and boxes weren't there." Value
    -- is set once at startup (it never changes -- row 3 is always "3") and
    -- its IsInvisible is toggled together with the rest of the row.
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_RowNum", ControlType="Text", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule: row number (hidden along with the rest of the row when no performance is scheduled there)" })

    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_StartTime", ControlType="Text", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule: performance start date/time" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_RunTime",   ControlType="Text", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule: performance run time, minutes (as reported -- NOT MM:SS like the Stat/RunTim field above)" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_PerfNum",   ControlType="Text", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule: performance number" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_Sold",      ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule: ticket(s) sold for this performance (Green=1/Red=0)" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_Cancel",    ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule: performance cancelled (reverse logic: Green=0/not cancelled, Red=1/cancelled)" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_Title",     ControlType="Text", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule: title" })

    -- Row markers, matching the real page's own Key legend/colors exactly
    -- (confirmed via a real screenshot): First Show Start=pink, First Show
    -- End=lime, Show Start=cyan, Show End=yellow, Last Show Start=chocolate,
    -- Last Show End=orange. Per Steve's explanation: FS/LS mark which row is
    -- the day's first/last performance (pinned there until that specific
    -- show ends); FE/LE only light up while that specific (first/last) show
    -- is actually airing; Start/End are the generic "currently airing"
    -- pointer, independent of first/last. All six are independent and can
    -- overlap on the same row (confirmed: FS and FE both point at row 0 in
    -- the sample capture, shown as two separate colored cells at once) --
    -- so these stay as six separate indicators per row, not collapsed into
    -- one "priority" color.
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_FS",    ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule marker: First Show Start" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_FE",    ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule marker: First Show End" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_Start", ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule marker: Show Start (currently-airing performance)" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_End",   ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule marker: Show End (currently-airing performance)" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_LS",    ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule marker: Last Show Start" })
    table.insert(ctrls, { Name="NanoHost_Show_LE",    ControlType="Indicator", IndicatorType="Led", Count=MAX_SHOWS, UserPin=true, PinStyle="Output", Description="Show Schedule marker: Last Show End" })
  end

  return ctrls
end

-- ============================================================
-- PROPERTIES: User-configurable options shown in Q-SYS Designer
-- ============================================================
function GetProperties(props)
  local list = {
    { Name="Num_Macros",  Type="integer",  Min=0,   Max=50, Value=50 },
    { Name="Num_RDI",     Type="integer",  Min=0,   Max=5,  Value=5  },
    -- v1.2.0.14: renamed from Poll_Rate/Scrape_Rate (which were integer in
    -- v1.1) to avoid the same caching issue that hit the float->double fix
    -- -- Designer appears to cache a property's TYPE on an already-placed
    -- instance, requiring a full remove/re-add to pick up a type change on
    -- an EXISTING property name. A brand-new name has no stale type to
    -- conflict with, so existing installs should just gain this as a new
    -- property (with the old integer one quietly dropping off) without
    -- needing to be torn out and replaced -- at the cost of losing
    -- whatever custom rate they'd set, back to the default, once.
    -- v1.2.0.45: Poll_Interval REMOVED from Properties entirely -- its only
    -- real purpose (confirmed against the eCNA-10 manual, page 89, item 1)
    -- is keeping the CAI channel from being bumped by a second client after
    -- 60s idle, not a user-tunable responsiveness knob like Scrape/
    -- LightPoll_Interval. There's no legitimate reason for an installer to
    -- ever change it, so per Steve it now lives as a fixed internal
    -- constant (POLL_RATE, see below) instead of a Designer-exposed
    -- property. Any existing instance with a custom Poll_Interval value
    -- quietly drops it, same as the old integer Poll_Rate/Scrape_Rate
    -- properties did when renamed in v1.2.0.14 above.
    { Name="Scrape_Interval", Type="double",  Min=0.5,   Max=20, Value=2  },
    -- v1.2.0.41: decouples the dimmer LIGHTPOLL (/rtLights.xml) from
    -- Scrape_Interval. Previously LIGHTPOLL consumed every OTHER routine
    -- turn no matter how low Scrape_Interval was set -- so lowering
    -- Scrape_Interval alone never actually sped up real scrape cadence, it
    -- just meant scrape and lightpoll got faster together (real
    -- scrape-to-scrape gap stayed ~2x whatever the "turn" cost was). Now
    -- LIGHTPOLL runs on its own slower cadence and Scrape_Interval controls
    -- real scrape cadence directly. Default of 3s (rounds to the same 1:1
    -- alternation as before at the default Scrape_Interval of 2s, so
    -- out-of-the-box behavior is unchanged) -- field-tested by Steve at a
    -- range of Scrape_Interval values down to 0.5s with no issues; a
    -- LightPoll_Interval of 3 (vs. the field-tested default Scrape_Interval
    -- of 2) noticeably improved offset-change responsiveness over the
    -- initial 4s figure. Meter animation between real polls already masks
    -- the slower dimmer refresh (per Steve: "we're already 'faking' the
    -- dimmer meters with our animation"), so LIGHTPOLL doesn't need to be
    -- nearly as frequent as scrape once they're no longer forced to share a
    -- turn 1:1.
    -- v1.2.0.45: Max reduced from 60 to 20, same reasoning as
    -- Scrape_Interval above -- no legitimate reason to run slower than
    -- that; higher values were only ever useful for testing/comparison.
    { Name="LightPoll_Interval", Type="double", Min=0.5, Max=20, Value=3 },
    { Name="Enable_QDC_Lighting", Type="boolean",  Value=false },
    -- QDC_Zones/QDC_Channels are always shown (not conditionally hidden behind
    -- Enable_QDC_Lighting) since Q-SYS Designer doesn't reliably redraw the
    -- properties dialog when the property SET changes reactively. They only
    -- take effect once Enable_QDC_Lighting=Yes.
    -- v1.2.0.47: Min relaxed from 2 to 1. Zone 1/2 are fixed by the eCNA as
    -- "House"/"Stage", but that's just how the device names them -- nothing
    -- requires an installation to actually use both. A single-zone site
    -- (House only) can now be configured that way instead of always
    -- carrying an unused Stage row. (This was previously untested at 1 --
    -- a real Q-SYS quirk around single-count controls made it silently
    -- broken; that's fixed in this same build, see the runtime comment
    -- near qdcZones/qdcChannels.)
    { Name="QDC_Zones",    Type="integer", Min=1, Max=16, Value=2 },
    { Name="QDC_Channels", Type="integer", Min=1, Max=16, Value=2 },
    -- v1.3: reveals the NanoHost page (appended after Program) and adds it
    -- to the HTTP poll rotation. No dependent sub-properties, so (unlike
    -- QDC_Zones/QDC_Channels) there's no "always visible" requirement here.
    { Name="Enable_NanoHost", Type="boolean", Value=false },
  }
  return list
end

function RectifyProperties(props)
  if props["QDC_Zones"] then
    local v = props["QDC_Zones"].Value
    if     v < 1  then props["QDC_Zones"].Value = 1
    elseif v > 16 then props["QDC_Zones"].Value = 16 end
  end
  if props["QDC_Channels"] then
    local v = props["QDC_Channels"].Value
    if     v < 1  then props["QDC_Channels"].Value = 1
    elseif v > 16 then props["QDC_Channels"].Value = 16 end
  end
  return props
end

-- ============================================================
-- PAGES: Tabs shown in the plugin UI
-- Macros and RDI tabs hidden if count is 0
-- Debug tab hidden unless Show_Debug property is true
-- ============================================================
function GetPages(props)
  local pages = {}
  for _, name in ipairs(buildPageList(props)) do
    table.insert(pages, { name = name })
  end
  return pages
end

-- ============================================================
-- LAYOUT: Per-page UI layout
-- Q-SYS calls this function once per page switch (driven by
-- the auto-injected page_index property). Only the current
-- page's controls and graphics are emitted.
-- ============================================================
function GetControlLayout(props)
  local layout   = {}
  local graphics = {}
  local pages    = buildPageList(props)
  local CurrentPage = pages[props["page_index"].Value]
  local numMacros = props["Num_Macros"] and props["Num_Macros"].Value or 50
  local numRDI    = props["Num_RDI"]    and props["Num_RDI"].Value    or 5
  local enableQDC, qZones, qChannels = qdcConfig(props)

  local LX  = 10    -- left margin
  -- v1.2.0.41: widened from 540 to fit the new Offset step (-/+) buttons on
  -- the Dimmer Control page, to the right of the Offset % text readout.
  -- Shared across all pages for a consistent look (widens header bars/
  -- warning-text wrapping slightly elsewhere too, but doesn't move or
  -- rearrange any other page's actual controls, which are all positioned
  -- at fixed offsets from LX).
  local W   = 630   -- page width
  local FX  = 130   -- field/control start x

  -- Section header (horizontal rule with centred text)
  local function hdr(y, text, size)
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Header", Text=text, Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, size or 16} })
  end
  -- Right-aligned label (used for row labels left of controls)
  local function lbl(x, y, w, text, size)
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label", Text=text, Position={x, y}, Size={w, size or 18},
      HTextAlign="Right", FontSize=size and math.floor(size*0.75) or 12 })
  end
  -- Left-aligned small label (used for button labels, column headers)
  local function textlbl(x, y, w, text, size, align)
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label", Text=text, Position={x, y}, Size={w, size or 14},
      HTextAlign=align or "Left", FontSize=size and math.floor(size*0.75) or 11 })
  end
  -- v1.2.0.48 BUG FIX: a control declared with Count=1 is NOT an array on
  -- the Q-SYS side -- its layout key must be the bare control Name, with no
  -- " 1" suffix (confirmed against QSC's own "Building a Plugin" debug-pin
  -- example: Count=1 paired with layout["code"], never layout["code 1"]).
  -- Every layout[Name.." "..i] built below for a control whose real Count
  -- can be exactly 1 -- Zone_Name/Zone_Offset*/Channel_* (QDC_Zones and
  -- QDC_Channels both now allow 1, see GetProperties) and Macros (Num_Macros
  -- allows 0-50) -- has to go through this helper instead of building the
  -- suffixed key directly, or the layout entry silently matches no real
  -- control and the whole row/element just never appears. Controls whose
  -- Count is always multiplied up to something >1 (Zone_Preset at
  -- qZones*5, RDI at numRDI*16) or is a fixed literal (House_Lights,
  -- Sound, Aux_Out, etc.) can never hit this and don't need it.
  local function layoutKey(name, count, idx)
    if count == 1 then return name else return name.." "..idx end
  end

  -- ================================================================
  -- SETUP TAB: Connection, device info, credits
  -- ================================================================
  if CurrentPage == "Setup" then
    local y = 8
    -- Eprad logo, centred
    table.insert(graphics, {
      Type     = "Image",
      Image    = "",
      Position = {(W-300)/2, y},
      Size     = {300, 64}
    })
    y = y + 74

    hdr(y, 'Connection', 18)
    y = y + 24
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'IP Address:', 16)
    layout["IP_ADDRESS"] = { PrettyName="Setup~IP Address", Style="Text", Position={FX,y}, Size={220,22} }
    y = y + 28
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'TCP Port:', 16)
    layout["TCP_PORT"] = { PrettyName="Setup~TCP Port", Style="Text", Position={FX,y}, Size={80,22} }
    y = y + 28
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Status:', 16)
    layout["Status_LED"]        = { PrettyName="Setup~Status LED",  Style="Led",  IsReadOnly=true, Position={FX, y+5},    Size={14,14} }
    layout["Status"] = { PrettyName="Setup~Status",      Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={FX+20, y},   Size={238,22} }
    layout["Reconnect"]         = { PrettyName="Setup~Reconnect",   Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Momentary", Legend="Reconnect", Position={FX+264,y}, Size={88,22} }
    y = y + 36

    hdr(y, 'Device Info', 18)
    y = y + 24
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Model:', 16)
    layout["Model"]            = { PrettyName="Setup~Model",    Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={FX,y}, Size={180,22} }
    y = y + 28
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Firmware:', 16)
    layout["Firmware_Version"] = { PrettyName="Setup~Firmware", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={FX,y}, Size={180,22} }
    y = y + 28
    -- v1.3.0.22: Screen Id, from the same CAI RID response as Model/
    -- Firmware Version above (confirmed in the manual: the RID record's
    -- third code is explicitly "Screen Id") -- always shown, unconditional,
    -- no longer tied to Enable_NanoHost at all (that dependency was the
    -- whole reason for this change, per Steve).
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Screen Id:', 16)
    layout["Screen_Id"] = { PrettyName="Setup~Screen Id", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={FX,y}, Size={60,22} }
    y = y + 36

    hdr(y, 'Refresh Setup Data', 18)
    y = y + 22
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="Input/output names, zone names, dimmer level/fade settings, and QDC-400 board count are only fetched once, at connect. If any of these are changed at the eCNA (Setup pages) after that, use this to pick up the changes.",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 30}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 32
    layout["Refresh_Setup"] = { PrettyName="Setup~Refresh Setup Data", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger", Legend="Refresh Setup Data", Position={LX, y}, Size={150, 22} }
    y = y + 34

    hdr(y, 'Credits', 18)
    y = y + 24
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label", Text="\xc2\xa9 2026 By Jay Wyatt and Steve Guttag.  Built with Claude AI.",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 18}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=12 })
    y = y + 26
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="This plugin may be freely distributed. It is supplied as-is and without support. Use at your own risk.",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 16}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 18
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="There are no expressed or implied warranties. This plugin is not a product of Eprad.",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 16}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 24
    -- STG logo, centred below Credits
    table.insert(graphics, {
      Type     = "Image",
      Image    = "",
      Position = {(W-21)/2, y},
      Size     = {21, 50}
    })
    -- Version number, lower-right corner
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label", Text="Version "..PluginInfo.Version,
      Position={W-100, y+44}, Size={90, 14}, HTextAlign="Right", FontSize=9 })

  -- ================================================================
  -- OUTPUTS TAB: All eCNA outputs grouped by type
  -- Toggle buttons send OUT commands and reflect state from scrape
  -- ================================================================
  elseif CurrentPage == "Outputs" then
    local BW, BH, BS = 54, 26, 56   -- button width, height, stride
    local y = 10

    -- Digital Projectors (state from RST polling)
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Dig Proj1 Pwr:', 14)
    layout["Dig1_Power"] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Dig Proj1 Power", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Position={FX, y}, Size={60, BH} }
    y = y + BH+4
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Dig Proj1 Vid:', 14)
    layout["Dig1_Video"] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Dig Proj1 Video", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Position={FX, y}, Size={60, BH} }
    y = y + BH+4
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Dig Proj2 Pwr:', 14)
    layout["Dig2_Power"] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Dig Proj2 Power", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Position={FX, y}, Size={60, BH} }
    y = y + BH+4
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Dig Proj2 Vid:', 14)
    layout["Dig2_Video"] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Dig Proj2 Video", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Position={FX, y}, Size={60, BH} }
    y = y + BH+4
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Slide Projector:', 14)
    layout["Aux_Projector"] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Slide Projector", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Position={FX, y}, Size={60, BH} }
    y = y + BH+8

    -- House Lights (mutually exclusive, state from scrape)
    local HLLabels = {"None","Down","Mid1","Mid2","Up"}
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'House Lights:', 14)
    for i,txt in ipairs(HLLabels) do
      layout["House_Lights "..i] = { PrettyName="Outputs~House Lights/"..txt, Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Legend=txt, Position={FX+(i-1)*BS, y}, Size={BW, BH} }
    end
    y = y + BH+4

    -- Stage Lights
    local SLLabels = {"None","Down","Up"}
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Stage Lights:', 14)
    for i,txt in ipairs(SLLabels) do
      layout["Stage_Lights "..i] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Stage Lights/"..txt, Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Legend=txt, Position={FX+(i-1)*BS, y}, Size={BW, BH} }
    end
    y = y + BH+4

    -- Curtain
    local CurtLabels = {"None","Close","Open"}
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Curtain:', 14)
    for i,txt in ipairs(CurtLabels) do
      layout["Curtain "..i] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Curtain/"..txt, Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Legend=txt, Position={FX+(i-1)*BS, y}, Size={BW, BH} }
    end
    y = y + BH+4

    -- Masking
    local MskLabels = {"None","Flat","Scope","Special"}
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Masking:', 14)
    for i,txt in ipairs(MskLabels) do
      layout["Masking "..i] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Masking/"..txt, Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Legend=txt, Position={FX+(i-1)*BS, y}, Size={BW, BH} }
    end
    y = y + BH+4

    -- Lens
    local LensLabels = {"None","Flat","Scope","Special"}
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Lens:', 14)
    for i,txt in ipairs(LensLabels) do
      layout["Lens "..i] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Lens/"..txt, Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Legend=txt, Position={FX+(i-1)*BS, y}, Size={BW, BH} }
    end
    y = y + BH+4

    -- Sound: row1 = None Aux1 Aux2 Dig1 Dig2, row2 = Mono NonSync SR SVA + Mute
    local SndLabels = {"None","Aux1","Aux2","Dig1","Dig2","Mono","NonSync","SR","SVA"}
    lbl(LX, y, 115, 'Sound:', 14)
    for i=1,5 do
      layout["Sound "..i] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Sound/"..SndLabels[i], Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Legend=SndLabels[i], Position={FX+(i-1)*BS, y}, Size={BW, BH} }
    end
    for i=6,9 do
      layout["Sound "..i] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Sound/"..SndLabels[i], Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Legend=SndLabels[i], Position={FX+(i-6)*BS, y+BH+4}, Size={BW, BH} }
    end
    layout["Mute"] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Mute", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Legend="Mute", Position={FX+4*BS, y+BH+4}, Size={BW, BH} }
    y = y + (BH+4)*2 + 8

    -- Aux Output Flags 1-16: 2 columns of 8
    -- Each entry: [Out N button] [user name text field]
    hdr(y, 'Aux Output Flags 1-16', 16)
    y = y + 22
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="Note: Names refer to Output Flag names as configured in the eCNA, not physical output names on any I/O board.",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 26}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 59
    local auxColW = math.floor((W-20)/2)  -- ~260px per column
    local auxBW   = 60                     -- button width
    local auxBH   = BH                     -- button height
    local auxRS   = 28                     -- row stride
    for i=1,16 do
      local col = math.floor((i-1)/8)      -- 0=left, 1=right
      local row = (i-1) % 8
      local bx  = LX + col*auxColW
      local by  = y + row*auxRS
      -- "Out N" label to the left of button
      textlbl(bx, by+4, 38, "Out "..i, 12, "Right")
      layout["Aux_Out "..i] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Aux Out "..i, Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Position={bx+42, by}, Size={auxBW, auxBH} }
      -- User name text field to the right of button
      layout["Out_Names "..i] = { PrettyName="Outputs~Aux Out "..i.." Name", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={bx+106, by}, Size={auxColW-110, auxBH} }
    end

  -- ================================================================
  -- DIMMER CONTROL TAB (v1.2): Eprad QDC-400 lighting monitor/control
  -- Replicates the eCNA's own Status: Light Control web page (manual §5.9)
  -- Only present when Enable_QDC_Lighting=Yes.
  -- Zone rows: name, 5 mutually-exclusive preset buttons, offset fader + text
  -- Channel bars: vertical level meter + % text + assigned zone name
  -- ================================================================
  elseif CurrentPage == "Dimmer Control" then
    local y = 10
    hdr(y, 'Zone Light Control', 18)
    y = y + 22

    -- QDC board count: label + narrow (single-digit, range is 0-4) box on
    -- the same line, positioned above the warning text so the two don't
    -- overlap.
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label", Text="QDC-400 boards found:", Position={LX, y+2}, Size={150, 16}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    layout["QDC_Board_Count"] = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~QDC Boards Found", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={LX+110, y}, Size={26, 20} }
    y = y + 26

    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="Warning: These controls cause action at the target device. Offset applies to all channels configured for that zone.",
      Position={LX, y-6}, Size={W-20, 28}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 41

    local presetLabels = {"Up","Down","Mid1","Mid2","None"}
    local zoneNameW = 90
    local presetBW  = 40
    local presetX   = LX + zoneNameW + 6
    local faderX    = presetX + 5*presetBW + 10
    local faderW    = 120
    local offTxtX   = faderX + faderW + 6
    local offTxtW   = 40
    local rowH      = 26
    -- v1.2.0.41: -/+ step buttons, placed to the right of the Offset % text
    -- readout (not beside the fader itself) with a deliberate gap -- so
    -- someone dragging the slider has no chance of also catching a step
    -- button by accident. Sized to match the preset buttons exactly
    -- (stepBW == presetBW) rather than a smaller custom width -- Q-SYS
    -- auto-fits a button's Legend text to its own size, so the "+"/"-"
    -- looking noticeably smaller than "Up"/"Down"/etc. was really just a
    -- side effect of the button itself being smaller, not a separate font
    -- setting to adjust.
    local stepBW    = presetBW
    local decX      = offTxtX + offTxtW + 10
    local incX      = decX + stepBW + 6

    -- Column headers (once, above the rows -- not repeated per row)
    textlbl(LX,      y-16, zoneNameW, "Zone", 12, "Center")
    textlbl(presetX + 2*presetBW, y-16, presetBW, "Preset", 12, "Center")  -- centered over the Mid1 button (button 3 of 5), the natural midpoint of the row
    textlbl(faderX,  y-16, faderW, "Offset %", 12, "Center")
    textlbl(decX,    y-16, incX+stepBW-decX, "Adjust", 12, "Center")  -- spans both step buttons

    for i = 1, qZones do
      layout[layoutKey("Zone_Name", qZones, i)] = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Zone "..i.." Name", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={LX, y}, Size={zoneNameW-4, rowH-4} }
      for b = 1, 5 do
        local idx = (i-1)*5 + b
        layout["Zone_Preset "..idx] = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Zone "..i.." "..presetLabels[b], Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Toggle", Legend=presetLabels[b], Position={presetX+(b-1)*presetBW, y}, Size={presetBW-2, rowH-4} }
      end
      -- Color must be an RGB table, not a string -- confirmed against a
      -- working reference plugin (DSS_Server) and verified on both
      -- Windows 10 and 11. Every earlier attempt here used a string
      -- ("blue", "Blue", a hex string), which was simply the wrong data
      -- type -- not a Designer-version quirk as previously suspected.
      layout[layoutKey("Zone_Offset", qZones, i)]      = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Zone "..i.." Offset",      Style="Fader", Orientation="Horizontal", Color={72,147,217}, Min=-100, Max=100, Position={faderX, y}, Size={faderW, rowH-4} }
      layout[layoutKey("Zone_Offset_Text", qZones, i)] = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Zone "..i.." Offset Text", Style="Text", Position={offTxtX, y}, Size={offTxtW, rowH-4} }
      -- ButtonStyle="Momentary" to match the Momentary ControlType declared
      -- in GetControls -- Legend is the standard universally-understood
      -- "-"/"+" glyph rather than text, since the one-time "Adjust" header
      -- above already establishes what these do.
      layout[layoutKey("Zone_Offset_Dec", qZones, i)] = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Zone "..i.." Offset Decrease", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Momentary", Legend="-", Position={decX, y}, Size={stepBW-2, rowH-4} }
      layout[layoutKey("Zone_Offset_Inc", qZones, i)] = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Zone "..i.." Offset Increase", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Momentary", Legend="+", Position={incX, y}, Size={stepBW-2, rowH-4} }
      y = y + rowH
    end
    y = y + 14

    hdr(y, 'Dimmer Channels', 18)
    y = y + 24
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="Channel output level (%). More than one channel may be assigned to the same zone.",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 16}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 22

    local chColW  = 56
    local barW    = 20
    local barH    = 90
    local perRow  = 8  -- fixed cap: a 16-channel system shows as two rows of 8
    local chBaseY = y
    for j = 1, qChannels do
      local col = (j-1) % perRow
      local row = math.floor((j-1)/perRow)
      local cx  = LX + col*chColW
      local cy  = chBaseY + row*(barH+56)
      textlbl(cx, cy, chColW-4, "Ch "..j, 12, "Center")
      -- Small LED in the corner: lit = this channel has confirmed a real,
      -- non-zero response at least once; dark = no confirmed dimmer yet,
      -- or 2+ consecutive unexpected 0% polls (see channelNoDimmer).
      layout[layoutKey("Channel_Present", qChannels, j)]    = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Channel "..j.." Present", Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color="green", Position={cx+chColW-14, cy}, Size={10,10} }
      -- Style="Meter" (not "Fader") for a non-interactive level-bar look.
      -- Color is an RGB table (not a string) -- see the Zone_Offset comment above.
      layout[layoutKey("Channel_Level", qChannels, j)]      = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Channel "..j.." Level",      Style="Meter", Orientation="Vertical", IsReadOnly=true, Color={0,210,0}, Min=0, Max=100, Position={cx + (chColW-barW)/2, cy+16}, Size={barW, barH} }
      layout[layoutKey("Channel_Level_Text", qChannels, j)] = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Channel "..j.." Level Text", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={cx, cy+16+barH+2}, Size={chColW-4, 16} }
      layout[layoutKey("Channel_Zone", qChannels, j)]       = { PrettyName="Dimmer Control~Channel "..j.." Zone",       Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={cx, cy+16+barH+20}, Size={chColW-4, 16} }
    end

  -- ================================================================
  -- INPUTS TAB: Web scrape input flags as LEDs with labels
  -- Two columns: In1-In16 on left, system inputs on right
  -- ================================================================
  elseif CurrentPage == "Inputs" then
    local y = 10
    local LED = 16   -- LED size
    local LS  = 22   -- row stride

    hdr(y, 'Input Flags', 20)
    y = y + 26
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="Note: Names below refer to Input Flag names as configured in the eCNA, not physical input names on any I/O board.",
      Position={LX, y-10}, Size={W-20, 32}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 38

    local col1 = {}   -- {index, name} for In1-In16
    local col2 = {}   -- {index, name} for system inputs
    local InFlagNames = {
      "Stop","Start","Dig1 Cue","Dig1 Fault","Dig1 Stop","Dig1 Start",
      "Dig2 Cue","Dig2 Fault","Dig2 Stop","Dig2 Start",
      "Bypass","Program Abort","Pause","In1","In2","In3","In4",
      "Fire Stop","In5","In6","In7","In8","In9","In10","In11","In12",
      "In13","In14","In15","In16","Cancel"
    }
    for i, name in ipairs(InFlagNames) do
      if name:sub(1,2) == "In" and tonumber(name:sub(3)) then
        table.insert(col1, {i, name})
      else
        table.insert(col2, {i, name})
      end
    end

    local colW = math.floor((W-20) / 2)

    -- Column headers sit 18px above the first row
    textlbl(LX,       y-20, colW, "General Inputs", 16)
    textlbl(LX+colW+80,  y-20, colW-80, "System Inputs",  16)

    -- Column 1: In1-In16 with user-defined name alongside
    -- In_Names[1..16] controls display the user name fetched from eCNA
    local y1 = y
    for idx, entry in ipairs(col1) do
      local inIdx = idx  -- In1=1, In2=2 ... In16=16
      layout["Inputs "..entry[1]] = { PrettyName="Inputs~"..entry[2], Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color="green", Position={LX, y1+3}, Size={LED, LED} }
      textlbl(LX+LED+6, y1+2, 36, entry[2], 16)
      layout["In_Names "..inIdx] = { PrettyName="Inputs~"..entry[2].." Name", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={LX+LED+46, y1}, Size={colW-LED-52, LS} }
      y1 = y1 + LS
    end

    -- Column 2: System inputs (shifted right with a visual gap from col1)
    local gap = 80   -- extra gap between columns
    local x2  = LX + colW + gap
    local col2W = W - x2 - 10
    local y2 = y
    for _, entry in ipairs(col2) do
      layout["Inputs "..entry[1]] = { PrettyName="Inputs~"..entry[2], Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color="green", Position={x2, y2+3}, Size={LED, LED} }
      textlbl(x2+LED+6, y2+2, col2W-LED-6, entry[2], 16)
      y2 = y2 + LS
    end

  -- ================================================================
  -- MACROS TAB: Trigger buttons with text labels above (no legends)
  -- ================================================================
  elseif CurrentPage == "Macros" then
    local y = 10
    hdr(y, 'Macros', 18)
    y = y + 24
    local cols  = 10
    local bw    = math.floor((W-20) / cols) - 2
    local bh    = 24
    for i = 1, numMacros do
      local col = (i-1) % cols
      local row = math.floor((i-1) / cols)
      local bx  = LX + col*(bw+2)
      local by  = y + row*42
      -- Text label centred above button, no legend on button itself
      textlbl(bx, by, bw+2, "Macro "..i, 14, "Center")
      layout[layoutKey("Macros", numMacros, i)] = { PrettyName="Macros~Macro "..i, Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger", Position={bx, by+16}, Size={bw, bh} }
    end

  -- ================================================================
  -- RDI TAB: 5 devices x 16 commands, text labels above Trigger buttons
  -- ================================================================
  elseif CurrentPage == "RDI" then
    local y = 10
    local bw     = 54
    local bh     = 24
    local stride = 56
    for dev = 1, numRDI do
      hdr(y, 'RDI '..dev, 18)
      y = y + 22
      for cmd = 1, 16 do
        local col = (cmd-1) % 8
        local row = math.floor((cmd-1) / 8)
        local idx = (dev-1)*16 + cmd
        local bx  = LX + col*stride
        local by  = y + row*42
        -- Text label: 'RDI N-N' centred above button
        textlbl(bx, by, bw, "RDI "..dev.."-"..cmd, 14, "Center")
        layout["RDI "..idx] = { PrettyName="RDI~RDI "..dev.." Cmd "..cmd, Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger", Position={bx, by+16}, Size={bw, bh} }
      end
      y = y + 2*42 + 8
    end

  -- ================================================================
  -- PROGRAM TAB: Transport controls, program selection, run state
  -- ================================================================
  elseif CurrentPage == "Program" then
    local y = 10
    local BH2 = 30   -- taller buttons for program controls

    hdr(y, 'Transport', 18)
    y = y + 26
    layout["Cmd_Start"]        = { PrettyName="Program~Start",        Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger",   Legend="Start",        Position={LX,    y}, Size={84,BH2} }
    layout["Cmd_Stop"]         = { PrettyName="Program~Stop",         Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger",   Legend="Stop",         Position={LX+88, y}, Size={84,BH2} }
    layout["Cmd_Cue"]          = { PrettyName="Program~Cue",          Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger",   Legend="Cue",          Position={LX+176,y}, Size={84,BH2} }
    layout["Cmd_Abort"]        = { PrettyName="Program~Abort",        Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger",   Legend="Abort",        Position={LX+264,y}, Size={84,BH2} }
    y = y + BH2+6
    layout["Cmd_Fault"]        = { PrettyName="Program~Set Fault",    Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger",   Legend="Set Fault",    Position={LX,    y}, Size={94,BH2} }
    layout["Cmd_Clear_Fault"]  = { PrettyName="Program~Clear Fault",  Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger",   Legend="Clear Fault",  Position={LX+98, y}, Size={94,BH2} }
    layout["Cmd_Reset"]        = { PrettyName="Program~Reset Fault",  Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger",   Legend="Reset Fault",  Position={LX+196,y}, Size={94,BH2} }
    layout["Cmd_Cancel_Alarm"] = { PrettyName="Program~Cancel Alarm", Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger",   Legend="Cancel Alarm", Position={LX+294,y}, Size={108,BH2} }
    y = y + BH2+10

    hdr(y, 'Program Selection', 18)
    y = y + 26
    lbl(LX, y, 120, 'Program #:', 16)
    layout["Set_Program"]      = { PrettyName="Program~Set Program",  Style="ComboBox", Position={FX+5,y}, Size={120,22} }
    layout["Cmd_Set_Program"]  = { PrettyName="Program~Set Prog",     Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger", Legend="Set Prog",  Position={FX+130,y}, Size={80,22} }
    layout["Cmd_Set_And_Run"]  = { PrettyName="Program~Set and Run",  Style="Button", ButtonStyle="Trigger", Legend="Set & Run", Position={FX+214,y}, Size={88,22} }
    y = y + 36

    hdr(y, 'Run State', 18)
    y = y + 26
    local stateRows = {
      {"Control_State",  "Control State"},
      {"Stopped_State",  "Stopped State"},
      {"Cue_Number",     "Cue Number"},
      {"Program_Number", "Program Number"},
      {"Segment_Name",   "Segment Name"},
      {"Segment_Index",  "Segment Index"},
      {"CAI_CMD_Access", "CMD Access"},
    }
    for _, row in ipairs(stateRows) do
      lbl(LX, y, 120, row[2]..':', 16)
      layout[row[1]] = { PrettyName="Program~"..row[2], Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={FX+5,y}, Size={190,22} }
      y = y + 28
    end

  -- ================================================================
  -- NANOHOST TAB: v1.3, informational only, appended after Program.
  -- Upper section (this build): Show Timers (left) + Status Flags (right),
  -- side by side, recreating (to a degree) the real nanoHost web page's own
  -- "Control Data" table layout. Lower section (shows schedule, variable
  -- row count) is NOT implemented yet -- pending a real field sample; see
  -- header comment and design notes.
  -- ================================================================
  elseif CurrentPage == "NanoHost" then
    local y = 10
    -- v1.3.0.17: instructions paragraph removed entirely per Steve ("The
    -- Text above 'Status' can be removed... and the space reclaimed").

    -- v1.3.0.9: Show Timers (left) and Status Flags (right) combined into
    -- one side-by-side section, per Steve, to recreate (to a degree) the
    -- real nanoHost web page's own "Control Data" table layout (Name/MM:SS
    -- paired with Name/Flag columns -- see manual Sec. 5.10 / the eCNA-5
    -- reference capture). Status Flags moved to the right with the LEDs to
    -- the right of their labels (reversed from the old left-LED layout) --
    -- LED_X is a single fixed x for every flag row, so all six LEDs land in
    -- one vertical column regardless of label text length, same principle
    -- as the timers column's fields already lining up via a fixed FX.
    hdr(y, 'Status', 18)
    y = y + 24

    -- Column geometry, named so the header-centering math below always
    -- matches the actual row layout, rather than duplicated magic numbers.
    local TLX = LX - 5      -- timer label box start x (v1.3.0.10: shifted 5px
                             -- left of LX -- label box was 170 wide starting
                             -- at LX=10, right edge=180, which is 5px PAST
                             -- the field's start at FX+45=175; this closes
                             -- that overlap instead of crowding the field)
    local TLW = 170          -- timer label box width
    local TFX = FX + 45      -- timer field start x
    local TFW = 100          -- timer field width (v1.3.0.10: widened from 80
                             -- -- 80 was too narrow for values like a full
                             -- date+time Time-of-Day string)
    local RLX = 340          -- flag label box start x
    local RLW = 150          -- flag label box width
    local LED = 14
    local LED_X = RLX + RLW + 10  -- fixed x for every LED -- vertical alignment

    -- Column headers: bold + black for stronger visual differentiation from
    -- the row labels below them (v1.3.0.11 -- textlbl()'s regular-weight
    -- style wasn't standing out enough), and centered so the MIDDLE of the
    -- header text sits on the demising line between each column's labels
    -- and its value element (field start x=TFX for Show Timers, LED start
    -- x=LED_X for Status Flags) -- not centered over the column's full
    -- span as in 1.3.0.10. Built directly rather than via textlbl(), which
    -- has no TextColor/IsBold parameters and is shared by many regular-
    -- weight labels elsewhere in the file that shouldn't be affected.
    --
    -- v1.3.0.21: FontStyle="Bold" confirmed to do NOTHING on this Label
    -- type (Steve reported no visible weight change) -- removed. IsBold
    -- confirmed working via the real Q-SYS SDK schema -- added in its
    -- place. FontSize kept at 13 (unchanged from 1.3.0.17).
    local HDR_W = 180
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label", Text="Show Timers",
      Position={TFX - HDR_W/2, y}, Size={HDR_W, 18},
      HTextAlign="Center", FontSize=13, IsBold=true, TextColor={0,0,0} })
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label", Text="Status Flags",
      Position={LED_X - HDR_W/2, y}, Size={HDR_W, 18},
      HTextAlign="Center", FontSize=13, IsBold=true, TextColor={0,0,0} })
    y = y + 22

    -- v1.3.0.26: label text updated per Steve -- control NAMES unchanged
    -- (NanoHost_TimeOfShow etc.), so any existing pin wiring is unaffected;
    -- only the on-screen labels/PrettyNames change.
    local timerRows = {
      {"NanoHost_TimeOfDay",        "Time of Day"},
      {"NanoHost_TimeOfShow",       "Feature Run Time"},
      {"NanoHost_TimeBetweenShows", "Time Between Features"},
      {"NanoHost_TimeBeforeStart",  "Time Before Feature Start"},
      {"NanoHost_TimeAfterStart",   "Time After Feature Start"},
      {"NanoHost_TimeBeforeEnd",    "Time Before Feature End"},
      {"NanoHost_TimeAfterEnd",     "Time After Feature End"},
    }
    local flagRows = {
      {"NanoHost_TicketSold", "POS Ticket Sold"},
      {"NanoHost_InShow",     "POS In Show"},
      {"NanoHost_PosOk",      "POS Ok"},
      {"NanoHost_PosEnabled", "POS Enabled"},
      {"NanoHost_HostUp",     "nanoHost Up"},
      {"NanoHost_Cancel",     "POS Cancel"},
    }
    local rowH = 26  -- shared row height -- keeps both columns on the same grid

    for i, row in ipairs(timerRows) do
      local ry = y + (i-1)*rowH
      lbl(TLX, ry, TLW, row[2]..':', 16)
      layout[row[1]] = { PrettyName="NanoHost~"..row[2], Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={TFX, ry}, Size={TFW,22} }
    end

    for i, row in ipairs(flagRows) do

      local ry = y + (i-1)*rowH
      -- Label right-aligned so it "meets" the fixed-position LED cleanly,
      -- same principle as the timer labels meeting their fields at FX+45.
      lbl(RLX, ry, RLW, row[2]..':', 16)
      -- Color set at runtime (green/red, reversed for Cancel) -- see
      -- setNanoFlag()/setNanoFlagRev() in the runtime section. "green" here
      -- is just the initial/default layout-time color before first poll.
      layout[row[1]] = { PrettyName="NanoHost~"..row[2], Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color="green", Position={LED_X, ry+3}, Size={LED,LED} }
    end

    -- Advance past whichever column is taller (7 timer rows vs 6 flag rows).
    y = y + math.max(#timerRows, #flagRows) * rowH + 10

    hdr(y, 'Show Schedule', 18)
    y = y + 22

    -- Column x positions -- v1.3.0.15: Start/End highlight LEDs moved out of
    -- the small marker cluster (which now holds only FS/FE/LS/LE) and repositioned
    -- immediately adjacent to StartTime/RunTime respectively -- per Steve,
    -- these two specifically represent "this is the currently-airing
    -- performance," which on the real page is a background highlight on the
    -- StartTime/RunTime cells themselves (cyan/yellow), not a separate
    -- marker column. Same NanoHost_Show_Start/NanoHost_Show_End controls as
    -- before (just relocated + restyled), so no control/pin renaming.
    local SNO_X    = LX
    local SFS_X    = SNO_X + 24
    local SFE_X    = SFS_X + 18
    local SLS_X    = SFE_X + 18
    local SLE_X    = SLS_X + 18
    local SSTARTHL_X = SLE_X + 22   -- Start highlight LED, immediately before StartTime
    local SST_X      = SSTARTHL_X + 16   -- StartTime
    local SENDHL_X   = SST_X + 130 + 2   -- End highlight LED, immediately before RunTime
    local SRT_X      = SENDHL_X + 16     -- RunTime
    local SPN_X    = SRT_X + 45    -- PerfNum
    local SPN_W    = 55            -- v1.3.0.16: widened from 35 -- "PerfNum" was clipped
    local SSOLD_X  = SPN_X + SPN_W -- Sold
    local SCAN_X   = SSOLD_X + 25  -- Cancel
    local STITLE_X = SCAN_X + 45   -- Title (v1.3.0.14: Cancel's header needs
                                    -- more room than the Sold/PerfNum columns
                                    -- -- was clipping "Cancel" at 25px wide)
    local SLED     = 12
    local SROWH    = 20
    -- v1.3.0.16: Sold/Cancel LEDs centered under their headers rather than
    -- left-aligned at the header box's start x.
    local SSOLD_LED_X = SSOLD_X + (25 - SLED) / 2
    local SCAN_LED_X  = SCAN_X  + (45 - SLED) / 2 - 4  -- v1.3.0.21: shifted 4px left per Steve, to better center under "Cancel"

    -- Column headers (FS/FE/LS/LE only -- Start/End highlights sit right
    -- next to StartTime/RunTime below, with no separate header needed since
    -- the highlight IS the cue, same as the real page).
    textlbl(SNO_X,    y, 20,  'No.',      12)
    textlbl(SFS_X,    y, 16,  'FS',       10)
    textlbl(SFE_X,    y, 16,  'FE',       10)
    textlbl(SLS_X,    y, 16,  'LS',       10)
    textlbl(SLE_X,    y, 16,  'LE',       10)
    textlbl(SST_X,    y, 130, 'StartTime',12)
    textlbl(SRT_X,    y, 45,  'RunTime',  12)
    textlbl(SPN_X,    y, SPN_W, 'PerfNum',  12)
    textlbl(SSOLD_X,  y, 25,  'Sold',     12)
    textlbl(SCAN_X,   y, 45,  'Cancel',   12)
    textlbl(STITLE_X, y, (W-20)-STITLE_X, 'Title', 12)
    y = y + 18

    -- v1.3.0.22: layout-time defaults now match each marker's own color
    -- (pink/lime/chocolate/orange) instead of a uniform green, consistent
    -- with the runtime off-color fix -- Boolean=false dims whatever Color
    -- is set, so this gives each marker its own dark shade from the very
    -- first render, before any poll has even landed. Same value TYPE
    -- (plain string) as everything else already confirmed safe -- no new
    -- risk vector, just a different string.
    --
    -- v1.3.0.23: FE's layout-time default changed from "lime" to "green" --
    -- these are pre-poll, i.e. inactive/off, states, and lime was confirmed
    -- to not read as dimmed the way green does (see setMarkerLed's comment).
    --
    -- v1.3.0.24: all four now use a uniform "darkgray" pre-poll default,
    -- matching the runtime off-color convention.
    --
    -- v1.3.0.25: switched to "dimgray" -- per Steve, and confirmed correct
    -- CSS-naming-wise: despite the names, "dimgray" (rgb 105,105,105) is
    -- actually darker/more muted than "darkgray" (rgb 169,169,169) -- same
    -- naming trap as lime being brighter than green.
    local MARKER_OFF_FS = "dimgray"
    local MARKER_OFF_FE = "dimgray"
    local MARKER_OFF_LS = "dimgray"
    local MARKER_OFF_LE = "dimgray"
    for i = 1, MAX_SHOWS do
      local ry = y + (i-1)*SROWH
      -- v1.3.0.16: row number vertically centered (+3, matching the LEDs'
      -- own vertical offset) instead of sitting at the row's top edge.
      -- v1.3.0.17: real control now (was static graphics) -- see
      -- GetControls comment; value set once at startup, IsInvisible toggled
      -- per-row at runtime along with everything else in the row.
      layout["NanoHost_Show_RowNum "..i] = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~Row Number", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={SNO_X, ry+3}, Size={20,16} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_FS "..i]    = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~First Show Start", Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color=MARKER_OFF_FS, Position={SFS_X, ry+3}, Size={SLED,SLED} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_FE "..i]    = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~First Show End",   Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color=MARKER_OFF_FE, Position={SFE_X, ry+3}, Size={SLED,SLED} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_LS "..i]    = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~Last Show Start",  Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color=MARKER_OFF_LS, Position={SLS_X, ry+3}, Size={SLED,SLED} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_LE "..i]    = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~Last Show End",    Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color=MARKER_OFF_LE, Position={SLE_X, ry+3}, Size={SLED,SLED} }
      -- Start/End highlight LEDs: default IsInvisible=true (hidden) until
      -- the runtime marks them active -- see setHighlightLed().
      layout["NanoHost_Show_Start "..i] = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~Show Start (Now Playing)", Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color="green", IsInvisible=true, Position={SSTARTHL_X, ry+3}, Size={SLED,SLED} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_End "..i]   = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~Show End (Now Playing)",   Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color="green", IsInvisible=true, Position={SENDHL_X, ry+3}, Size={SLED,SLED} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_StartTime "..i] = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~StartTime", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={SST_X, ry}, Size={130,18} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_RunTime "..i]   = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~RunTime",   Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={SRT_X, ry}, Size={40,18} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_PerfNum "..i]   = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~PerfNum",   Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={SPN_X, ry}, Size={40,18} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_Sold "..i]      = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~Sold",   Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color="green", Position={SSOLD_LED_X, ry+3}, Size={SLED,SLED} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_Cancel "..i]    = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~Cancel", Style="Led", IsReadOnly=true, Color="green", Position={SCAN_LED_X, ry+3}, Size={SLED,SLED} }
      layout["NanoHost_Show_Title "..i]     = { PrettyName="NanoHost~Show "..i.."~Title", Style="Text", IsReadOnly=true, Position={STITLE_X, ry}, Size={(W-20)-STITLE_X, 18} }
    end
    y = y + MAX_SHOWS * SROWH + 10

    hdr(y, 'Key', 14)
    y = y + 20
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="FS = First Show Start        FE = First Show End        LS = Last Show Start        LE = Last Show End",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 16}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 18
    -- v1.3.0.30: reformatted per Steve -- the Cyan LED explanation is one
    -- paragraph (both sentences), allowed to word-wrap within a single,
    -- taller Label rather than being split into two explicit lines (unlike
    -- the top instructions paragraph, where wrapping was avoided out of
    -- caution -- here Steve explicitly asked for wrapping, expecting it's
    -- likely needed given the combined length). NOT fully confirmed that
    -- this Label type wraps rather than clips long text -- worth checking
    -- once this is visible in Designer; if it clips instead of wrapping,
    -- this would need to go back to two explicit lines.
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="The Cyan LED and highlighted show indicate which is the active show. The \"POS Ticket Sold\" and \"POS In Show\" Status Flags refer to this show.",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 32}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 32
    y = y + 8  -- blank line -- paragraph break before the Yellow LED paragraph (v1.3.0.31: halved from 16 -- Steve reported it reading as roughly double the Key-header-to-Cyan-paragraph gap, which he confirmed was the right amount)
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="The Yellow LED and highlighted RunTime indicate that the show is in progress and past the posted showtime.",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 16}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 16
    y = y + 8  -- blank line -- paragraph break before the help-file sentence (v1.3.0.31: halved from 16, same reasoning)
    table.insert(graphics, { Type="Label",
      Text="For additional information, please see the help file.",
      Position={LX, y}, Size={W-20, 16}, HTextAlign="Left", FontSize=10 })
    y = y + 16
  end

  -- (The Debug tab that lived here -- Last TX/RX/Error text fields -- was
  -- removed entirely in v1.2.0.21. Everything it showed was already
  -- duplicated to the Q-SYS Debug window via dbg()/print(), which remains
  -- fully active; that's the actual troubleshooting tool in practice.)

  return layout, graphics
end

-- ============================================================
-- RUNTIME: Executes on Q-SYS Core when Controls table is available
-- All live device communication happens in this block
-- ============================================================
if Controls then

  -- ── Configuration ──────────────────────────────────────────
  local TCP_PORT    = 13002  -- default port; overridden by Setup page TCP Port field
  -- v1.2.0.45: no longer a user property (see GetProperties) -- fixed
  -- internal CAI keep-alive cadence. Manual-confirmed purpose (page 89,
  -- item 1): a CAI channel idle past 60s isn't itself dropped, but becomes
  -- vulnerable to being bumped if a second client tries to connect while
  -- it's idle. 45s keeps periodic traffic flowing with 15s of margin under
  -- that 60s window -- not something an installer has any reason to tune.
  local POLL_RATE   = 45
  -- Use property values; fall back to defaults if not set
  local SCRAPE_RATE = (Properties["Scrape_Interval"] and Properties["Scrape_Interval"].Value or 2)
  -- v1.2.0.41: dimmer LIGHTPOLL's own decoupled cadence (see GetProperties
  -- comment). lightPollEveryNTicks converts that into "every Nth routine
  -- turn" since the plugin only reasons in turns/ticks (no wall-clock query
  -- available), same style as meterTimer's fixed-step MTICK simulation
  -- elsewhere in this file. Rounds to the nearest whole tick, floored at 2.
  --
  -- v1.2.0.44 BUG FIX: this was floored at 1, not 2. Whenever LIGHTPOLL_RATE
  -- rounded down to exactly 1 tick (e.g. LightPoll_Interval=3 with
  -- Scrape_Interval anywhere above 2.0 up to 6.0 -- 3/2.1=1.43, rounds to
  -- 1), httpRequest()'s "routineTicks >= lightPollEveryNTicks" check was
  -- satisfied on EVERY single routine tick (routineTicks increments from 0
  -- to 1 before the check), so LIGHTPOLL won every turn and scrape NEVER
  -- ran at all -- confirmed via a field debug log showing 168 consecutive
  -- LIGHTPOLL requests, zero SCRAPE requests, and Status stuck on
  -- "Initializing" forever (populated.scrape can never become true, so
  -- checkFullyPopulated() can never succeed). Flooring at 2 guarantees
  -- scrape at least every-other-tick no matter how close the two intervals
  -- are -- the tightest quantization the single-connection/one-request-
  -- per-tick design can represent while still letting scrape run at all,
  -- consistent with scrape always being the higher-priority default action.
  local LIGHTPOLL_RATE = (Properties["LightPoll_Interval"] and Properties["LightPoll_Interval"].Value or 3)
  local lightPollEveryNTicks = math.max(2, math.floor(LIGHTPOLL_RATE / SCRAPE_RATE + 0.5))
  -- v1.3: nanoHost POS management data -- not a user property (see
  -- GetProperties comment on Enable_NanoHost) because there's no legitimate
  -- reason to tune this: Steve confirmed the nanoHost itself only updates
  -- what the eCNA reports at most every 5 minutes, so anything meaningfully
  -- faster than that just burns HTTP turns for stale data, and it's
  -- explicitly the lowest-priority poll in this plugin. Same "every Nth
  -- routine tick" conversion and floor-at-2 pattern as LIGHTPOLL_RATE above,
  -- for the same reason (guards against a starvation edge case if
  -- Scrape_Interval is ever set unusually high).
  --
  -- v1.3.0.32: changed from 150s (2.5 min) to 120s (2 min), per Steve.
  local NANO_POLL_RATE = 120
  local nanoPollEveryNTicks = math.max(2, math.floor(NANO_POLL_RATE / SCRAPE_RATE + 0.5))
  -- v1.2.0.4: periodic name auto-refresh removed entirely. Names (input,
  -- output, and dimmer zone/channel setup) are fetched once on connect and
  -- otherwise only via their manual Refresh buttons -- they essentially
  -- never change after commissioning, so spending any recurring poll slot
  -- on them was pure overhead competing with the flag scrape / light poll.
  local ENABLE_QDC   = Properties["Enable_QDC_Lighting"] and Properties["Enable_QDC_Lighting"].Value or false
  local qdcZones     = ENABLE_QDC and (Properties["QDC_Zones"]    and Properties["QDC_Zones"].Value    or 2) or 0
  local qdcChannels  = ENABLE_QDC and (Properties["QDC_Channels"] and Properties["QDC_Channels"].Value or 2) or 0
  -- v1.3: when off, nanoHost is fully out of the poll rotation (see
  -- httpRequest()'s priority chain below) per Steve's "remove its place on
  -- any polling scheme we develop" instruction -- not just hidden controls.
  local ENABLE_NANOHOST = Properties["Enable_NanoHost"] and Properties["Enable_NanoHost"].Value or false

  -- v1.2.0.47 BUG FIX: Q-SYS hands back a Count=1 control as the control
  -- itself (Controls.Foo), not a 1-element array (Controls.Foo[1] does not
  -- exist) -- every OTHER control declared with a variable Count only ever
  -- got exercised at Count>1 in this plugin, so this never surfaced until
  -- Steve found that QDC_Channels=1 (always allowed, Min=1) left every
  -- channel meter blank: every [j] index into Controls.Channel_Level etc.
  -- was silently indexing into the control object itself rather than an
  -- array, finding nothing there. QDC_Zones couldn't hit the same bug
  -- before this build only because its own Min was 2 -- see the
  -- GetProperties comment for why that's being relaxed to 1 in the same
  -- build. Normalizing here, once, up front, means every other place in
  -- this file that does Controls.Channel_Level[j] / Controls.Zone_Offset[i]
  -- / etc. keeps working exactly as written, regardless of whether the
  -- count is 1.
  local function normalizeSingleControl(name, count)
    if count == 1 and Controls[name] then
      Controls[name] = { Controls[name] }
    end
  end
  if ENABLE_QDC then
    normalizeSingleControl("Zone_Name",          qdcZones)
    normalizeSingleControl("Zone_Offset",        qdcZones)
    normalizeSingleControl("Zone_Offset_Text",   qdcZones)
    normalizeSingleControl("Zone_Offset_Inc",    qdcZones)
    normalizeSingleControl("Zone_Offset_Dec",    qdcZones)
    normalizeSingleControl("Channel_Level",      qdcChannels)
    normalizeSingleControl("Channel_Level_Text", qdcChannels)
    normalizeSingleControl("Channel_Zone",       qdcChannels)
    normalizeSingleControl("Channel_Present",    qdcChannels)
  end
  -- v1.2.0.48: same Count=1 gotcha, same fix -- Num_Macros allows 0-50, so
  -- a single-macro design is just as reachable as single-zone/single-
  -- channel. Without this, Controls.Macros at Num_Macros=1 would be the
  -- bare control rather than a 1-element array, and the
  -- "ipairs(Controls.Macros)" wiring loop below would silently iterate
  -- zero times -- the button would be visible (once the matching
  -- GetControlLayout key fix takes effect) but would never actually do
  -- anything when pressed.
  normalizeSingleControl("Macros", (Properties["Num_Macros"] and Properties["Num_Macros"].Value or 50))

  -- ── Flag name tables (used to initialise LED legends) ──────
  local InFlagNames = {
    "Stop","Start","Dig1 Cue","Dig1 Fault","Dig1 Stop","Dig1 Start",
    "Dig2 Cue","Dig2 Fault","Dig2 Stop","Dig2 Start",
    "Bypass","Program Abort","Pause","In1","In2","In3","In4",
    "Fire Stop","In5","In6","In7","In8","In9","In10","In11","In12",
    "In13","In14","In15","In16","Cancel"
  }

  -- ── State variables ────────────────────────────────────────
  local psn          = 0       -- Packet Sequence Number (0-65535, wraps)
  local nameQueue    = {}      -- queue of {pgIdx, applyFn} name fetch requests
  local currentReq   = nil     -- current httpSock request context (nil=scrape)
  local httpBusy     = false   -- true while a request is in-flight; prevents double-sends
  local applyInputNames  = nil -- forward declaration; defined after name tables
  local applyOutputNames = nil -- forward declaration; defined after name tables
  local httpSock         = nil -- forward declaration; assigned after httpSock section
  local sock         = TcpSocket.New()  -- CAI TCP connection (port 13002)
  local pollTimer    = Timer.New()      -- Fires RST poll at POLL_RATE seconds
  local reconnectTmr = Timer.New()      -- Fires reconnect attempt after disconnect
  local meterTimer   = nil              -- forward decl; assigned via Timer.New() below only if ENABLE_QDC. MUST live at this persistent scope, not inside "if ENABLE_QDC then" -- a Timer.New() declared as a `local` fully inside that block has no reference from outside it once the block finishes executing, and despite its EventHandler self-referencing it (a closure cycle), an object unreachable from any persistent root can still be garbage collected. That was very likely why the meter animation went choppy/stopped ticking in the field: the timer was probably being collected shortly after creation instead of running for the plugin's whole lifetime like pollTimer/reconnectTmr/scrapeTimer do.
  local nanoTickTimer = nil             -- v1.3: forward decl; same persistent-scope requirement as meterTimer above -- assigned via Timer.New() below only if ENABLE_NANOHOST.
  local rxBuf        = ""      -- Receive buffer for incoming CAI data
  local isConnected  = false   -- True when CAI TCP socket is connected
  local connecting        = false  -- true from the moment doConnect() actually calls sock:Connect() until Connected/Closed/Error resolves it; also used by the 10s failsafe below
  local connectingGen     = 0      -- bumped on every connect() call; debounces the whole disconnect-cooldown-reconnect sequence so rapid repeated calls collapse into one attempt (see connect()), and also invalidates a stale 10s failsafe timeout once a newer attempt has started
  local cooldownPending   = false  -- true from the moment a disconnect-then-reconnect cooldown is scheduled until doConnect() actually runs (whether it proceeds or stands down). Needed because between "we disconnected" and "we reconnect", isConnected and connecting are BOTH false -- without this, a second connect() call arriving in that window looks identical to "nothing in progress" and would skip the cooldown entirely.
  local intentionalDisconnect = false  -- true only for the brief window between connect()'s own deliberate sock:Disconnect() and the Closed event it causes; lets that event be correctly classified as expected teardown, not a fault
  -- v1.2.0.32: true from the moment we've reacted to an unexpected
  -- disconnect (Fault status set, reconnectTmr:Start(5) scheduled) until
  -- the NEXT connect() attempt actually begins (doConnect() calling
  -- sock:Connect()). Guards against a single failed connection attempt
  -- generating more than one terminal Closed/Reconnect/Error notification
  -- -- observed in the field against a genuinely unreachable IP: the raw
  -- socket layer can report failure more than once for what is, from our
  -- perspective, the same outstanding attempt (e.g. an initial low-level
  -- error followed later by a formal socket-closed notification). Without
  -- this guard, each of those redundant notifications re-logged Fault and
  -- restarted the 5s countdown from scratch, so the actual retry kept
  -- getting pushed further out and Status flapped Initializing/Disconnected
  -- unpredictably instead of retrying on a clean, predictable cadence.
  local reconnectScheduled = false

  -- ── QDC-400 Dimmer Lighting state (v1.2) ────────────────────
  -- Forward-declared per the scoping rule in DESIGN NOTES §4: anything
  -- referenced inside a closure defined earlier in this block (socket
  -- EventHandlers, Control EventHandlers) must be declared here first.
  local applyDimmerSetup = nil    -- forward decl; defined after zoneNames/channelZone tables
  local resetForNewTarget = nil  -- forward decl; defined once all state tables below exist. Clears every queued command and every learned assumption about the connected device -- called whenever IP_ADDRESS actually changes, so a command queued for one unit (e.g. while testing against an unreachable address) can never be flushed out and applied to a DIFFERENT unit once connectivity resumes.
  local applyLinNetwork  = nil    -- forward decl; defined near applyDimmerSetup. Parses /rtLin.xml (Status: Local I/O Network) to count active QDC-400 boards -- a structural "is there even a dimmer on the bus" signal, independent of per-channel level polling.
  local qdcBoardCount    = nil    -- nil = not yet checked; 0+ = active QDC-400 boards found on the LIN network at last check
  local queueLightCmd    = nil    -- forward decl; defined after lightCmdQueue setup
  local parseLights       = nil   -- forward decl; defined near scrape()
  local parseNanoHost     = nil   -- v1.3: forward decl; defined near parseLights/scrape()
  local lightCmdQueue     = {}    -- queue of {zone0based, state, level, fader}; max depth 4, mirrors eCNA's own CmdBuf
  local zoneNames         = {}    -- zoneNames[3..16] = user-defined zone name (House/Stage are fixed, not fetched)
  local channelZone       = {}    -- channelZone[1..qdcChannels] = 0-based rtLights.xml zone index, or -1 if unassigned
  local currentReqType    = "SCRAPE" -- "SCRAPE" | "LIGHTPOLL" | "NAME" | "LIGHTCMD" | "NANOHOST" -- routes the HTTP response to the right parser
  local currentApplyFn    = nil      -- used only when currentReqType == "NAME"
  -- v1.2.0.41 (see httpRequest() below): replaces the old lightsPollToggle.
  -- Scrape is now the default action on every routine turn; the dimmer
  -- LIGHTPOLL only steals a turn once its own decoupled interval elapses,
  -- tracked as a tick count (see routineTicks/lightPollEveryNTicks near
  -- httpRequest).

  -- Optimistic-UI masking (v1.2.0.2): while a user-initiated zone change is
  -- in flight, the eCNA's rtLights.xml poll can still echo back the OLD
  -- level for a cycle or two (single shared HTTP connection = latency).
  -- Without masking this makes the offset slider visibly crawl/overshoot
  -- toward the released position across several refreshes. Fix: once the
  -- user changes a zone, ignore polled updates for that zone's controls
  -- until the polled value matches what was requested, or 15s elapses
  -- (whichever comes first) -- then resume normal live updates.
  local beginOffsetPending = nil  -- forward decl; defined after queueLightCmd
  local beginPresetPending = nil  -- forward decl; defined after queueLightCmd
  local offsetPending = {}  -- offsetPending[zone] = true while masking Zone_Offset/_Text for that zone
  local offsetDebounceGen = {}  -- offsetDebounceGen[zone] = generation counter for the 1s fader-settle debounce
  local offsetTarget  = {}  -- offsetTarget[zone]  = offset value we're waiting to see echoed back
  local offsetGen      = {} -- offsetGen[zone]      = generation counter; invalidates stale 15s timeouts
  local presetPending  = {} -- presetPending[zone]  = true while masking Zone_Preset buttons for that zone
  local presetTarget   = {} -- presetTarget[zone]   = preset state (0-4) we're waiting to see echoed back
  local presetGen      = {} -- presetGen[zone]      = generation counter; invalidates stale 15s timeouts

  -- ── Local dimmer meter simulation (v1.2.0.4) ────────────────
  -- The shared HTTP connection can only poll rtLights.xml every couple of
  -- seconds, which is far slower than a real dimmer fade (e.g. Mid1->Up in
  -- 2.5s per the configured level/fade-time). Rather than have the meter
  -- visibly jump or lag, we animate it locally between polls using the
  -- actual configured Level%/Fade-time for the preset being transitioned
  -- to (fetched from Setup.xml PgIdx=13, manual §4.3.29/§4.3.19-21), then
  -- hand back control to the live poll once our own predicted ramp
  -- finishes -- "verify/correct" happens naturally at that point since
  -- parseLights() only trusts the local simulation while animating.
  local channelPresetLevel = {} -- channelPresetLevel[ch][0..3] = configured target level % for state Up/Down/Mid1/Mid2
  local channelPresetFade  = {} -- channelPresetFade[ch][0..3]  = configured fade-in seconds for that same preset (nil/0 = instant)
  local zoneCurrentPreset  = {} -- zoneCurrentPreset[zone] = last known preset state (0-4), used to combine with a later offset-only change
  local zoneLastOffset     = {} -- zoneLastOffset[zone] = last known confirmed offset value, used (alongside zoneCurrentPreset) to detect whether a poll update represents a genuine preset and/or offset change, so the two can be combined into one correct animation target instead of animating to the bare preset level first
  local zoneFastPreset     = {} -- zoneFastPreset[zone: 1 or 2 only] = last House/Stage state as derived from the fast CAI output flags; triggers early animation only, never used for offset math (see scrape())
  local channelAnimating   = {} -- channelAnimating[ch] = true while locally simulating (parseLights ignores live cact for this channel)
  local channelSimTarget   = {} -- channelSimTarget[ch] = level % the local simulation is ramping toward
  local channelSimRate     = {} -- channelSimRate[ch]   = %/second ramp rate (100 / configured fade seconds)
  -- v1.2.0.41: must be declared here (before parseLights, below) rather
  -- than alongside channelWaitZone/channelWaitKind further down -- parseLights
  -- references channelPendingUnmask directly, and it's defined earlier in
  -- the file than that later declaration block, so a `local` placed after
  -- it would silently resolve to a global inside parseLights instead of the
  -- intended upvalue. See the longer design comment near channelWaitZone.
  local channelInvolvesOffset = {} -- channelInvolvesOffset[ch] = true if this channel's current/most recent transition had a non-zero offset at either end
  local channelPendingUnmask  = {} -- channelPendingUnmask[ch] = true for exactly one parseLights pass: local ramp + zone flag(s) are done, but this next poll is still skipped; cleared (and channelAnimating unmasked) after that one pass
  local startChannelAnim   = nil -- forward decl; defined near queueLightCmd/parseLights
  local animatePresetChange = nil -- forward decl; defined near startChannelAnim (preset button transitions -- uses the preset's configured fade time)
  local animateOffsetChange = nil -- forward decl; defined near startChannelAnim (offset slider/text changes -- always OFFSET_FADE_SECONDS, regardless of active preset)

  -- ── Dimmer-presence detection (v1.2.0.7) ────────────────────
  -- Guards against the "meter ramps toward a computed target, poll shows
  -- real 0%, meter resets, ramps again, resets again" cycle when a channel
  -- has no physical dimmer connected (or it's unpowered) -- our LUT-based
  -- target is only ever a prediction, and if the real hardware never
  -- reports back anything but 0% while we expect otherwise, we should stop
  -- fighting it and just show the truth.
  local channelZeroStreak = {} -- channelZeroStreak[ch] = consecutive live polls reporting 0% while a non-zero level was expected
  local channelNoDimmer   = {} -- channelNoDimmer[ch]   = true once 2 such polls in a row are seen; cleared the instant any non-zero level is seen
  local channelConfirmed  = {} -- channelConfirmed[ch]  = true only once a genuine non-zero level has actually been observed; drives Channel_Present (starts unlit/unknown, not lit-by-default)

  -- IP address validator: rejects empty, 0.0.0.0, or malformed addresses
  local function isValidIP(ip)
    if not ip or #ip == 0 then return false end
    local a,b,c,d = ip:match("^(%d+)%.(%d+)%.(%d+)%.(%d+)$")
    if not a then return false end
    a,b,c,d = tonumber(a),tonumber(b),tonumber(c),tonumber(d)
    if a==0 and b==0 and c==0 and d==0 then return false end
    return (a<=255 and b<=255 and c<=255 and d<=255)
  end

  -- ── Debug helper: logs to Q-SYS debug window if Show_Debug is true ──
  -- Debug output: always prints to Q-SYS debug window when ShowDebug=true in PluginInfo
  local function dbg(msg)
    print('[eCNA] ' .. tostring(msg))
  end

  -- ── CAI Protocol helpers ────────────────────────────────────
  -- Compute CAI checksum: sum of all ASCII bytes in the prefix, mod 65536
  local function checksum(s)
    local sum = 0
    for i = 1, #s do sum = sum + string.byte(s, i) end
    return tostring(sum % 65536)
  end

  -- Increment and return the next Packet Sequence Number (wraps at 65535)
  local function nextPSN()
    psn = (psn + 1) % 65536
    return tostring(psn)
  end

  -- Build and send a CAI command: CMD,<body>,<checksum>\r\n
  local function sendCmd(body)
    local prefix = "CMD,"..body..","
    local msg    = prefix..checksum(prefix).."\r\n"
    dbg("TX: " .. msg:gsub("\r\n",""))
    if isConnected then
      sock:Write(msg)
    else
      dbg("Not connected - dropped: "..msg:gsub("\r\n",""))
    end
  end

  -- Split a comma-separated string into a table
  local function split(str, sep)
    local t = {}
    for field in str:gmatch("([^"..sep.."]*)"..sep.."?") do
      if field ~= "" then table.insert(t, field) end
    end
    return t
  end

  -- Set one button in a group active (lit), clear all others
  local function setExclusive(group, idx)
    for i, c in ipairs(group) do c.Boolean = (i == idx) end
  end

  -- ── Q-SYS Status indicator values ──────────────────────────
  -- Used for Status (text box) and Status_LED
  -- 0=OK(green) 1=Compromised(yellow) 2=Fault(red)
  -- 3=NotPresent(grey) 4=Missing(orange) 5=Initializing(blue)
  local STATUS_OK=0; local STATUS_FAULT=2
  local STATUS_MISSING=4; local STATUS_INITIALIZING=5

  -- Update both the status text box and the LED indicator
  local function setStatus(value, msg)
    Controls.Status.String = msg
    Controls.Status.Value  = value
    Controls.Status_LED.Value         = value
    dbg("Status: " .. msg)
  end

  -- Status only reaches "OK" once every data source has responded at least
  -- once since the current connection began -- not just the first RST.
  -- Seeing "OK" should mean everything on screen reflects a real response
  -- from the currently-connected unit, not just that the TCP/CAI handshake
  -- succeeded. QDC-specific sources are only required when lighting is
  -- enabled; a unit with zero physical dimmer boards still fully responds
  -- to Setup.xml PgIdx=13 and rtLin.xml (just with sparse/zero data), so
  -- this doesn't get stuck waiting for hardware that will never appear.
  local populated = {
    rid = false, rst = false, inNames = false, outNames = false,
    dimmerSetup = false, linScan = false, scrape = false, lightPoll = false,
    nanoHost = false,  -- v1.3: tracked for visibility/debug only, NOT part of checkFullyPopulated's gate -- see comment below.
  }
  local statusIsOK = false

  -- v1.3: nanoHost free-running timer extrapolation. Per Steve, the nanoHost
  -- only refreshes what the eCNA reports at most every 5 minutes and our own
  -- NANOHOST poll runs even slower than that (NANO_POLL_RATE) -- too coarse
  -- to display live-looking countdowns directly from poll data alone. So the
  -- four fields that behave as genuine live counters (BSTim/ASTim count down/
  -- up toward/from a show start; BETim/AETim do the same for a show end) are
  -- extrapolated locally, once per second, between polls -- corrected back
  -- to ground truth by each real poll. RunTim/BtwTim are NOT extrapolated --
  -- confirmed against two live captures of the same real showtime ~8 minutes
  -- apart that only BSTim had actually moved (119:06 vs our own 127:33
  -- moments earlier); RunTim/BtwTim were bit-for-bit identical in both, so
  -- those are configured/reported values, not live counters, and ticking
  -- them locally would be fabricating movement with no evidence it's real.
  --
  -- NANO_TIME_MAX (255:59, i.e. 255*60+59=15359 seconds) is the eCNA's own
  -- observed cap -- confirmed against real captures showing exactly this
  -- value for "Time Between Shows"/"Time After End" when not actively
  -- counting toward/from anything. Per Steve: "there should not be any time
  -- greater than that" -- the up-counters (ASTim/AETim) are clamped to this
  -- ceiling every tick so local extrapolation can never exceed what the
  -- real device itself would ever report.
  --
  -- Time of Day is NOT sourced from nanoHost/rtmandata.xml at all as of this
  -- build -- per Steve, it's awkward for it to sit stale for up to
  -- NANO_POLL_RATE seconds, so it's generated directly from the Q-SYS
  -- Core's own clock (os.date), ticked every second, completely independent
  -- of nanoHost connectivity/HostUp/nanoValid. This is a deliberate, isolated
  -- exception to this file's otherwise-consistent no-wall-clock-dependency
  -- convention (MTICK-style fixed-step timers elsewhere) -- justified here
  -- because the alternative (extrapolating a parsed date+time string with no
  -- os.* support) is far more fragile than just asking the Core what time it
  -- is. NOT yet field-verified that os.date/os.time are actually permitted
  -- in the Q-SYS plugin Lua sandbox -- worth confirming on real hardware.
  --
  -- Explicit anti-faking guards for the FOUR extrapolated timers (both
  -- required, per Steve's instruction) -- these do NOT apply to Time of Day,
  -- which is always live/self-generated regardless of nanoHost state:
  --   1) nanoValid stays false (timers stay blanked "--:--", nothing
  --      ticks) until the FIRST real poll response has actually landed --
  --      never extrapolate from a Text control's pre-poll default.
  --   2) Whenever the last-known NanoHost_HostUp flag is false, the timers
  --      are blanked and extrapolation stops immediately -- "any time the
  --      Host Up is not true, the Time counters are not true either." A
  --      later poll with HostUp true again re-seeds everything from fresh
  --      ground truth before ticking resumes.
  local nanoValid      = false  -- true once at least one real (non-UpToDate) poll has landed
  local nanoHostUp     = false  -- last known NanoHost_HostUp flag value; gates ticking/display validity
  local nanoBSSec      = 0      -- Time Before Start, seconds, counts down
  local nanoASSec      = 0      -- Time After Start, seconds, counts up
  local nanoBESec      = 0      -- Time Before End, seconds, counts down
  local nanoAESec      = 0      -- Time After End, seconds, counts up
  local NANO_TICK      = 1      -- seconds per local extrapolation tick
  local NANO_TIME_MAX  = 255*60 + 59  -- 15359s -- the eCNA's own observed time-field ceiling (255:59)

  local function checkFullyPopulated()
    if statusIsOK then return end
    if not (populated.rid and populated.rst and populated.inNames
        and populated.outNames and populated.scrape) then return end
    if ENABLE_QDC and not (populated.dimmerSetup and populated.linScan and populated.lightPoll) then
      return
    end
    statusIsOK = true
    setStatus(STATUS_OK, "OK")
  end
  -- v1.3 design decision: nanoHost data is deliberately NOT part of the
  -- Status=OK gate above, unlike QDC's dimmerSetup/linScan/lightPoll. It's
  -- purely informational (no action depends on it), and it's intentionally
  -- the slowest poll in the plugin (NANO_POLL_RATE=150s) -- gating overall
  -- Status on it would mean every fresh connect with Enable_NanoHost=Yes
  -- takes up to 2.5 minutes to reach "OK" even though everything else the
  -- plugin actually does is ready immediately. NanoHost_* controls simply
  -- hold their last-known (or blank) values until their own slow poll
  -- eventually lands. Flag for Steve to confirm/override if he'd rather it
  -- gate Status when enabled, for consistency with the QDC precedent.

  -- v1.2.0.32: split in two. CAI (RID/RST) and HTTP (names, dimmer setup,
  -- LIN scan, scrape, light poll) are independent channels/sockets --
  -- a hiccup on one doesn't mean the other's already-fresh data is now
  -- suspect. Previously a single resetPopulationTracking() wiped BOTH on
  -- every connect() call, including the CAI side's own automatic retries.
  -- Field-observed consequence: an eCNA still finishing its own boot
  -- rejects the first couple of CAI sessions with "Resource Unavailable"
  -- while its HTTP interface is already up and successfully answering --
  -- each rejected CAI attempt was discarding HTTP-side progress that had
  -- JUST succeeded moments earlier, forcing the full Setup.xml/rtLin.xml
  -- sequence to restart from scratch over the single shared HTTP
  -- connection every time, repeatedly, and pushing "OK" out by tens of
  -- seconds even though the unit had clearly been responding the whole
  -- time. Now a CAI-only reconnect (button, IP unchanged, automatic retry)
  -- only re-earns the CAI side; HTTP-side freshness only resets on an
  -- actual target change (resetForNewTarget, i.e. IP_ADDRESS changed --
  -- see below), since that's the only event that actually invalidates
  -- previously-fetched HTTP data. "OK" still requires every source fresh
  -- from ITS OWN channel's most recent (re)connection -- this only changes
  -- which events count as invalidating which half.
  local function resetCaiPopulationTracking()
    populated.rid = false; populated.rst = false
    statusIsOK = false
  end
  local function resetHttpPopulationTracking()
    populated.inNames = false; populated.outNames = false
    populated.dimmerSetup = false; populated.linScan = false
    populated.scrape = false; populated.lightPoll = false
    populated.nanoHost = false  -- v1.3
    statusIsOK = false
  end
  -- Full reset (both channels) -- used by resetForNewTarget() where the
  -- physical device itself may be entirely different.
  local function resetPopulationTracking()
    resetCaiPopulationTracking()
    resetHttpPopulationTracking()
  end

  -- v1.2.0.42/43 (Steve's design): three-tier trust model for the 4 Digital
  -- Projector buttons (Dig1_Power/Dig1_Video/Dig2_Power/Dig2_Video).
  -- DP1ON/DP1OFF/DV1ON/DV1OFF/DP2ON/DP2OFF/DV2ON/DV2OFF are the only output
  -- changes with a dedicated unsolicited RPT,EVT code (confirmed against
  -- the manual's full event list -- Slide/Aux Projector has none, so it
  -- stays scrape-only, untouched by all of this).
  --
  --   Tier 1 (fastest): the unsolicited RPT,EVT notification itself sets
  --   the button immediately, at face value -- see parseRPTEVT. No round
  --   trip at all; the event is the eCNA telling us what already happened.
  --
  --   Tier 2 (first backstop): parseRPTEVT already triggers a reactive RST
  --   re-poll ~0.2s after the event; its response's D1P/D1V/D2P/D2V output-
  --   status fields (previously discarded entirely) now also set these 4
  --   buttons directly -- see parseStatusRecord below -- confirming/
  --   correcting Tier 1's guess almost immediately.
  --
  --   Tier 3 (second backstop): per Steve, "I would tend to let Scrape
  --   'fix' a DV status if we get two consecutive scrapes that differ from
  --   what our state is showing." dpMismatch[1..4] tracks a per-button
  --   streak of consecutive scrapes that disagree with the current value;
  --   a single differing scrape is treated as a possible stale/
  --   transitional read and ignored, but two in a row overrides (see
  --   scrape() below). Both Tier 1 and Tier 2 reset the relevant counter to
  --   0, since a fresh assertion makes any prior streak against the OLD
  --   value no longer meaningful.
  --
  -- Declared here (not down near scrape() where it's also used) because
  -- parseStatusRecord is defined earlier in the file and references it as
  -- an upvalue -- same rule as channelAnimating/channelPendingUnmask above.
  local dpMismatch = {0, 0, 0, 0}  -- [1]=Dig1_Power [2]=Dig1_Video [3]=Dig2_Power [4]=Dig2_Video

  -- ── RST Response Parser ─────────────────────────────────────
  -- Parses the RSP,RST response which contains full device state
  local function parseStatusRecord(fields)
    if #fields < 6 or fields[4] ~= "0" then
      if fields[4] and fields[4] ~= "0" then
        dbg("RST error: " .. fields[4])
      end
      return
    end
    local f = fields
    Controls.Control_State.String    = f[6]  or ""
    Controls.Stopped_State.String    = f[7]  or ""
    Controls.Cue_Number.String       = f[8]  or ""
    -- v1.2.0.42: RST's own Digital Projector Power/Video OUTPUT STATUS
    -- fields (codes 6/8/10/12 of the status record -- the "actual" state,
    -- not the "desired" control-flag field right before each) -- comma
    -- positions f[10]/f[12]/f[14]/f[16]. Guarded on record length since
    -- these sit well past the minimum-6 check above. Any RST response
    -- (periodic, reactive, or the one-time post-connect poll) authoritatively
    -- sets these 4 -- see scrape() for the mismatch-correction backstop.
    if #f >= 16 then
      Controls.Dig1_Power.Boolean = (f[10] == "D1P")
      Controls.Dig1_Video.Boolean = (f[12] == "D1V")
      Controls.Dig2_Power.Boolean = (f[14] == "D2P")
      Controls.Dig2_Video.Boolean = (f[16] == "D2V")
      dpMismatch[1] = 0; dpMismatch[2] = 0; dpMismatch[3] = 0; dpMismatch[4] = 0
    end
    -- Note: Aux_Projector (Slide Projector, "SLD" on this hardware rather
    -- than the manual's documented "AUX") has no unsolicited RPT,EVT of its
    -- own, so RST offers no faster path for it than scrape -- it stays
    -- scrape-only (flag 19), unaffected by this change.
    -- Program/segment info
    Controls.Segment_Index.String    = f[29] or ""
    Controls.Segment_Name.String     = f[30] or ""
    Controls.CAI_CMD_Access.String   = f[31] or ""
    Controls.Program_Number.String   = f[32] or ""
    populated.rst = true
    checkFullyPopulated()
    dbg("RST: state=" .. (f[6] or "") .. " seg=" .. (f[30] or ""))
  end

  -- ── RID Response Parser ─────────────────────────────────────
  -- Parses the RSP,RID response containing model, firmware version, and
  -- (v1.3.0.22) Screen Id. Manual confirms all three are the record's three
  -- codes in this exact order (code1=Device Name, code2=Software Version,
  -- code3=Screen Id) -- e.g. "RSP,RID,0,0,eCNA-10,1007,27,1630" has Screen
  -- Id "27" as field 7. The existing `#fields < 7` guard already ensures
  -- field 7 is present whenever this function actually processes a
  -- response, so no additional length check is needed for Screen Id.
  local function parseRID(fields)
    if #fields < 7 or fields[4] ~= "0" then return end
    Controls.Model.String = fields[5] or ""
    local ver = tonumber(fields[6])
    Controls.Firmware_Version.String = ver and string.format("%.3f", ver/1000) or (fields[6] or "")
    Controls.Screen_Id.String = fields[7] or ""
    populated.rid = true
    checkFullyPopulated()
    dbg("RID: model=" .. (fields[5] or "") .. " fw=" .. (fields[6] or "") .. " screen=" .. (fields[7] or ""))
  end

  -- ── Unsolicited Event Parser ────────────────────────────────
  -- Handles RPT,EVT messages sent by the eCNA without being polled
  -- Re-polls RST on state-changing events for immediate UI update
  --
  -- v1.2.0.43 (Steve's design): for the 4 Digital Projector buttons, trust
  -- the unsolicited event itself at face value the instant it arrives --
  -- "I would think we should take an unsolicited response at face value."
  -- This is as fast as it gets: no round trip at all, since the event is
  -- the eCNA telling us what already happened. The reactive RST re-poll
  -- below still fires exactly as before and is now the FIRST backstop
  -- (confirms/corrects within ~0.2-0.4s if the event turns out to have been
  -- stale or superseded); scrape's existing 2-consecutive-mismatch rule
  -- (see scrape()) remains the SECOND backstop. Resetting dpMismatch here
  -- too, same as parseStatusRecord -- a fresh face-value assertion is a new
  -- baseline, so any prior scrape-disagreement streak against the OLD value
  -- is no longer meaningful.
  local function parseRPTEVT(fields)
    local evt = fields[4] or ""
    dbg("RPT EVT: " .. evt)
    if     evt == "DP1ON"  then Controls.Dig1_Power.Boolean = true;  dpMismatch[1] = 0
    elseif evt == "DP1OFF" then Controls.Dig1_Power.Boolean = false; dpMismatch[1] = 0
    elseif evt == "DV1ON"  then Controls.Dig1_Video.Boolean = true;  dpMismatch[2] = 0
    elseif evt == "DV1OFF" then Controls.Dig1_Video.Boolean = false; dpMismatch[2] = 0
    elseif evt == "DP2ON"  then Controls.Dig2_Power.Boolean = true;  dpMismatch[3] = 0
    elseif evt == "DP2OFF" then Controls.Dig2_Power.Boolean = false; dpMismatch[3] = 0
    elseif evt == "DV2ON"  then Controls.Dig2_Video.Boolean = true;  dpMismatch[4] = 0
    elseif evt == "DV2OFF" then Controls.Dig2_Video.Boolean = false; dpMismatch[4] = 0
    end
    if evt=="START" or evt=="IDLE"    or evt=="ALLSTOP"
    or evt=="DP1ON" or evt=="DP1OFF"  or evt=="DV1ON"  or evt=="DV1OFF"
    or evt=="DP2ON" or evt=="DP2OFF"  or evt=="DV2ON"  or evt=="DV2OFF"
    or evt=="CUE"   or evt=="FIRESTOP" then
      Timer.CallAfter(function() sendCmd("RST,"..nextPSN()) end, 0.2)
    end
  end

  -- ── Incoming Line Processor ─────────────────────────────────
  -- Routes each complete CAI response line to the appropriate parser
  local function processLine(line)
    line = line:gsub("[\r\n]","")
    if #line == 0 then return end
    dbg("RX: " .. line)
    local f = split(line, ",")
    if #f < 2 then return end
    if f[1] == "RSP" then
      if     f[2] == "RST" or f[2] == "XST" then parseStatusRecord(f)
      elseif f[2] == "RID"                   then parseRID(f)
      elseif f[2] == "ERR"                   then
        dbg("ERR: " .. line)
      end
    elseif f[1] == "RPT" and f[2] == "EVT" then
      parseRPTEVT(f)
    end
  end

  -- ── CAI TCP Socket Handler ──────────────────────────────────
  -- Manages connection state and incoming data buffering
  sock.EventHandler = function(sock, evt, err)
    if evt == TcpSocket.Events.Connected then
      isConnected = true
      connecting  = false
      -- v1.2.0.33: the raw TCP handshake succeeding doesn't mean we have
      -- real, current data yet (RID/RST/names/etc. below still have to
      -- arrive) -- but it IS genuine progress, and worth showing as such.
      -- Previously Status could sit on a stale Fault message (e.g. "Connect
      -- timed out" from several failed automatic retries) right up until
      -- checkFullyPopulated() flipped it directly to "OK" -- looking like
      -- the plugin had been stuck the whole time it was actually already
      -- talking to the unit and pulling in real data. Guarded by
      -- `not statusIsOK` so a redundant/spurious Connected notification
      -- while already fully populated can't regress the display backwards.
      -- If we lose the connection again before reaching OK, the normal
      -- Closed/Error/Reconnect handling below (Fault + reconnectScheduled)
      -- takes over exactly as it already does -- nothing else needed to
      -- protect that case.
      if not statusIsOK then
        setStatus(STATUS_INITIALIZING, "Initializing")
      end
      -- Request device ID and enable unsolicited event reports
      sendCmd("RID,"..nextPSN())
      sendCmd("CFG,"..nextPSN()..",RPTON,N")
      -- Fetch both name pages (and dimmer setup, if QDC enabled) once on connect.
      Timer.CallAfter(function()
        table.insert(nameQueue, {"/Setup.xml?PgIdx=75", applyInputNames})   -- inputs
        table.insert(nameQueue, {"/Setup.xml?PgIdx=74", applyOutputNames})  -- outputs
        if ENABLE_QDC then
          table.insert(nameQueue, {"/Setup.xml?PgIdx=13", applyDimmerSetup})  -- QDC zone names + channel assignments
          table.insert(nameQueue, {"/rtLin.xml", applyLinNetwork})  -- confirm QDC-400 board(s) actually present on the LIN network
        end
        -- v1.3: per Steve, get the nanoHost's initial conditions in the same
        -- bootstrap burst as everything else while "Initializing", rather
        -- than waiting for the first slow NANOHOST poll tier turn (up to
        -- NANO_POLL_RATE seconds later). This is a ONE-TIME priority fetch --
        -- routine refresh after this still runs on its own much slower
        -- cadence via httpRequest()'s NANOHOST tier, unaffected by this.
        if ENABLE_NANOHOST then
          table.insert(nameQueue, {"/rtmandata.xml", parseNanoHost})
        end
        dbg("Queuing initial name fetches")
      end, 0.3)
      -- Short delay before first RST poll to let device settle
      Timer.CallAfter(function() sendCmd("RST,"..nextPSN()) end, 0.5)
      pollTimer:Start(POLL_RATE)
    elseif evt == TcpSocket.Events.Data then
      -- Accumulate data and process complete lines
      rxBuf = rxBuf .. sock:Read(sock.BufferLength)
      while true do
        local nl = rxBuf:find("\n")
        if not nl then break end
        local line = rxBuf:sub(1, nl)
        rxBuf = rxBuf:sub(nl+1)
        local ok, err = pcall(processLine, line)
        if not ok then
          dbg("Parse error: " .. tostring(err))
        end
      end
    elseif evt == TcpSocket.Events.Closed
        or evt == TcpSocket.Events.Reconnect
        or evt == TcpSocket.Events.Error then
      isConnected = false
      connecting  = false
      if intentionalDisconnect then
        -- This close is a direct result of connect()'s own sock:Disconnect()
        -- call, immediately followed by a fresh connection attempt for the
        -- same deliberate reconnect (manual button, IP change, or the
        -- automatic retry) -- not an unexpected fault. Don't flag Fault
        -- status or schedule a redundant 5s retry on top of the reconnect
        -- that's already happening.
        intentionalDisconnect = false
        dbg("Disconnected as part of our own reconnect -- not a fault")
      elseif reconnectScheduled then
        -- v1.2.0.32: we already reacted to a failure for this outstanding
        -- attempt (Fault logged, 5s retry already ticking) -- this is a
        -- redundant terminal notification for that SAME failure, not a
        -- fresh disconnect. Ignore it: re-logging Fault and restarting
        -- reconnectTmr here would just push the actual retry further out
        -- every time one of these arrives, which is exactly the
        -- Initializing/Disconnected/Disconnected flapping seen in the
        -- field against a genuinely unreachable IP.
        dbg("Redundant disconnect notification while a retry is already pending -- ignored")
      else
        reconnectScheduled = true
        setStatus(STATUS_FAULT, (err and err ~= "") and ("Disconnected: "..err) or "Disconnected")
        pollTimer:Stop()
        reconnectTmr:Start(5)  -- retry connection after 5 seconds
      end
    end
  end

  -- ── Timers ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
  -- RST poll: sends status request at POLL_RATE interval
  pollTimer.EventHandler = function()
    if isConnected then
      local ok, err = pcall(function() sendCmd("RST,"..nextPSN()) end)
      if not ok then dbg("Poll error: "..(err or "")) end
    end
  end

  -- ── Connect function ────────────────────────────────────────
  -- Initiates CAI TCP connection using current IP/port settings.
  --
  -- v1.2.0.26: clearing the old `connecting` guard the instant the raw TCP
  -- handshake completed (in the Connected handler) turned out to be too
  -- narrow a window. Field testing showed two Reconnect presses ~90ms
  -- apart: the first's TCP connect succeeded and immediately cleared the
  -- guard, so the second press wasn't blocked -- it disconnected the
  -- barely-established first connection and reconnected again, which the
  -- eCNA rejected with "Resource Unavailable" because it hadn't yet fully
  -- released the just-closed session. A generation counter debounces the
  -- entire sequence instead: every connect() call bumps it, a fresh
  -- attempt only actually fires after a short cooldown, and if a NEWER
  -- connect() call arrives during that cooldown, the older one silently
  -- stands down rather than racing it. Repeated rapid presses collapse
  -- into a single attempt, timed from the last press.
  -- v1.2.0.32: `isAutoRetry` distinguishes the automatic 5s-after-Fault
  -- retry (called only from reconnectTmr.EventHandler) from every other
  -- caller (initial startup, manual Reconnect button, IP change) -- all of
  -- which pass nothing, i.e. isAutoRetry=false. Previously every single
  -- call unconditionally flashed Status to "Initializing", including the
  -- 2nd/3rd/50th automatic retry against a target that's been Faulted the
  -- whole time -- misleadingly implying fresh progress on every cycle
  -- rather than "still failing, still retrying." An automatic retry now
  -- leaves Status showing whatever Fault/Missing state it already had
  -- (still fully updated the instant something actually responds, via the
  -- normal Connected/RST-populated path) -- "Initializing" is reserved for
  -- attempts the operator actually initiated or that are happening for the
  -- first time.
  local function connect(isAutoRetry)
    local ip   = Controls.IP_ADDRESS.String
    local port = tonumber(Controls.TCP_PORT.String)
    if not port or port < 1 then port = TCP_PORT end
    if not isValidIP(ip) then
      setStatus(STATUS_MISSING, ip and #ip > 0 and "Invalid IP address" or "Missing")
      return
    end

    connectingGen = connectingGen + 1
    local myGen = connectingGen
    -- v1.2.0.32: CAI-side only -- see resetCaiPopulationTracking's comment.
    -- A CAI reconnect (this function) doesn't invalidate already-fresh
    -- HTTP-side data; only resetForNewTarget() (an actual IP change) does.
    resetCaiPopulationTracking()
    if not isAutoRetry then
      setStatus(STATUS_INITIALIZING, "Initializing")
    end

    local function doConnect()
      cooldownPending = false
      if connectingGen ~= myGen then
        dbg("Superseded by a newer connect() request, standing down")
        return  -- a newer connect() call arrived during the cooldown -- let it own the attempt
      end
      rxBuf = ""
      connecting = true
      reconnectScheduled = false  -- a fresh attempt is actually starting now -- the NEXT terminal event (whichever it is) is new information, not a redundant echo of the last failure
      Timer.CallAfter(function()
        if connecting and connectingGen == myGen then
          -- v1.2.0.32: this used to only clear `connecting` -- which
          -- prevented the flag from wrongly blocking some FUTURE connect()
          -- call, but didn't itself do anything to actually retry. If the
          -- raw socket layer never delivers a terminal Closed/Error event
          -- at all for an unreachable address (the exact case this
          -- failsafe exists for), nothing was left to un-stick the plugin
          -- -- it would sit at "Initializing" indefinitely. Now treat a
          -- 10s non-resolution the same as an unexpected disconnect: flag
          -- Fault and schedule the normal 5s automatic retry, same path a
          -- real Closed/Error event would take. Guarded by
          -- `reconnectScheduled` like that path too, in case the real
          -- terminal event arrives at nearly the same moment.
          dbg("Connect attempt did not resolve within 10s, treating as failed")
          connecting = false
          isConnected = false
          if not reconnectScheduled then
            reconnectScheduled = true
            setStatus(STATUS_FAULT, "Connect timed out")
            pollTimer:Stop()
            reconnectTmr:Start(5)
          end
        end
      end, 10)
      sock:Connect(ip, port)
    end

    if isConnected or connecting or cooldownPending then
      intentionalDisconnect = true
      if isConnected or connecting then sock:Disconnect() end
      -- Give the eCNA a moment to fully release the old CAI session before
      -- asking for a new one, rather than reconnecting in the same tick.
      cooldownPending = true
      Timer.CallAfter(doConnect, 1.5)
    else
      doConnect()
    end
  end

  -- Reconnect: fires 5 seconds after disconnect, attempts new connection.
  -- Routed through connect() (rather than calling sock:Connect() directly,
  -- as before) so the automatic retry gets the same re-entrancy guard,
  -- population-tracking reset, and status handling as every other
  -- reconnect path -- there's only one place connection attempts start now.
  -- v1.2.0.32: passes isAutoRetry=true so Status keeps showing Fault/Missing
  -- through repeated automatic retries instead of flashing back to
  -- "Initializing" every 5 seconds against a target that's been unreachable
  -- the whole time.
  reconnectTmr.EventHandler = function()
    reconnectTmr:Stop()
    connect(true)
  end

  -- ── Control Event Handlers ──────────────────────────────────
  -- Connect when IP is entered or changed. Reset first -- see
  -- resetForNewTarget's comment for why this matters: without it, a
  -- command queued while pointed at a different (or unreachable) address
  -- would otherwise get sent, with top priority, to whatever unit we
  -- connect to next.
  Controls.IP_ADDRESS.EventHandler = function()
    resetForNewTarget()
    if Controls.TCP_PORT.String == "" then
      Controls.TCP_PORT.String = tostring(TCP_PORT)
    end
    connect()
    httpConnected = false
    httpBuf = ""
    local ip = Controls.IP_ADDRESS.String
    if httpSock and isValidIP(ip) then httpSock:Connect(ip, 80) end
  end

  Controls.Reconnect.EventHandler = function() connect() end

  -- Single consolidated refresh: re-fetches everything that's normally
  -- only fetched once at connect (v1.2.0.11 -- previously 4 separate
  -- buttons across 3 pages). Queued in order at the FRONT of nameQueue so
  -- it executes on the next few HTTP cycles ahead of routine traffic.
  Controls.Refresh_Setup.EventHandler = function()
    local items = {
      {"/Setup.xml?PgIdx=75", applyInputNames},
      {"/Setup.xml?PgIdx=74", applyOutputNames},
    }
    if ENABLE_QDC then
      table.insert(items, {"/Setup.xml?PgIdx=13", applyDimmerSetup})
      table.insert(items, {"/rtLin.xml", applyLinNetwork})
    end
    for k = #items, 1, -1 do  -- reverse order so repeated front-inserts land in the right final sequence
      table.insert(nameQueue, 1, items[k])
    end
    dbg("Manual setup refresh queued (priority): " .. #items .. " items")
  end

  -- Transport command buttons (Trigger type)
  Controls.Cmd_Start.EventHandler        = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",STA,Y") end
  Controls.Cmd_Stop.EventHandler         = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",STP,Y") end
  Controls.Cmd_Cue.EventHandler          = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",CUE,Y") end
  Controls.Cmd_Abort.EventHandler        = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",ABT,Y") end
  Controls.Cmd_Fault.EventHandler        = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",FLT,Y") end
  Controls.Cmd_Clear_Fault.EventHandler  = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",CLR,Y") end
  Controls.Cmd_Reset.EventHandler        = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",RES,Y") end
  Controls.Cmd_Cancel_Alarm.EventHandler = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",CNL,Y") end

  -- Program selection (Trigger type)
  Controls.Cmd_Set_Program.EventHandler = function()
    sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",PGM,"..Controls.Set_Program.String..",Y")
  end
  Controls.Cmd_Set_And_Run.EventHandler = function()
    sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",SPR,"..Controls.Set_Program.String..",Y")
  end

  -- Macro triggers (Trigger type, indexed 1-N)
  if Controls.Macros then
    for idx, ctl in ipairs(Controls.Macros) do
      ctl.EventHandler = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",MAC,"..idx..",Y") end
    end
  end

  -- RDI triggers (Trigger type, device and command derived from flat index)
  if Controls.RDI then
    for idx, ctl in ipairs(Controls.RDI) do
      local dev = math.ceil(idx/16)
      local cmd = ((idx-1) % 16) + 1
      ctl.EventHandler = function() sendCmd("EVT,"..nextPSN()..",RDI,"..dev..","..cmd..",Y") end
    end
  end

  -- House Lights: mutually exclusive Toggle, sends HLNONE/HLDOWN/etc.
  local HouseLightCodes = {"HLNONE","HLDOWN","HLMID1","HLMID2","HLUP"}
  for idx, ctl in ipairs(Controls.House_Lights) do
    ctl.EventHandler = function()
      setExclusive(Controls.House_Lights, idx)
      sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..HouseLightCodes[idx]..",N")
    end
  end

  -- Stage Lights: mutually exclusive Toggle
  local StageLightCodes = {"SLNONE","SLDOWN","SLUP"}
  for idx, ctl in ipairs(Controls.Stage_Lights) do
    ctl.EventHandler = function()
      setExclusive(Controls.Stage_Lights, idx)
      sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..StageLightCodes[idx]..",N")
    end
  end

  -- Curtain: mutually exclusive Toggle
  local CurtainCodes = {"CURTNONE","CURTCLOS","CURTOPEN"}
  for idx, ctl in ipairs(Controls.Curtain) do
    ctl.EventHandler = function()
      setExclusive(Controls.Curtain, idx)
      sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..CurtainCodes[idx]..",N")
    end
  end

  -- Masking: mutually exclusive Toggle
  local MaskCodes = {"MSKNONE","MSKFLAT","MSKSCOPE","MSKSPECL"}
  for idx, ctl in ipairs(Controls.Masking) do
    ctl.EventHandler = function()
      setExclusive(Controls.Masking, idx)
      sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..MaskCodes[idx]..",N")
    end
  end

  -- Lens: mutually exclusive Toggle
  local LensCodes = {"LENNONE","LENFLAT","LENSCOPE","LENSPECL"}
  for idx, ctl in ipairs(Controls.Lens) do
    ctl.EventHandler = function()
      setExclusive(Controls.Lens, idx)
      sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..LensCodes[idx]..",N")
    end
  end

  -- Sound: mutually exclusive Toggle
  local SoundCodes = {"SNDNONE","SNDAUX1","SNDAUX2","SNDDIG1","SNDDIG2","SNDMONO","SNDNSYNC","SNDSR","SNDSVA"}
  for idx, ctl in ipairs(Controls.Sound) do
    ctl.EventHandler = function()
      setExclusive(Controls.Sound, idx)
      sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..SoundCodes[idx]..",N")
    end
  end

  -- Mute: independent Toggle
  Controls.Mute.EventHandler = function()
    sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..(Controls.Mute.Boolean and "MUTEON" or "MUTEOFF")..",N")
  end

  -- Digital Projector toggles (send ON/OFF commands)
  Controls.Dig1_Power.EventHandler    = function() sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..(Controls.Dig1_Power.Boolean    and "DP1ON"   or "DP1OFF")  ..",Y") end
  Controls.Dig1_Video.EventHandler    = function() sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..(Controls.Dig1_Video.Boolean    and "DV1ON"   or "DV1OFF")  ..",Y") end
  Controls.Dig2_Power.EventHandler    = function() sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..(Controls.Dig2_Power.Boolean    and "DP2ON"   or "DP2OFF")  ..",Y") end
  Controls.Dig2_Video.EventHandler    = function() sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..(Controls.Dig2_Video.Boolean    and "DV2ON"   or "DV2OFF")  ..",Y") end
  Controls.Aux_Projector.EventHandler = function() sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..(Controls.Aux_Projector.Boolean and "SPROJON" or "SPROJOFF")..",Y") end

  -- Aux Outputs 1-16
  for idx, ctl in ipairs(Controls.Aux_Out) do
    ctl.EventHandler = function()
      sendCmd("OUT,"..nextPSN()..","..(Controls.Aux_Out[idx].Boolean and "OUT"..idx.."ON" or "OUT"..idx.."OFF")..",Y")
    end
  end

  -- ── QDC-400 Dimmer Lighting: Zone preset / offset controls (v1.2) ──
  -- NOTE: unlike every other output group in this file, these are NOT sent
  -- via the CAI socket (sendCmd/"OUT,..."). The CAI protocol has no codes
  -- for Zone 3-16 lights, individual channel levels, or the offset -- the
  -- only path is HTTP GET /rtLights.xml?Zone=..&State=..&Level=..&Fader=..
  -- (see manual §4.3.19-21, §5.9, and the eCNA's own statLightCtrl.htm).
  -- Commands are queued via queueLightCmd() and sent by httpRequest(),
  -- sharing the single HTTP connection with the flag scrape and name
  -- fetches, exactly like the Refresh_Setup button already does for the name queue.
  if Controls.Zone_Preset then
    -- rtLights.xml State codes: 0=Up 1=Down 2=Mid1 3=Mid2 4=None
    -- (matches button order Up/Down/Mid1/Mid2/None used throughout this file)
    local ZonePresetState = {0,1,2,3,4}
    for i = 1, qdcZones do
      local base = (i-1)*5
      for b = 1, 5 do
        local ctl = Controls.Zone_Preset[base+b]
        if ctl then
          ctl.EventHandler = function()
            for k = 1, 5 do Controls.Zone_Preset[base+k].Boolean = (k == b) end
            -- v1.2.0.41: capture whatever offset was actually showing right
            -- before beginPresetPending resets it to 0, so the one-extra-
            -- poll-cycle settling guard knows this transition "started"
            -- with a non-zero offset even though the target itself (offset
            -- reset to 0 on a fresh preset selection) doesn't.
            local priorOffset = Controls.Zone_Offset[i] and Controls.Zone_Offset[i].Value or 0
            beginPresetPending(i, ZonePresetState[b])  -- mask until eCNA confirms (or 15s), avoids visible flicker/reversion
            zoneCurrentPreset[i] = ZonePresetState[b]  -- remembered so a later offset-only change knows which preset level to combine with
            -- v1.2.0.41 fix: a preset selection ALSO resets the zone's
            -- offset to 0 (manual sec 5.9, mirrored above via
            -- beginPresetPending -> beginOffsetPending(i, 0)) -- but until
            -- now, zoneLastOffset[i] (the unified detection block's own
            -- "last known offset" bookkeeping) was never updated here, only
            -- zoneCurrentPreset was. zoneLastOffset only gets refreshed
            -- inside that detection block itself, which stays fully gated
            -- off while offsetPending is true -- so it remained stale at
            -- whatever offset was active BEFORE this button press. The
            -- very poll that finally confirms our command (clearing both
            -- presetPending and offsetPending) runs that detection block
            -- immediately afterward, in the SAME call -- sees the stale
            -- prevOff no longer matches the real (now zero) offset, and
            -- mistakes it for a fresh, independent offset-only change --
            -- firing animateOffsetChange with applyCompensation=true, which
            -- uses the fixed ~3s OFFSET_FADE_SECONDS (minus
            -- DETECTION_LAG_COMPENSATION) instead of the PRESET's own,
            -- typically much longer, configured fade for whatever distance
            -- is left. Symptom: the meter starts out correctly on the
            -- preset's own fade, then suddenly speeds up partway through.
            -- Updating zoneLastOffset here, in step with zoneCurrentPreset,
            -- means that once the real confirmation arrives, the detection
            -- block sees no change at all (0 == 0) and stays quiet, exactly
            -- as it already correctly does for the preset side.
            zoneLastOffset[i] = 0
            animatePresetChange(i, ZonePresetState[b], 0, false, priorOffset)  -- offset resets to 0 on a fresh preset selection (manual §5.9); self-initiated, no detection-lag compensation needed
            queueLightCmd(i-1, ZonePresetState[b], 0, 0)  -- Level/Fader=0, mirrors the web page's preset buttons
          end
        end
      end
    end
  end

  if Controls.Zone_Offset then
    for i = 1, qdcZones do
      local ctl = Controls.Zone_Offset[i]
      if ctl then
        ctl.EventHandler = function()
          -- Debounced network commit: text updates on every tick, but the
          -- actual command only fires once the fader has been still for 1s
          -- -- sending on every intermediate tick while dragging was
          -- fighting the poll latency and made the slider feel broken (it
          -- would "chase" a stale in-flight value). Masking is engaged on
          -- every tick (not just at commit) so a poll landing mid-drag
          -- can't flip the displayed value back before the debounce fires.
          -- The local channel-meter animation, by contrast, previews live
          -- on every tick -- we already know the target instantly, no need
          -- to wait for the network round trip to show the user what's coming.
          local v = math.floor(ctl.Value + 0.5)
          if Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i] then Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i].String = tostring(v) end
          beginOffsetPending(i, v)  -- masks immediately; re-armed (target + 15s failsafe) on every tick
          -- v1.2.0.41: keep zoneLastOffset in step with our own optimistic
          -- change, same reasoning as the preset button handler above --
          -- otherwise the unified detection block, once offsetPending
          -- finally clears, would compare the real (now-matching) offset
          -- against this stale value and mistake it for a fresh change,
          -- re-triggering the animation with applyCompensation=true.
          zoneLastOffset[i] = v
          animateOffsetChange(i, v, false)  -- self-initiated (live drag preview), no detection-lag compensation needed
          offsetDebounceGen[i] = (offsetDebounceGen[i] or 0) + 1
          local myGen = offsetDebounceGen[i]
          Timer.CallAfter(function()
            if offsetDebounceGen[i] == myGen then  -- no further movement since this tick -- fader has settled
              queueLightCmd(i-1, 5, v, 3)  -- State=5 (offset-only), Fader=3, mirrors the web page's slider commit
            end
          end, 1)
        end
      end
    end
  end

  if Controls.Zone_Offset_Text then
    for i = 1, qdcZones do
      local ctl = Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i]
      if ctl then
        ctl.EventHandler = function()
          local v = tonumber(ctl.String)
          if v then
            v = math.floor(v + 0.5)
            if     v < -100 then v = -100
            elseif v > 100  then v = 100 end
            Controls.Zone_Offset[i].Value = v
            ctl.String = tostring(v)
            beginOffsetPending(i, v)  -- mask until eCNA echoes back this exact value (or 15s)
            zoneLastOffset[i] = v  -- v1.2.0.41: see the fader handler above -- avoids a stale-comparison false re-trigger once offsetPending clears
            animateOffsetChange(i, v, false)  -- self-initiated, no detection-lag compensation needed
            queueLightCmd(i-1, 5, v, 3)
          else
            ctl.String = tostring(Controls.Zone_Offset[i].Value)  -- reject non-numeric entry, restore last known value
          end
        end
      end
    end
  end

  -- ── Offset step buttons (v1.2.0.41; debounced v1.2.0.46) ────────
  -- Momentary Increase/Decrease buttons beside the Offset readout: a quick
  -- press/release nudges the offset by 1; holding past HOLD_DELAY begins
  -- repeating at 1 unit per HOLD_REPEAT seconds until released. Reuses the
  -- exact same self-initiated offset pipeline as the fader/text box
  -- (beginOffsetPending, zoneLastOffset sync, animateOffsetChange,
  -- queueLightCmd) so it gets the same masking/animation/race protections
  -- for free -- no new interaction with the eCNA beyond what a fader drag
  -- or text commit already does.
  if Controls.Zone_Offset_Inc or Controls.Zone_Offset_Dec then
    local HOLD_DELAY  = 2.0   -- seconds held before repeat kicks in
    local HOLD_REPEAT = 0.5   -- seconds between repeated steps once past HOLD_DELAY
    local offsetStepTimer = {} -- offsetStepTimer[zone][dir] = current Timer instance ("inc"/"dec" kept independent so pressing both at once can't cross-cancel each other)
    local offsetStepGen   = {} -- offsetStepGen[zone][dir]   = generation counter; invalidates a stale scheduled callback after release or a fresh press

    local function stepOffset(i, delta)
      local ctl = Controls.Zone_Offset[i]
      if not ctl then return end
      -- v1.2.0.41 fix: Zone_Offset (a Knob/Fader control) stores Value as a
      -- Lua float even when it's showing a whole number -- the fader itself
      -- can be dragged to fractional positions, though nothing else in
      -- this plugin ever intentionally sets a fractional offset. Reading
      -- it raw and adding an integer delta (float + integer = float, per
      -- Lua 5.3's arithmetic subtype rules) kept the result a float too, so
      -- tostring(v) printed "6.0" instead of "6" -- until the next live
      -- poll's tonumber(zofs[i]) (a plain integer string, no decimal point)
      -- overwrote it with a genuine Lua integer and "corrected" the
      -- display. Rounding here forces the integer subtype up front, same
      -- as the fader/text handlers already do via math.floor(x + 0.5), so
      -- every write to Zone_Offset_Text from a self-initiated change is a
      -- clean integer string from the start.
      local cur = math.floor((ctl.Value or 0) + 0.5)
      local v = cur + delta
      if v < -100 then v = -100 elseif v > 100 then v = 100 end
      if v == cur then return end  -- already at the +/-100 limit -- nothing new to send
      ctl.Value = v
      if Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i] then Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i].String = tostring(v) end
      beginOffsetPending(i, v)   -- masks immediately; re-armed on every step, same as the fader drag
      zoneLastOffset[i] = v      -- keep the unified-detection baseline in sync (v1.2.0.41 fix)
      animateOffsetChange(i, v, false)  -- self-initiated, no detection-lag compensation
      -- v1.2.0.46 fix: this used to call queueLightCmd() immediately on
      -- every step, on the theory that each tap is "a deliberate discrete
      -- action, not a continuous drag needing debounce." Field testing
      -- showed otherwise: a fast burst of taps (or the HOLD_REPEAT
      -- auto-repeat, one step per 0.5s) can generate commands faster than
      -- httpRequest() drains them -- LIGHTCMD is serviced at most once per
      -- HTTP round trip, roughly once per Scrape_Interval -- and
      -- queueLightCmd's 4-deep cap (mirroring the eCNA's own command
      -- buffer) silently drops anything past it, with no guarantee the
      -- LAST tapped value is among the survivors. Net effect: rapidly
      -- tapping to +10% could leave the real device short (e.g. 8%) while
      -- our own local prediction still showed 10%, only correcting once a
      -- later scrape caught the mismatch. Now debounced exactly like the
      -- fader drag handler above, sharing its same offsetDebounceGen[i]
      -- counter (both ultimately commit the same zone offset, so unifying
      -- the debounce is correct regardless of which control last moved) --
      -- only the final value, once input has been idle for 1s, is ever
      -- sent. The local display/animation still updates instantly on every
      -- tap; only the network commit waits.
      offsetDebounceGen[i] = (offsetDebounceGen[i] or 0) + 1
      local myGen = offsetDebounceGen[i]
      Timer.CallAfter(function()
        if offsetDebounceGen[i] == myGen then  -- no further movement (button or fader) since this tick -- settled
          queueLightCmd(i-1, 5, v, 3)  -- State=5 (offset-only), Fader=3, mirrors the web page's slider commit
        end
      end, 1)
    end

    local function startOffsetHold(i, dir, delta)
      offsetStepGen[i] = offsetStepGen[i] or {}
      offsetStepGen[i][dir] = (offsetStepGen[i][dir] or 0) + 1
      local myGen = offsetStepGen[i][dir]
      offsetStepTimer[i] = offsetStepTimer[i] or {}
      -- v1.2.0.41: always a FRESH Timer here, never reused across separate
      -- press cycles. A stale scheduled fire from an earlier press (one
      -- Timer:Stop() didn't manage to cancel before it fired -- can't
      -- assume otherwise across every possible runtime) would otherwise
      -- call whatever EventHandler is CURRENTLY assigned to a shared,
      -- reused Timer object -- i.e. the latest closure, whose captured
      -- myGen matches the CURRENT generation and so isn't recognized as
      -- stale at all. A brand-new Timer per press means an old, abandoned
      -- one's EventHandler closure is permanently fixed to the OLD myGen,
      -- so the generation check above correctly catches it as stale
      -- regardless of whether Stop() actually prevented it from firing.
      local t = Timer.New()
      offsetStepTimer[i][dir] = t
      stepOffset(i, delta)  -- immediate first step on press
      t.EventHandler = function()
        if offsetStepGen[i][dir] ~= myGen then return end  -- released (or re-pressed) since this fire was scheduled -- stale, ignore
        stepOffset(i, delta)
        t:Start(HOLD_REPEAT)
      end
      t:Start(HOLD_DELAY)
    end

    local function stopOffsetHold(i, dir)
      offsetStepGen[i] = offsetStepGen[i] or {}
      offsetStepGen[i][dir] = (offsetStepGen[i][dir] or 0) + 1  -- invalidates any pending timer callback
      if offsetStepTimer[i] and offsetStepTimer[i][dir] then offsetStepTimer[i][dir]:Stop() end
    end

    if Controls.Zone_Offset_Inc then
      for i = 1, qdcZones do
        local ctl = Controls.Zone_Offset_Inc[i]
        if ctl then
          ctl.EventHandler = function()
            if ctl.Boolean then startOffsetHold(i, "inc", 1) else stopOffsetHold(i, "inc") end
          end
        end
      end
    end

    if Controls.Zone_Offset_Dec then
      for i = 1, qdcZones do
        local ctl = Controls.Zone_Offset_Dec[i]
        if ctl then
          ctl.EventHandler = function()
            if ctl.Boolean then startOffsetHold(i, "dec", -1) else stopOffsetHold(i, "dec") end
          end
        end
      end
    end
  end

  -- (Refresh_Dimmer_Setup and Refresh_LIN_Network consolidated into the
  -- single Refresh_Setup handler above -- v1.2.0.11.)

  -- ── User-defined name tables ────────────────────────────────
  -- Fetched from eCNA on connect; fall back to default names if empty
  local inputNames  = {}  -- inputNames[1..16]  = user name for In1..In16
  local outputNames = {}  -- outputNames[1..16] = user name for Out1..Out16
  for i=1,16 do
    inputNames[i]  = "In"..i
    outputNames[i] = "Out"..i
  end

  -- Parse <tx>...</tx> values from Setup.xml response in order
  local function parseNames(data)
    local names = {}
    for name in data:gmatch("<tx>([^<]*)</tx>") do
      table.insert(names, name ~= "" and name:match("^%s*(.-)%s*$") or nil)
    end
    return names
  end

  -- Apply fetched input names to controls and internal table.
  -- Takes the raw HTTP body (not pre-parsed) so the Closed handler can
  -- route to any NAME-type applyFn -- including applyDimmerSetup below,
  -- which needs the raw body since it parses different tags (<txt>/<zone>
  -- rather than <tx>) -- with one uniform `currentApplyFn(body)` call.
  applyInputNames = function(body)
    local names = parseNames(body)
    for i = 1, math.min(#names, 16) do
      if names[i] then
        inputNames[i] = names[i]
      end
      -- Update the In_Names control string (used as display text in layout)
      if Controls.In_Names[i] then
        Controls.In_Names[i].String = inputNames[i]
      end
    end
    dbg("Input names loaded: " .. inputNames[1] .. ", " .. inputNames[2] .. "...")
    populated.inNames = true
    checkFullyPopulated()
  end

  -- Apply fetched output names to controls and internal table
  applyOutputNames = function(body)
    local names = parseNames(body)
    for i = 1, math.min(#names, 16) do
      if names[i] then
        outputNames[i] = names[i]
      end
      if Controls.Out_Names[i] then
        Controls.Out_Names[i].String = outputNames[i]
      end
    end
    dbg("Output names loaded: " .. outputNames[1] .. ", " .. outputNames[2] .. "...")
    populated.outNames = true
    checkFullyPopulated()
  end

  -- Apply fetched Setup.xml PgIdx=13 (QDC dimmer setup) response.
  -- Unlike applyInputNames/applyOutputNames this parses two different
  -- structures out of one response body, so it does its own parsing
  -- rather than going through parseNames() (which matches <tx>, not <txt>).
  --   Zone names: /setup/dimmers/names/nam/txt -- 14 entries, Zone3..Zone16 in order
  --   Channels:   /setup/dimmers/channels/chan -- 16 <chan> blocks, one per
  --     channel, each containing <zone>, <lev><up/dn/m1/m2></lev> (target
  --     level % for each preset), and <fad><up/dn/m1/m2></fad> (fade-in
  --     seconds for each preset). Parsed per-<chan> block (not with a flat
  --     global gmatch) so level/fade/zone stay correctly correlated to the
  --     right channel. <zone> value is a 1-based index into
  --     [none, House, Stage, Zone3..Zone16], i.e. 0=unassigned, 1=House,
  --     2=Stage, 3..16=Zone 3..16 (matches the zone number directly).
  --     Converted to rtLights.xml's 0-based Zone index (0=House..15=Zone16)
  --     as channelZone[ch] = value - 1.
  -- The lev/fad tables feed the local meter-animation simulation (see
  -- startChannelAnim below) -- manual §4.3.29/§5.9: a preset drives a
  -- channel to its configured level, and the offset is an additive
  -- override on top of that (absolute value when preset=None).
  applyDimmerSetup = function(body)
    local nIdx = 0
    for txt in body:gmatch("<txt>([^<]*)</txt>") do
      nIdx = nIdx + 1
      local zi = nIdx + 2  -- zone number 3..16
      if zi <= 16 then
        local nm = txt ~= "" and txt:match("^%s*(.-)%s*$") or nil
        zoneNames[zi] = (nm and nm ~= "") and nm or ("Zone "..zi)
        if zi <= qdcZones and Controls.Zone_Name and Controls.Zone_Name[zi] then
          Controls.Zone_Name[zi].String = zoneNames[zi]
        end
      end
    end
    local cIdx = 0
    for chanBlock in body:gmatch("<chan>(.-)</chan>") do
      cIdx = cIdx + 1
      local zv = tonumber(chanBlock:match("<zone>(%d+)</zone>")) or 0
      channelZone[cIdx] = zv - 1  -- 0-based rtLights.xml zone index; -1 = unassigned

      local levBlock = chanBlock:match("<lev>(.-)</lev>") or ""
      local fadBlock = chanBlock:match("<fad>(.-)</fad>") or ""
      channelPresetLevel[cIdx] = {
        [0] = tonumber(levBlock:match("<up>(%-?%d+)</up>")) or 0,  -- index by rtLights State code: 0=Up
        [1] = tonumber(levBlock:match("<dn>(%-?%d+)</dn>")) or 0,  -- 1=Down
        [2] = tonumber(levBlock:match("<m1>(%-?%d+)</m1>")) or 0,  -- 2=Mid1
        [3] = tonumber(levBlock:match("<m2>(%-?%d+)</m2>")) or 0,  -- 3=Mid2
      }
      channelPresetFade[cIdx] = {
        [0] = tonumber(fadBlock:match("<up>(%d+)</up>")),
        [1] = tonumber(fadBlock:match("<dn>(%d+)</dn>")),
        [2] = tonumber(fadBlock:match("<m1>(%d+)</m1>")),
        [3] = tonumber(fadBlock:match("<m2>(%d+)</m2>")),
      }

      if cIdx <= qdcChannels and Controls.Channel_Zone and Controls.Channel_Zone[cIdx] then
        local label
        if     zv == 0 then label = "-"
        elseif zv == 1 then label = "House"
        elseif zv == 2 then label = "Stage"
        else                label = zoneNames[zv] or ("Zone "..zv) end
        Controls.Channel_Zone[cIdx].String = label
      end
    end
    dbg("Dimmer setup loaded: "..nIdx.." zone names, "..cIdx.." channel level/fade configs")
    populated.dimmerSetup = true
    checkFullyPopulated()
  end

  -- Apply fetched /rtLin.xml (Status: Local I/O Network) response.
  -- Structure (from the eCNA's own statLin.htm): <lin><id>NNNN<dtyp>7</dtyp>
  -- <stat>132</stat>...other fields...</id><id>...</id></lin> -- one <id>
  -- block per device responding on the LIN network. dtyp 7 = "QDC-400"
  -- (dtyp 8 is its boot-loader mode, not counted as a working board). The
  -- stat field is a bitmask; bit 0x80 = "Device Active". This is a
  -- structural, independent confirmation of dimmer hardware presence --
  -- if zero active QDC-400 boards are found, every channel is immediately
  -- marked unconfirmed/no-dimmer rather than waiting on the slower
  -- per-channel "2 unexpected 0% polls" heuristic in parseLights.
  applyLinNetwork = function(body)
    local activeCount = 0
    local totalCount  = 0
    for idBlock in body:gmatch("<id>(.-)</id>") do
      local dtyp = tonumber(idBlock:match("<dtyp>(%d+)</dtyp>"))
      local stat = tonumber(idBlock:match("<stat>(%d+)</stat>")) or 0
      if dtyp == 7 then
        totalCount = totalCount + 1
        if (stat % 256) >= 128 then activeCount = activeCount + 1 end  -- bit 0x80 (Device Active), computed via arithmetic rather than a bitwise operator for portability
      end
    end
    qdcBoardCount = activeCount
    if Controls.QDC_Board_Count then Controls.QDC_Board_Count.String = tostring(activeCount) end
    dbg("LIN network scan: "..totalCount.." QDC-400 board(s) found, "..activeCount.." active")

    if activeCount == 0 then
      -- Structurally confirmed: no working QDC-400 hardware on the bus at
      -- all. Mark every channel unconfirmed/no-dimmer immediately rather
      -- than waiting for a preset change and 2 failed polls to find out.
      for ch = 1, qdcChannels do
        channelNoDimmer[ch]  = true
        channelConfirmed[ch] = false
        if Controls.Channel_Present and Controls.Channel_Present[ch] then
          Controls.Channel_Present[ch].Boolean = false
        end
      end
    end
    -- Note: activeCount > 0 does NOT clear channelNoDimmer/channelConfirmed
    -- for any channel -- a board being present on the bus doesn't prove any
    -- *particular* channel is wired to a working fixture. That positive
    -- confirmation still only comes from an actual non-zero level reading.
    populated.linScan = true
    checkFullyPopulated()
  end

  -- (v1.2.0.4: names -- input, output, and dimmer setup -- are fetched once
  -- on connect and otherwise only via their manual Refresh buttons; no
  -- periodic re-fetch. See the Connected handler above and the three
  -- Refresh_*_Names button handlers below.)

  -- ── Web Scrape via raw TCP HTTP/1.0 ─────────────────────────
  -- scrapeTimer is the sole reconnect driver (fires every SCRAPE_RATE seconds).
  -- httpRequest() called from both scrapeTimer AND Connected handler:
  --   scrapeTimer: not connected -> Connect(); connected -> no-op (httpBusy)
  --   Connected handler: always sends the GET immediately
  httpSock            = TcpSocket.New()  -- assigns to forward-declared upvalue
  local httpBuf       = ""
  local httpConnected = false
  local scrapeTimer   = Timer.New()

  -- Send HTTP GET, tagging currentReqType so the Closed handler knows
  -- which parser to route the response to.
  local function httpSend(path)
    local ip = Controls.IP_ADDRESS.String
    local req = "GET " .. path .. " HTTP/1.0\r\n"
             .. "Host: " .. ip .. "\r\n"
             .. "Authorization: Basic YWRtaW46MzE0MTU5\r\n"
             .. "Connection: close\r\n"
             .. "\r\n"
    httpSock:Write(req)
    httpBusy = true
    dbg("HTTP GET " .. path)
  end

  -- v1.2.0.41: scrape (/rtIoFDetail.xml) is the plugin's core purpose --
  -- it's how preset changes and every other CAI-flag-driven indicator
  -- (Inputs/Outputs pages, House/Stage fast-path) get detected, same as the
  -- original script this plugin replaced.
  --
  -- This build decouples the dimmer LIGHTPOLL from Scrape_Interval, after
  -- two rounds of field experimentation (build 40 stayed untouched
  -- throughout). The first attempt made scrape strictly alternate 1:1 with
  -- an "other" turn (light commands/name fetches/dimmer poll) -- but field
  -- logs (Scrape_Interval=1s) showed that barely moved real scrape cadence
  -- versus the unmodified build, because scrapeTimer restarts fresh after
  -- EVERY request regardless of type: real scrape-to-scrape gap was always
  -- ~2x(Scrape_Interval + round-trip) whenever the dimmer LIGHTPOLL was
  -- enabled, since it was consuming every other turn either way. Lowering
  -- Scrape_Interval sped up scrape AND lightpoll together, never scrape
  -- alone.
  --
  -- This version decouples them properly: LIGHTPOLL now runs on its OWN
  -- slower cadence (LightPoll_Interval, tracked in routine "ticks" via
  -- lightPollEveryNTicks -- see GetProperties/config comments) instead of
  -- automatically claiming every other turn. Scrape is the DEFAULT action
  -- every tick that nothing higher-priority claims, so Scrape_Interval now
  -- controls real scrape cadence directly, exactly as Steve asked ("let
  -- scrape have a real (or more real) setting"). Confirmed via field debug
  -- logs: at Scrape_Interval=1/LightPoll_Interval=4, ticks land in a clean
  -- SCRAPE,SCRAPE,SCRAPE,LIGHTPOLL repeating pattern (2/3 of scrape-to-
  -- scrape gaps ~1.2-1.4s, the other 1/3 ~2.5-2.7s where a lightpoll sits in
  -- between) -- a real improvement over the prior scheme's constant
  -- ~2.5-2.7s. Steve found LightPoll_Interval=3 (vs. the default
  -- Scrape_Interval of 2) a further, noticeable improvement, particularly
  -- for offset-change responsiveness -- see GetProperties comment.
  --
  -- Priority order per tick:
  --   1) lightCmdQueue (button/offset manual commands) -- immediate, always
  --   2) nameQueue while NOT yet fully populated (one-time init bootstrap,
  --      or re-init after a target change) -- immediate, always; nothing is
  --      trustworthy yet so there's no scrape cadence worth protecting
  --   3) nameQueue once populated (e.g. a manual Refresh_Setup press) --
  --      still manual control, still immediate -- no longer has to wait for
  --      an "other" turn at all, which is a small additional improvement
  --   4) dimmer LIGHTPOLL, only once its own slower interval has elapsed
  --   5) nanoHost NANOHOST poll (v1.3), only once its own MUCH slower
  --      interval has elapsed -- checked here, still ahead of the SCRAPE
  --      default, because SCRAPE has no "due" gating of its own (it's
  --      unconditional once reached) -- if NANOHOST were checked after it,
  --      it would never actually get a turn. Lower priority than LIGHTPOLL
  --      is expressed simply by checking it second: on the rare tick where
  --      both are due at once, LIGHTPOLL wins and NANOHOST's counter just
  --      isn't reset, so it gets picked up the very next tick instead.
  --   6) SCRAPE -- the default, every tick nothing above claimed
  local routineTicks = 0  -- counts turns since the last LIGHTPOLL; reset on send or on a fresh target
  local nanoTicks    = 0  -- v1.3: counts turns since the last NANOHOST poll; reset on send or on a fresh target
  local function httpRequest()
    local ip = Controls.IP_ADDRESS.String
    if not isValidIP(ip) then
      scrapeTimer:Start(SCRAPE_RATE)  -- ensure timer restarts if invalid IP
      return
    end
    scrapeTimer:Stop()  -- pause timer; restarted in Closed handler
    if not httpConnected then
      httpSock:Connect(ip, 80)
      return
    end
    if httpBusy then return end  -- request already in-flight, wait for Closed event

    if #lightCmdQueue > 0 then
      local cmd = table.remove(lightCmdQueue, 1)
      currentReqType = "LIGHTCMD"
      httpSend(string.format("/rtLights.xml?Zone=%d&State=%d&Level=%d&Fader=%d", cmd[1], cmd[2], cmd[3], cmd[4]))
      return
    end

    -- The one-time initial population (input/output names, dimmer setup,
    -- LIN scan -- queued in nameQueue right after Connected) keeps its
    -- original top priority, ahead of scrape. Per Steve: "The initial
    -- interaction to retrieve all of the information can take priority over
    -- the scrape function. It is presumed that until we're done
    -- initializing, nothing is correct yet." statusIsOK is false during
    -- this window (and again briefly after a target change re-triggers
    -- population), so this only engages during genuine (re)initialization.
    if #nameQueue > 0 and not statusIsOK then
      local item = table.remove(nameQueue, 1)
      currentReqType = "NAME"
      currentApplyFn = item[2]
      httpSend(item[1])
      return
    end

    -- A LATER name fetch once already populated (e.g. a manual
    -- Refresh_Setup press) is manual control, same priority tier as light
    -- commands -- still immediate, doesn't wait for anything.
    if #nameQueue > 0 then
      local item = table.remove(nameQueue, 1)
      currentReqType = "NAME"
      currentApplyFn = item[2]
      httpSend(item[1])
      return
    end

    routineTicks = routineTicks + 1

    -- Dimmer LIGHTPOLL: decoupled from scrape -- only takes a turn once its
    -- OWN slower interval has elapsed, instead of automatically claiming
    -- every other tick. Meter animation between real polls already masks
    -- the slower refresh (per Steve: "we're already 'faking' the dimmer
    -- meters with our animation").
    if ENABLE_QDC and routineTicks >= lightPollEveryNTicks then
      routineTicks = 0
      currentReqType = "LIGHTPOLL"
      httpSend("/rtLights.xml")
      return
    end

    -- v1.3: nanoHost NANOHOST poll -- lowest priority, own much-slower
    -- cadence (NANO_POLL_RATE, ~2.5 min). Only takes a turn when enabled AND
    -- due; per Steve, this data updates no faster than every 5 minutes at
    -- the source, so polling it any more aggressively than this buys nothing
    -- and would just compete with scrape/lightpoll for no benefit.
    nanoTicks = nanoTicks + 1
    if ENABLE_NANOHOST and nanoTicks >= nanoPollEveryNTicks then
      nanoTicks = 0
      currentReqType = "NANOHOST"
      httpSend("/rtmandata.xml")
      return
    end

    -- Default: SCRAPE, every tick nothing above claimed. This is now the
    -- common case, so Scrape_Interval directly reflects real scrape cadence.
    currentReqType = "SCRAPE"
    httpSend("/rtIoFDetail.xml")
  end

  -- ── Web Scrape XML Parser ────────────────────────────────────
  -- Parses <outs> and <ins> flag lists from the XML response
  -- Updates button states and LED indicators accordingly
  local function csvSplit(s)
    local t, pos = {}, 1
    while true do
      local nx = string.find(s, ",", pos, true)
      if nx == nil then
        if pos <= #s then table.insert(t, string.sub(s, pos)) end
        break
      end
      table.insert(t, string.sub(s, pos, nx-1))
      pos = nx + 1
    end
    return t
  end

  local function scrape(data)
    local function fi(sub) return string.find(data, sub, 1, true) or 0 end
    local os, oe  = fi("<outs>"),  fi("</outs>")
    local is_, ie = fi("<ins>"),   fi("</ins>")
    if os == 0 or is_ == 0 then return end

    -- Parse comma-separated flag numbers from XML tags
    local OutputFlags, InputFlags = {}, {}
    for _, v in ipairs(csvSplit(string.sub(data, os+6, oe-1)))  do table.insert(OutputFlags, tonumber(v)) end
    for _, v in ipairs(csvSplit(string.sub(data, is_+5, ie-1))) do table.insert(InputFlags,  tonumber(v)) end
    dbg("Scrape: " .. #OutputFlags .. " out flags, " .. #InputFlags .. " in flags")

    -- Helper: returns true if flag n is in the active output list
    local function flagActive(n)
      for _, v in ipairs(OutputFlags) do if v == n then return true end end
      return false
    end

    -- (The Controls.Outputs mirror loop that lived here was removed in
    -- v1.2.0.20 along with the Outputs control itself -- flagActive()
    -- above already has everything scrape() needs.)
    for idx = 1, #Controls.Inputs do
      local a = false
      -- Input flags are offset by 3 from their InFlagNames index (per eCNA manual)
      for _, v in ipairs(InputFlags) do if (v - 3) == idx then a = true; break end end
      Controls.Inputs[idx].Value = a and 1 or 0
    end

    -- Sync mutually exclusive output button groups from active flags
    -- House Lights: flags 5=Down, 6=Mid1, 7=Mid2, 8=Up, none=None
    if     flagActive(8)  then setExclusive(Controls.House_Lights, 5)
    elseif flagActive(7)  then setExclusive(Controls.House_Lights, 4)
    elseif flagActive(6)  then setExclusive(Controls.House_Lights, 3)
    elseif flagActive(5)  then setExclusive(Controls.House_Lights, 2)
    else                       setExclusive(Controls.House_Lights, 1) end

    -- Stage Lights: flags 9=Down, 10=Up
    if     flagActive(10) then setExclusive(Controls.Stage_Lights, 3)
    elseif flagActive(9)  then setExclusive(Controls.Stage_Lights, 2)
    else                       setExclusive(Controls.Stage_Lights, 1) end

    -- Fast-path dimmer animation trigger for House/Stage (v1.2.0.11): the
    -- CAI I/O flags above are carried on /rtIoFDetail.xml, which is
    -- prioritized to stay responsive (per explicit preference: flags
    -- should never feel laggy, even if that means lighting is
    -- comparatively worse). House and Stage happen to be the only two
    -- zones with flag-level representation at all -- but they're also the
    -- most commonly the ONLY active zones in practice (a QDC-400 board has
    -- 4 channels, but real installs usually only populate 1-2 with actual
    -- power modules). So for those two zones specifically, we don't have
    -- to wait for the slower /rtLights.xml poll to notice a preset change
    -- and start the local ramp -- this scrape (which is already running at
    -- the fast, prioritized rate) can kick it off immediately.
    --
    -- This is DELIBERATELY decoupled from zoneCurrentPreset/animatePresetChange's
    -- authoritative bookkeeping: zoneFastPreset only ever triggers the
    -- animation early, and is never used for the offset-additive math (see
    -- animateOffsetChange) -- that stays governed exclusively by the
    -- full-fidelity rtLights.xml zsta poll, since Stage's flags can't
    -- distinguish Mid1/Mid2 from None (CAI only exposes Up/Down/None for
    -- Stage). A brief, self-correcting animation toward a possibly-wrong
    -- guess is an acceptable trade per explicit preference for smooth over
    -- momentarily-precise; the real rtLights.xml poll corrects it shortly after.
    if ENABLE_QDC and Controls.Zone_Preset then
      local houseState
      if     flagActive(8) then houseState = 0  -- Up
      elseif flagActive(7) then houseState = 3  -- Mid2
      elseif flagActive(6) then houseState = 2  -- Mid1
      elseif flagActive(5) then houseState = 1  -- Down
      else                       houseState = 4 end  -- None
      if zoneFastPreset[1] ~= nil and houseState ~= zoneFastPreset[1] then
        local curOffset = (Controls.Zone_Offset[1] and Controls.Zone_Offset[1].Value) or 0
        animatePresetChange(1, houseState, curOffset, true)
      end
      zoneFastPreset[1] = houseState

      if qdcZones >= 2 then
        local stageState
        if     flagActive(10) then stageState = 0  -- Up
        elseif flagActive(9)  then stageState = 1  -- Down
        else                        stageState = 4 end  -- None (CAI can't distinguish Mid1/Mid2 for Stage; corrected by the next rtLights.xml poll)
        if zoneFastPreset[2] ~= nil and stageState ~= zoneFastPreset[2] then
          local curOffset2 = (Controls.Zone_Offset[2] and Controls.Zone_Offset[2].Value) or 0
          animatePresetChange(2, stageState, curOffset2, true)
        end
        zoneFastPreset[2] = stageState
      end
    end

    -- Curtain: flags 11=Close, 12=Open
    if     flagActive(12) then setExclusive(Controls.Curtain, 3)
    elseif flagActive(11) then setExclusive(Controls.Curtain, 2)
    else                       setExclusive(Controls.Curtain, 1) end

    -- Masking: flags 13=Flat, 14=Scope, 15=Special
    if     flagActive(15) then setExclusive(Controls.Masking, 4)
    elseif flagActive(14) then setExclusive(Controls.Masking, 3)
    elseif flagActive(13) then setExclusive(Controls.Masking, 2)
    else                       setExclusive(Controls.Masking, 1) end

    -- Lens: flags 16=Flat, 17=Scope, 18=Special
    if     flagActive(18) then setExclusive(Controls.Lens, 4)
    elseif flagActive(17) then setExclusive(Controls.Lens, 3)
    elseif flagActive(16) then setExclusive(Controls.Lens, 2)
    else                       setExclusive(Controls.Lens, 1) end

    -- Sound: flags 20=Aux1, 21=Aux2, 22=Dig1, 23=Dig2, 24=Mono,
    --        26=NonSync, 27=SR, 28=SVA  (25=Mute handled separately)
    if     flagActive(28) then setExclusive(Controls.Sound, 9)
    elseif flagActive(27) then setExclusive(Controls.Sound, 8)
    elseif flagActive(26) then setExclusive(Controls.Sound, 7)
    elseif flagActive(24) then setExclusive(Controls.Sound, 6)
    elseif flagActive(23) then setExclusive(Controls.Sound, 5)
    elseif flagActive(22) then setExclusive(Controls.Sound, 4)
    elseif flagActive(21) then setExclusive(Controls.Sound, 3)
    elseif flagActive(20) then setExclusive(Controls.Sound, 2)
    else                       setExclusive(Controls.Sound, 1) end

    -- Aux Outputs 1-16: flags 29-44
    for i = 1, 16 do
      Controls.Aux_Out[i].Boolean = flagActive(28 + i)
    end

    -- v1.2.0.42: Dig1/Dig2 Power+Video (flags 1-4) are now primarily driven
    -- by RST (see parseStatusRecord/dpMismatch above) -- RST gets these
    -- events near-instantly via the reactive DP/DV re-poll, whereas scrape
    -- only refreshes on its own Scrape_Interval cadence. Scrape still acts
    -- as a backstop: only override the current (RST-set) value once it's
    -- disagreed for TWO CONSECUTIVE scrapes in a row -- a single differing
    -- reading is treated as a possible stale/transitional echo, not yet a
    -- correction (per Steve's explicit design). A fresh RST response resets
    -- the streak back to 0 (see parseStatusRecord).
    local function scrapeCorrectDP(idx, ctl)
      local newVal = flagActive(idx)
      if newVal == ctl.Boolean then
        dpMismatch[idx] = 0
      else
        dpMismatch[idx] = dpMismatch[idx] + 1
        if dpMismatch[idx] >= 2 then
          ctl.Boolean = newVal
          dpMismatch[idx] = 0
        end
      end
    end
    scrapeCorrectDP(1, Controls.Dig1_Power)
    scrapeCorrectDP(2, Controls.Dig1_Video)
    scrapeCorrectDP(3, Controls.Dig2_Power)
    scrapeCorrectDP(4, Controls.Dig2_Video)
    -- Slide (Aux) Projector: unaffected by the above -- no unsolicited
    -- RPT,EVT exists for it (confirmed against the manual's full event
    -- list), so RST offers no faster path here; scrape remains the sole,
    -- unconditional source, exactly as before.
    Controls.Aux_Projector.Boolean = flagActive(19)
    populated.scrape = true
    checkFullyPopulated()
  end

  -- ── QDC-400 Dimmer Lighting: rtLights.xml parser (v1.2) ─────────
  -- Handles both the routine poll (/rtLights.xml, no params) and the
  -- response to a queued command (/rtLights.xml?Zone=...&State=...) --
  -- both return the identical <rtlights> status document, exactly like
  -- the eCNA's own statLightCtrl.htm always routes through showXDoc().
  -- <zofs>/<zsta>/<cact> are always 16 comma-separated values regardless
  -- of how many zones/channels are actually configured; only the first
  -- qdcZones/qdcChannels entries are applied to controls.
  -- Predicts what channel `ch` should currently read, based on its zone's
  -- last known preset + offset (manual §4.3.29/§5.9 additive-override
  -- formula -- same one startChannelAnim/animatePresetChange/animateOffsetChange use). Returns
  -- nil when there isn't enough information yet to have an expectation
  -- (unassigned channel, or preset never observed).
  local function expectedChannelLevel(ch)
    local zone0 = channelZone[ch]
    if zone0 == nil or zone0 < 0 then return nil end
    local zone   = zone0 + 1
    local preset = zoneCurrentPreset[zone]
    if preset == nil then return nil end
    local offset = (Controls.Zone_Offset[zone] and Controls.Zone_Offset[zone].Value) or 0
    local t
    if preset >= 0 and preset <= 3 then
      local base = channelPresetLevel[ch] and channelPresetLevel[ch][preset]
      if not base then return nil end
      t = base + offset
    else -- None: offset is the absolute level (manual §5.9)
      t = offset
    end
    if t < 0 then t = 0 elseif t > 100 then t = 100 end
    return t
  end

  parseLights = function(data)
    local function fi(sub) return string.find(data, sub, 1, true) or 0 end
    local zs, ze = fi("<zofs>"), fi("</zofs>")
    local ss, se = fi("<zsta>"), fi("</zsta>")
    local cs, ce = fi("<cact>"), fi("</cact>")
    if zs == 0 or ze == 0 or ss == 0 or se == 0 or cs == 0 or ce == 0 then return end

    local zofs = csvSplit(string.sub(data, zs+6, ze-1))
    local zsta = csvSplit(string.sub(data, ss+6, se-1))
    local cact = csvSplit(string.sub(data, cs+6, ce-1))

    if Controls.Zone_Offset then
      for i = 1, qdcZones do
        local off = tonumber(zofs[i]) or 0
        local sta = tonumber(zsta[i])

        -- Offset masking: while a user change is pending for this zone, only
        -- accept a polled value once it matches the requested target -- a
        -- moving/settling intermediate value would otherwise make the fader
        -- visibly crawl across several refreshes. See forward-decl comment.
        if offsetPending[i] then
          if off == offsetTarget[i] then
            offsetPending[i] = false
            Controls.Zone_Offset[i].Value = off
            if Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i] then Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i].String = tostring(off) end
          end
          -- else: leave the UI showing the user's requested value (masked)
        else
          Controls.Zone_Offset[i].Value = off
          if Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i] then Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i].String = tostring(off) end
        end

        -- zsta: 0=Up 1=Down 2=Mid1 3=Mid2 4=None; anything else (e.g. before
        -- first command) leaves all 5 preset buttons unlit, matching the
        -- web page's own guard (`if(arZSta[i]<a.length)`).
        if Controls.Zone_Preset then
          local base = (i-1)*5
          if presetPending[i] then
            if sta == presetTarget[i] then
              presetPending[i] = false
              for b = 1, 5 do Controls.Zone_Preset[base+b].Boolean = (b == sta+1) end
            end
            -- else: leave the buttons showing the user's selection (masked)
          else
            for b = 1, 5 do
              Controls.Zone_Preset[base+b].Boolean = (sta ~= nil and sta >= 0 and sta <= 4 and (sta+1) == b)
            end
          end
        end

        -- v1.2.0.29: unified preset+offset change detection. Almost all
        -- real-world changes originate at the eCNA itself (a cinema server
        -- sends it a cue), not at this plugin -- we only find out via this
        -- poll. Skipped entirely while EITHER is still pending our own
        -- command (already animated optimistically at button-press/drag
        -- time -- re-triggering here would just restart that animation
        -- partway through) and on the very first observation of a zone
        -- (zoneCurrentPreset[i] still nil -- no known prior state to fade
        -- from). Combining them matters: if the eCNA changes preset AND
        -- offset together in the same update (e.g. a cue setting both at
        -- once), animating to the bare preset level first and correcting
        -- to the true combined level only once a later poll overwrote it
        -- looked like the meter animating, then popping to a different value.
        if sta ~= nil and sta >= 0 and sta <= 4 and not presetPending[i] and not offsetPending[i] then
          local prevSta = zoneCurrentPreset[i]
          local prevOff = zoneLastOffset[i]
          if prevSta ~= nil then
            if sta ~= prevSta then
              -- Preset changed (offset may have changed in the same update
              -- too) -- combine both into one target, using the PRESET's
              -- own fade time.
              animatePresetChange(i, sta, off, true, prevOff)
            elseif prevOff ~= nil and off ~= prevOff then
              -- Only the offset changed -- use the fixed offset fade time.
              animateOffsetChange(i, off, true)
            end
          end
          zoneCurrentPreset[i] = sta
          zoneLastOffset[i]    = off
        end
      end
    end

    if Controls.Channel_Level then
      for j = 1, qdcChannels do
        local lvl = tonumber(cact[j]) or 0

        -- v1.2.0.11: removed the "2 identical polls = settled, stop
        -- simulating" check that was here. It caused exactly the jumpy
        -- behavior it was meant to prevent: with multiple channels ramping
        -- at once (or even a single channel), a transient/coincidental
        -- repeated poll reading could trust a not-actually-final
        -- intermediate value, snap the meter to it, and then jump again
        -- once a later poll showed the real (different) reading -- "goes
        -- higher then jumps low" / "pops down then pops back up". Per
        -- explicit preference: smooth and eventually-accurate beats
        -- momentarily-accurate and jumpy. The local ramp now runs to its
        -- own computed completion every time, full stop -- the only thing
        -- that still overrides it early is the no-dimmer detection just
        -- below (2 consecutive UNEXPECTED 0% polls), which is a distinct,
        -- narrower signal than "any 2 identical readings".

        -- While locally animating (see startChannelAnim), trust the
        -- simulation over the poll -- the poll is slower than a real fade
        -- and would otherwise make the meter visibly lag/jump. Once the
        -- simulated ramp finishes (on its own clock, or via the settled
        -- check above), channelAnimating[j] clears and live polling
        -- resumes automatically -- that's the "verify/correct our
        -- position" behavior. If a level changes on the poll with no
        -- animation in progress at all (e.g. someone adjusted the offset
        -- directly at the physical unit), it just flows straight through
        -- here at ordinary polling cadence -- there's nothing to predict
        -- in that case, so a less-smooth appearance is expected/fine.
        if channelPendingUnmask[j] then
          -- v1.2.0.41: one-extra-polling-cycle settling guard (Steve's
          -- explicit request). The local ramp is done and the zone-level
          -- pending flag(s) have genuinely cleared, but this transition
          -- involved a non-zero offset at the start or the new position --
          -- real hardware can ack the protocol-level state fields slightly
          -- ahead of the physical dimmer output actually settling to the
          -- new combined level. Skip trusting THIS poll's cact once more;
          -- resume live trust starting with the poll after this one.
          channelPendingUnmask[j] = nil
          channelAnimating[j] = false  -- takes effect for the NEXT parseLights call, not this one
        elseif not channelAnimating[j] then
          -- Dimmer-presence detection: a real 0% reading is expected and
          -- fine (None preset, a preset configured to 0%, or an offset that
          -- clamps to 0) -- only an UNEXPECTED 0% (LUT says it should be
          -- non-zero) counts as evidence the channel isn't really there.
          -- Two such polls in a row => presume no dimmer/power; a single
          -- non-zero reading at any time clears that presumption immediately.
          if lvl == 0 then
            local expected = expectedChannelLevel(j)
            if expected and expected > 0 then
              channelZeroStreak[j] = (channelZeroStreak[j] or 0) + 1
              if channelZeroStreak[j] >= 2 then
                channelNoDimmer[j]  = true
                channelConfirmed[j] = false  -- revoke: we're no longer confident this channel is real
              end
            else
              channelZeroStreak[j] = 0  -- 0% was actually expected -- not a signal of absence
            end
          else
            channelZeroStreak[j] = 0
            channelNoDimmer[j]   = false
            channelConfirmed[j]  = true  -- a genuine non-zero reading is the only thing that lights the LED
          end
          if Controls.Channel_Present and Controls.Channel_Present[j] then
            Controls.Channel_Present[j].Boolean = (channelConfirmed[j] == true)
          end

          Controls.Channel_Level[j].Value = lvl
          if Controls.Channel_Level_Text[j] then Controls.Channel_Level_Text[j].String = string.format("%d%%", lvl) end
        end
      end
    end
    dbg("Lights: " .. #zofs .. " zone offsets, " .. #cact .. " channel levels")
    populated.lightPoll = true
    checkFullyPopulated()
  end

  -- ── nanoHost POS Management Data: rtmandata.xml parser (v1.3) ────
  -- Reference: eCNA-5 statManDataJs.js showXDoc()/arInfo (Steve confirmed
  -- eCNA-5/eCNA-10 share the same CPU and command set, so this is treated
  -- as confirmed, not merely a hint). The real page issues
  -- rtmandata.xml?TimeStamp=<n> and the device may reply with a bare
  -- <UpToDate/> when nothing has changed since that TimeStamp -- we don't
  -- track our own TimeStamp state (always requesting fresh, unparameterized
  -- rtmandata.xml, see httpRequest above), so we should always get a full
  -- <PosData><Stat>...</Stat></PosData> body back, not an <UpToDate/> reply.
  -- If a real capture ever shows otherwise, that's the first thing to
  -- revisit here.
  --
  -- Flags (arInfo type 1): HostUp, PosEna, PosOk, InSho, Sold, Cancel.
  -- Timers (arInfo type 2, MM:SS as total seconds on the wire): RunTim,
  -- BtwTim, BSTim, ASTim, BETim, AETim. Tod is the plain time-of-day clock
  -- string, not a duration.
  --
  -- Only the upper Stat section is parsed in this build -- the lower
  -- variable-row Screen (shows schedule) section is not yet implemented,
  -- see header comment.
  local function xmlTag(data, tag)
    local s = string.find(data, "<"..tag..">", 1, true)
    if not s then return nil end
    local e = string.find(data, "</"..tag..">", s, true)
    if not e then return nil end
    return string.sub(data, s + #tag + 2, e - 1)
  end

  -- Formats a raw seconds value (as the flags/timers appear on the wire,
  -- per the eCNA-5 reference's own `min:sec` conversion in showXDoc()) into
  -- "MM:SS" for the Text controls -- same format the real web page shows.
  local function fmtMinSec(secStr)
    local total = tonumber(secStr)
    if not total then return secStr or "" end
    local m = math.floor(total / 60)
    local s = total - (m * 60)
    return string.format("%d:%02d", m, s)
  end

  -- Sets an LED control's Boolean AND its display Color together --
  -- Green=1 (true/active), Red=0 (false/inactive). Used for every nanoHost
  -- flag except NanoHost_Cancel (see setNanoFlagRev below).
  local function setNanoFlag(ctl, active)
    if not ctl then return end
    ctl.Boolean = active
    ctl.Color = active and "green" or "red"
  end

  -- POS Cancel uses REVERSE logic per Steve's spec: Green=0 (not cancelled),
  -- Red=1 (cancelled) -- the only one of the six flags where "flag true"
  -- means something bad rather than something good/normal.
  local function setNanoFlagRev(ctl, active)
    if not ctl then return end
    ctl.Boolean = active
    ctl.Color = active and "red" or "green"
  end

  -- Placeholder shown for the four extrapolated timer fields before the
  -- first valid poll ever lands, and whenever NanoHost_HostUp is false --
  -- per Steve: "any time the Host Up is not true, the Time counters are not
  -- true either." Never show a numeric value (0:00, or a stale frozen
  -- number) that could be mistaken for real data in either of those states.
  -- Time of Day is intentionally NOT included here -- it's a self-generated
  -- live clock (see state-block comment), always valid regardless of
  -- nanoHost/HostUp state, so it's never blanked.
  local NANO_BLANK = "--:--"

  local function blankNanoTimers()
    if Controls.NanoHost_TimeOfShow        then Controls.NanoHost_TimeOfShow.String        = NANO_BLANK end
    if Controls.NanoHost_TimeBetweenShows  then Controls.NanoHost_TimeBetweenShows.String  = NANO_BLANK end
    if Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeStart   then Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeStart.String   = NANO_BLANK end
    if Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterStart    then Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterStart.String    = NANO_BLANK end
    if Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeEnd     then Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeEnd.String     = NANO_BLANK end
    if Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterEnd      then Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterEnd.String      = NANO_BLANK end
  end

  -- Clamps a raw seconds value into [0, NANO_TIME_MAX] -- applied both when
  -- seeding from a real poll (defensive -- the device is the authority, but
  -- there's no reason to trust an out-of-range value if one ever showed up)
  -- and every local extrapolation tick (where it matters in practice -- see
  -- NANO_TIME_MAX's comment: confirmed the up-counters can otherwise walk
  -- past the device's own observed 255:59 ceiling).
  local function clampNanoSec(v)
    if v < 0 then return 0 end
    if v > NANO_TIME_MAX then return NANO_TIME_MAX end
    return v
  end

  -- ── Show Schedule (v1.3.0.12) ────────────────────────────────────
  -- v1.3.0.13 CRASH FIX: field report -- "3114: bad argument #2 to
  -- '__newindex' (string expected, got table)" -- crashing at plugin
  -- STARTUP (not even waiting for a poll), since blankShowSchedule() runs
  -- unconditionally at startup and hit this same line via the "inactive"
  -- branch too. Root cause: Controls.X.Color apparently only accepts a
  -- STRING at runtime on real Q-SYS hardware, not an RGB table -- the
  -- opposite of what was assumed when picking RGB triples to exactly match
  -- the original page's pink/lime/cyan/yellow/chocolate/orange Key legend
  -- (every OTHER Color assignment in this entire file, going back to v1.2,
  -- has only ever used plain color-name strings like "green"/"red" -- this
  -- was the one place that broke that pattern, without ever having been
  -- verified against real hardware first).
  --
  -- Fix: retreat to "green" for every active marker (the only two string
  -- values -- "green" and "red" -- confirmed extensively safe across this
  -- entire project) rather than guess at more exotic named-color strings
  -- and risk a third crash cycle. This sacrifices the distinct per-marker
  -- hue the real page uses, but the marker LOGIC (which row/column is
  -- active) is unaffected and already verified against Steve's real XML
  -- capture -- only the color richness is reduced, and only until specific
  -- additional color-name strings are confirmed safe on real hardware.
  -- v1.3.0.17: restored the real palette (pink/lime/chocolate/orange for
  -- FS/FE/LS/LE) now that Steve confirmed named string colors work broadly
  -- on real hardware -- not just "green"/"red", and it's specifically RGB
  -- TABLES that don't work, not named strings in general (cyan/yellow/
  -- black all confirmed working for the Now Playing highlight). Same
  -- safe-baseline-then-pcall-upgrade pattern as setHighlightLed: "green"
  -- always succeeds first, then a pcall-wrapped attempt at the real color
  -- -- if pink/lime/chocolate/orange specifically ever turned out not to be
  -- valid, this degrades to green instead of crashing, same lesson as
  -- v1.3.0.13.
  -- v1.3.0.23: FE's inactive color split off from its active color. Steve
  -- confirmed the ACTIVE lime is correct (matches the real page), but
  -- reported the INACTIVE/dimmed lime still looked "almost on" -- vibrant,
  -- not dull -- compared to Cancel's dull green in the same screenshot.
  --
  -- v1.3.0.24: per Steve, ALL FOUR markers' inactive/off color switched to
  -- a uniform dark grey -- active colors (pink/lime/chocolate/orange)
  -- unchanged, already confirmed correct. This supersedes 1.3.0.23's
  -- green-for-FE-only fix with a simpler, uniform "off is off" convention
  -- for the whole marker cluster -- one dull neutral color regardless of
  -- which marker, rather than trying to find a marker-specific muted shade
  -- of each hue.
  --
  -- v1.3.0.25: "darkgray" swapped for "dimgray" -- despite the names,
  -- "dimgray" (rgb 105,105,105) is actually darker/more muted than
  -- "darkgray" (rgb 169,169,169), same naming trap as lime being brighter
  -- than green (see v1.3.0.23's comment above).
  local MARKER_COLOR_ACTIVE = {
    FS = "pink",
    FE = "lime",
    LS = "chocolate",
    LE = "orange",
  }
  local MARKER_COLOR_INACTIVE = {
    FS = "dimgray",
    FE = "dimgray",
    LS = "dimgray",
    LE = "dimgray",
  }
  -- v1.3.0.22: testing THIS ONE feature in isolation, per Steve's explicit
  -- request ("if we want to try ONE thing of the new features... getting
  -- the LED off colors correct... if that blows it up, we know where we
  -- went wrong") -- deliberately not reintroducing anything else from the
  -- 1.3.0.18-20 lineage alongside it. Per Steve's own confirmed observation
  -- that Boolean=false renders as a dimmed/dark version of whatever Color
  -- is currently set (that's how "green" was showing as dark green when
  -- off), setting the marker's OWN target hue regardless of active state --
  -- rather than always resetting to "green" first -- gives each marker a
  -- dark version of its own color when off. "green" remains the ultra-safe
  -- fallback if the specific named color ever fails.
  local function setMarkerLed(ctl, active, colorKey)
    if not ctl then return end
    ctl.Boolean = active
    local palette = active and MARKER_COLOR_ACTIVE or MARKER_COLOR_INACTIVE
    local target = (colorKey and palette[colorKey]) or "green"
    local ok = pcall(function() ctl.Color = target end)
    if not ok then ctl.Color = "green" end
  end

  -- v1.3.0.15: "Now Playing" highlight for the currently-airing performance
  -- (Start/End markers specifically) -- per Steve's request to recreate the
  -- real page's cyan/yellow StartTime/RunTime cell highlighting, using a
  -- safer mechanism: a small LED next to each field that's hidden
  -- (IsInvisible=true) when not applicable, visible when it is, rather than
  -- always-visible-but-dim. Color is set to a KNOWN-SAFE baseline ("green",
  -- confirmed extensively across this project) first -- that assignment
  -- always succeeds -- then a pcall-wrapped attempt is made to upgrade to
  -- the actual requested hue (cyan/yellow). If that specific string isn't
  -- valid on real hardware, the pcall silently swallows the error and the
  -- LED just stays green instead of crashing the plugin a third time.
  local function setHighlightLed(ctl, active, preferredColor)
    if not ctl then return end
    ctl.Boolean = active
    ctl.IsInvisible = not active
    ctl.Color = "green"
    if active then
      pcall(function() ctl.Color = preferredColor end)
    end
  end

  -- v1.3.0.15 EXPERIMENT: attempts to color the StartTime/RunTime TEXT
  -- controls themselves, closer to the real page's actual cell-background
  -- highlight -- per Steve, "let's try to see if we can color the
  -- background on the fly." This is genuinely unverified: it's not known
  -- whether a Text-style control's Color property is even settable at
  -- runtime, or whether it affects foreground text vs. background fill, on
  -- real Q-SYS hardware. Entirely pcall-wrapped so a failure here can never
  -- affect anything else -- the setHighlightLed() indicator LEDs above are
  -- the guaranteed-working mechanism regardless of whether this does
  -- anything visible. Worth reporting back whether this visibly changes
  -- anything on a real Core.
  local function tryExperimentalTextHighlight(ctl, active, preferredColor)
    if not ctl then return end
    pcall(function() ctl.Color = active and preferredColor or "black" end)
  end

  -- Extracts each performance from <Screen>...</Screen> -- confirmed
  -- structure via a real capture: each <StartTime> element carries BOTH its
  -- own direct text (the date/time string) AND child elements (RunTime/
  -- PerfNum/Sold/Cancel/Title). Returns an array in document order, which
  -- matches the 0-based row index the Stat block's FS/FE/Start/End/LS/LE
  -- markers point into.
  local function extractShows(data)
    local shows = {}
    local screenStart = string.find(data, "<Screen>", 1, true)
    local screenEnd    = string.find(data, "</Screen>", 1, true)
    if not screenStart or not screenEnd then return shows end
    local screenBody = string.sub(data, screenStart, screenEnd)

    local pos = 1
    while true do
      local s = string.find(screenBody, "<StartTime>", pos, true)
      if not s then break end
      local e = string.find(screenBody, "</StartTime>", s, true)
      if not e then break end
      local block = string.sub(screenBody, s, e)

      -- Direct text content: everything between "<StartTime>" and the
      -- first child tag, trimmed.
      local afterOpen = #"<StartTime>" + 1
      local nextTagPos = string.find(block, "<", afterOpen, true)
      local dateStr = string.sub(block, afterOpen, nextTagPos and (nextTagPos - 1) or #block)
      dateStr = dateStr:gsub("^%s+", ""):gsub("%s+$", "")

      table.insert(shows, {
        StartTime = dateStr,
        RunTime   = xmlTag(block, "RunTime"),
        PerfNum   = xmlTag(block, "PerfNum"),
        Sold      = xmlTag(block, "Sold"),
        Cancel    = xmlTag(block, "Cancel"),
        Title     = xmlTag(block, "Title"),
      })

      pos = e + 1
    end
    return shows
  end

  -- Blanks a single Show Schedule row -- used both for rows beyond the
  -- actual show count for the day, and (via blankShowSchedule) for the
  -- whole section whenever HostUp is false.
  -- v1.3.0.17: every control belonging to a Show Schedule row, so a whole
  -- row (including its now-real RowNum control) can be shown/hidden
  -- together -- per Steve, cleaner than leaving unused LEDs/boxes visible
  -- for rows with no scheduled performance. NanoHost_Show_Start/End are
  -- deliberately NOT in this list -- their IsInvisible is governed
  -- separately by setHighlightLed() ("is this the currently-airing
  -- performance"), a different, more granular concept than "does this row
  -- have a scheduled performance at all" -- including them here would
  -- unconditionally force them visible whenever the row has data, wiping
  -- out the "only the now-playing row's highlight shows" behavior.
  local ROW_CONTROL_NAMES = {
    "NanoHost_Show_RowNum", "NanoHost_Show_FS", "NanoHost_Show_FE", "NanoHost_Show_LS", "NanoHost_Show_LE",
    "NanoHost_Show_StartTime", "NanoHost_Show_RunTime",
    "NanoHost_Show_PerfNum", "NanoHost_Show_Sold", "NanoHost_Show_Cancel", "NanoHost_Show_Title",
  }
  local function setRowVisible(i, visible)
    for _, name in ipairs(ROW_CONTROL_NAMES) do
      if Controls[name] and Controls[name][i] then
        Controls[name][i].IsInvisible = not visible
      end
    end
  end

  local function blankShowRow(i)
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime and Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime[i] then Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime[i].String = "" end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime   and Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime[i]   then Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime[i].String   = "" end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_PerfNum   and Controls.NanoHost_Show_PerfNum[i]   then Controls.NanoHost_Show_PerfNum[i].String   = "" end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_Title     and Controls.NanoHost_Show_Title[i]     then Controls.NanoHost_Show_Title[i].String     = "" end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_Sold      and Controls.NanoHost_Show_Sold[i]      then setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_Show_Sold[i], false) end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_Cancel    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_Cancel[i]    then setNanoFlagRev(Controls.NanoHost_Show_Cancel[i], false) end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_FS    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_FS[i]    then setMarkerLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_FS[i],    false, "FS") end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_FE    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_FE[i]    then setMarkerLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_FE[i],    false, "FE") end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_LS    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_LS[i]    then setMarkerLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_LS[i],    false, "LS") end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_LE    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_LE[i]    then setMarkerLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_LE[i],    false, "LE") end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_Start and Controls.NanoHost_Show_Start[i] then setHighlightLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_Start[i], false, "cyan") end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_End   and Controls.NanoHost_Show_End[i]   then setHighlightLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_End[i],   false, "yellow") end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime and Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime[i] then tryExperimentalTextHighlight(Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime[i], false, "cyan") end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime   and Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime[i]   then tryExperimentalTextHighlight(Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime[i],   false, "yellow") end
    setRowVisible(i, false)
  end

  local function blankShowSchedule()
    for i = 1, MAX_SHOWS do blankShowRow(i) end
  end

  parseNanoHost = function(data)
    -- If the device ever does reply with <UpToDate/> (see comment above),
    -- there's nothing new to parse -- the local tick extrapolation (if
    -- already valid) just keeps running from where it was rather than being
    -- reset or blanked.
    if string.find(data, "<UpToDate", 1, true) then
      dbg("NanoHost: <UpToDate/> reply, no change since last request")
      populated.nanoHost = true
      return
    end

    -- v1.3.0.28 BUG FIX (field report: "POS Ticket Sold... is staying
    -- true"): xmlTag() finds the FIRST occurrence of "<tag>" anywhere in
    -- the string it's given. Every call below used the FULL response body
    -- (`data`) -- but <Screen> (which comes BEFORE <Stat> in the document)
    -- contains its own per-show <Sold> and <Cancel> tags inside each
    -- <StartTime> block, and those are the exact same tag names the
    -- top-level Stat flags use. So `xmlTag(data, "Sold")` was silently
    -- finding the FIRST show's own per-show Sold value instead of the
    -- real top-level Stat/Sold flag -- and since a day's first performance
    -- is very often already sold by the time you're checking status later
    -- on, POS Ticket Sold would end up pinned true regardless of the
    -- actual live flag. Same latent bug affected NanoHost_Cancel (Stat and
    -- per-show both have a <Cancel> tag) -- masked in testing purely by
    -- coincidence, since both happened to be 0 in every capture used so
    -- far. No other Stat field collides with a per-show tag name (RunTim
    -- vs RunTime, Start vs StartTime, etc. differ enough that the "<tag>"
    -- substring search doesn't cross-match) -- confirmed by checking every
    -- Stat tag against the per-show field set (RunTime/PerfNum/Sold/
    -- Cancel/Title), not just assumed. Fixed by scoping every top-level
    -- lookup below to the <Stat>...</Stat> substring specifically, instead
    -- of the whole document.
    local statStart = string.find(data, "<Stat>", 1, true)
    local statEnd   = string.find(data, "</Stat>", 1, true)
    local statBlock = (statStart and statEnd) and string.sub(data, statStart, statEnd) or data

    local function flag(tag) return xmlTag(statBlock, tag) == "1" end

    -- Flags always reflect ground truth at face value, regardless of
    -- HostUp -- only the TIMERS get blanked/suppressed below, per Steve's
    -- instruction (flags aren't durations, so "not true" doesn't apply the
    -- same way; the HostUp LED itself is exactly what tells the operator
    -- the timers can't be trusted right now).
    if Controls.NanoHost_TicketSold then setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_TicketSold, flag("Sold")) end
    if Controls.NanoHost_InShow     then setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_InShow,     flag("InSho")) end
    if Controls.NanoHost_PosOk      then setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_PosOk,      flag("PosOk")) end
    if Controls.NanoHost_PosEnabled then setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_PosEnabled, flag("PosEna")) end
    if Controls.NanoHost_HostUp     then setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_HostUp,     flag("HostUp")) end
    if Controls.NanoHost_Cancel     then setNanoFlagRev(Controls.NanoHost_Cancel,  flag("Cancel")) end

    nanoHostUp = flag("HostUp")

    if not nanoHostUp then
      -- Host is down: the timers aren't true. Blank them and stop trusting/
      -- extrapolating from whatever numbers this response carried, even if
      -- it did include some -- the tick timer itself also checks
      -- nanoHostUp and won't advance anything while this is false. The Show
      -- Schedule is nanoHost-sourced data too, so it gets the same
      -- treatment (v1.3.0.12).
      blankNanoTimers()
      blankShowSchedule()
      dbg("NanoHost: HostUp=false, timers and show schedule blanked")
      populated.nanoHost = true
      return
    end

    -- Host is up: this is a real, trustworthy dataset -- (re)seed everything
    -- from ground truth. RunTim/BtwTim are displayed as-is (not
    -- extrapolated, see the state-block comment above); BSTim/ASTim/BETim/
    -- AETim additionally seed the raw-second counters the 1Hz tick timer
    -- extrapolates between now and the next poll. Time of Day is NOT read
    -- from this response at all -- see the self-generated clock below.
    if Controls.NanoHost_TimeOfShow then
      local v = xmlTag(statBlock, "RunTim")
      if v then Controls.NanoHost_TimeOfShow.String = fmtMinSec(v) end
    end
    if Controls.NanoHost_TimeBetweenShows then
      local v = xmlTag(statBlock, "BtwTim")
      if v then Controls.NanoHost_TimeBetweenShows.String = fmtMinSec(v) end
    end
    local bs = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "BSTim"))
    if bs then
      nanoBSSec = clampNanoSec(bs)
      if Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeStart then Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeStart.String = fmtMinSec(nanoBSSec) end
    end
    local as_ = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "ASTim"))
    if as_ then
      nanoASSec = clampNanoSec(as_)
      if Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterStart then Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterStart.String = fmtMinSec(nanoASSec) end
    end
    local be = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "BETim"))
    if be then
      nanoBESec = clampNanoSec(be)
      if Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeEnd then Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeEnd.String = fmtMinSec(nanoBESec) end
    end
    local ae = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "AETim"))
    if ae then
      nanoAESec = clampNanoSec(ae)
      if Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterEnd then Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterEnd.String = fmtMinSec(nanoAESec) end
    end

    nanoValid = true  -- only ever set true once we've actually seen a real, HostUp=true dataset

    -- ── Show Schedule (v1.3.0.12) ────────────────────────────────────
    -- Marker indices from Stat -- 0-based row pointers (or a 255 sentinel
    -- meaning "not applicable right now," per Steve's explanation; a plain
    -- equality check against each row's 0-based index handles this
    -- correctly without any special-casing, since 255 can never match a
    -- real row index within MAX_SHOWS=10).
    local fsIdx    = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "FS"))
    local feIdx    = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "FE"))
    local startIdx = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "Start"))
    local endIdx   = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "End"))
    local lsIdx    = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "LS"))
    local leIdx    = tonumber(xmlTag(statBlock, "LE"))

    local shows = extractShows(data)
    for i = 1, MAX_SHOWS do
      local show = shows[i]
      if show then
        local rowIdx0 = i - 1  -- 0-based, matching FS/FE/Start/End/LS/LE
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime and Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime[i] then Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime[i].String = show.StartTime or "" end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime   and Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime[i]   then Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime[i].String   = show.RunTime or "" end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_PerfNum   and Controls.NanoHost_Show_PerfNum[i]   then Controls.NanoHost_Show_PerfNum[i].String   = show.PerfNum or "" end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_Title     and Controls.NanoHost_Show_Title[i]     then Controls.NanoHost_Show_Title[i].String     = show.Title or "" end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_Sold      and Controls.NanoHost_Show_Sold[i]      then setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_Show_Sold[i], show.Sold == "1") end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_Cancel    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_Cancel[i]    then setNanoFlagRev(Controls.NanoHost_Show_Cancel[i], show.Cancel == "1") end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_FS    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_FS[i]    then setMarkerLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_FS[i],    fsIdx    == rowIdx0, "FS") end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_FE    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_FE[i]    then setMarkerLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_FE[i],    feIdx    == rowIdx0, "FE") end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_LS    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_LS[i]    then setMarkerLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_LS[i],    lsIdx    == rowIdx0, "LS") end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_LE    and Controls.NanoHost_Show_LE[i]    then setMarkerLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_LE[i],    leIdx    == rowIdx0, "LE") end
        -- v1.3.0.15: "Now Playing" highlight -- guaranteed-safe indicator
        -- LED (setHighlightLed) plus an experimental attempt to also color
        -- the StartTime/RunTime text itself (tryExperimentalTextHighlight,
        -- pcall-protected -- see its comment).
        local isNowStart = (startIdx == rowIdx0)
        local isNowEnd   = (endIdx   == rowIdx0)
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_Start then setHighlightLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_Start[i], isNowStart, "cyan") end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_End   then setHighlightLed(Controls.NanoHost_Show_End[i],   isNowEnd,   "yellow") end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime then tryExperimentalTextHighlight(Controls.NanoHost_Show_StartTime[i], isNowStart, "cyan") end
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime   then tryExperimentalTextHighlight(Controls.NanoHost_Show_RunTime[i],   isNowEnd,   "yellow") end
        setRowVisible(i, true)
      else
        blankShowRow(i)
      end
    end

    dbg("NanoHost: Sold=" .. tostring(flag("Sold")) .. " InSho=" .. tostring(flag("InSho"))
      .. " PosOk=" .. tostring(flag("PosOk")) .. " PosEna=" .. tostring(flag("PosEna"))
      .. " HostUp=" .. tostring(flag("HostUp")) .. " Cancel=" .. tostring(flag("Cancel"))
      .. " | Show Schedule: " .. #shows .. " performance(s)")
    populated.nanoHost = true
  end

  -- Queue a Zone preset/offset command; capped at 4 in-flight, matching the
  -- eCNA's own web page (`if(CmdBuf.length<4)`) so rapid clicking can't
  -- grow this unbounded.
  queueLightCmd = function(zone0based, state, level, fader)
    if #lightCmdQueue < 4 then
      table.insert(lightCmdQueue, {zone0based, state, level, fader})
      dbg(string.format("Queued light cmd: zone=%d state=%d level=%d fader=%d", zone0based, state, level, fader))
    end
  end

  -- Begin masking Zone_Offset/_Text updates for `zone` (1-based) until the
  -- polled offset matches `v`, or 15s elapses. The generation counter lets a
  -- second change (or a device confirmation) invalidate an older pending
  -- timeout so it doesn't wrongly clear a newer mask.
  beginOffsetPending = function(zone, v)
    offsetPending[zone] = true
    offsetTarget[zone]  = v
    offsetGen[zone] = (offsetGen[zone] or 0) + 1
    local myGen = offsetGen[zone]
    Timer.CallAfter(function()
      if offsetGen[zone] == myGen then offsetPending[zone] = false end
    end, 15)
  end

  -- Begin masking Zone_Preset updates for `zone` (1-based) until the polled
  -- zsta matches `state`, or 15s elapses. Selecting a preset also resets the
  -- zone's offset to 0 on the device (manual §5.9), so this optimistically
  -- shows/masks that too, matching what the eCNA will actually do.
  beginPresetPending = function(zone, state)
    presetPending[zone] = true
    presetTarget[zone]  = state
    presetGen[zone] = (presetGen[zone] or 0) + 1
    local myPGen = presetGen[zone]
    Timer.CallAfter(function()
      if presetGen[zone] == myPGen then presetPending[zone] = false end
    end, 15)

    beginOffsetPending(zone, 0)
    if Controls.Zone_Offset[zone] then Controls.Zone_Offset[zone].Value = 0 end
    if Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[zone] then Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[zone].String = "0" end
  end

  -- ── Local dimmer meter simulation (v1.2.0.9) ────────────────
  -- Begin animating channel `ch` (1-based) from wherever it's currently
  -- displayed toward `target` (0-100%).
  --
  -- Fade model, corrected from field measurement: `fadeSec` is the FULL
  -- TRANSITION DURATION for going from whichever preset was active to the
  -- one being selected now, regardless of how far apart their configured
  -- levels are -- NOT a constant %/second rate as originally assumed.
  -- Measured on the real hardware: Down(0%)->Up(100%) at a 10s configured
  -- rate took ~10-11s, and separately Mid1(50%)->Up(75%) at the SAME 10s
  -- rate ALSO took ~10-11s, even though that's a much shorter distance.
  -- So the ramp's %/sec speed is `distance / fadeSec`, computed fresh for
  -- every transition -- fast for a big jump, slow for a small one, but
  -- both finishing in about the same configured duration.
  --
  -- MTICK below steps channelSimLevel[ch] toward channelSimTarget[ch] at
  -- channelSimRate[ch] %/sec until it arrives, or until parseLights sees 2
  -- consecutive identical live poll readings (device has evidently settled
  -- before our estimate finished) -- whichever comes first -- then hands
  -- back to live polling.
  local MTICK = 0.2  -- animation tick interval, seconds
  -- By the time a change is detected (via HTTP poll or, for House/Stage,
  -- the fast flag scrape) and this animation actually starts, the real
  -- dimmer has typically already been moving for 1-2 seconds -- polling
  -- has inherent lag, we don't find out instantly. Running the full
  -- configured fade time from that late start would finish correspondingly
  -- late; shortening our own animation duration by roughly that same
  -- amount gets it finishing closer to when the real transition actually
  -- completes. This does not change anything sent to the eCNA -- it only
  -- affects how fast our local prediction moves.
  local DETECTION_LAG_COMPENSATION = 2  -- seconds (raised from 1.5s after live-Core field testing showed it tracking well)
  local channelSimLevel = {}  -- channelSimLevel[ch] = current simulated level (float), only meaningful while channelAnimating[ch]
  -- v1.2.0.30: for a SELF-initiated change (button press, fader drag), the
  -- eCNA hasn't actually made the change yet when our local animation
  -- starts -- our own command still has to travel the shared connection,
  -- possibly behind something already in flight. If the local animation's
  -- duration is shorter than that real round trip (most likely for the
  -- ~0.5s instant/None floor, but possible for any short fade), the
  -- channel unmasks and trusts live polling again before the eCNA has
  -- actually confirmed anything -- a poll that predates our command shows
  -- the OLD value, then our real confirmation arrives and corrects it:
  -- meter pops to old, then pops back. This is NOT a risk for a
  -- poll/flag-detected change, since the confirmation IS the detection --
  -- there's nothing else to wait for in that case.
  -- channelWaitZone/channelWaitKind track, for a self-initiated animation
  -- only, which zone-level pending flag (presetPending/offsetPending) must
  -- ALSO clear before the channel is allowed to trust live polls again --
  -- the local animation reaching its target just holds there, still
  -- masked, until real confirmation (or that flag's own 15s failsafe) says so.
  local channelWaitZone = {}  -- channelWaitZone[ch] = zone number to check, or nil (poll/flag-detected changes don't set this)
  local channelWaitKind = {}  -- channelWaitKind[ch] = "preset" or "offset" -- which pending flag to check for that zone

  -- v1.2.0.41: two related fixes for Steve's report that the jump-to-old-
  -- value symptom persists more broadly than the None-specific case, and
  -- that a combined preset+offset change seemed to animate at the
  -- offset's fixed rate instead of the preset's configured rate.
  --
  -- The fade-rate question traced out as already correct in code (the
  -- unified detection in parseLights already uses the preset's own fade
  -- whenever the preset changes, even if the offset changes alongside it
  -- -- confirmed via targeted reproduction). The broader jump-back,
  -- though, is real: beginPresetPending ALWAYS also resets the zone's
  -- offset to 0 (manual sec 5.9), setting BOTH presetPending[zone] AND
  -- offsetPending[zone] true -- but a preset-tagged channel wait
  -- (channelWaitKind[ch] == "preset") only ever checked presetPending,
  -- never offsetPending. Real hardware typically acks the preset state
  -- field (zsta) almost immediately -- well before the physical dimmer
  -- finishes its multi-second fade, and often before the offset has
  -- genuinely re-settled to 0 either. That let the channel unmask the
  -- instant our own local ramp finished, even though offsetPending was
  -- still genuinely pending -- the next poll's still-transitional cact
  -- reading would flow straight through and pop the meter back.
  --
  -- Fix 1 (below, in startChannelAnim's guard and meterTimer's stillPending
  -- check): for a "preset" wait, require BOTH presetPending[zone] AND
  -- offsetPending[zone] to clear, not just presetPending -- matching what
  -- beginPresetPending actually does.
  --
  -- Fix 2 (Steve's explicit follow-up request): even once both zone-level
  -- flags genuinely clear and our own local ramp is done, don't trust the
  -- very first live poll that arrives -- wait one more full polling cycle.
  -- This absorbs the residual gap where the protocol-level state fields
  -- confirm slightly ahead of the physical dimmer output actually
  -- settling. Applies whenever the transition involved an offset, either
  -- at the start (a non-zero offset was active/being cleared) or at the
  -- new position (the target itself has a non-zero offset component) --
  -- not to plain preset-to-preset moves with no offset in play at all,
  -- which stay exactly as responsive as before. (channelInvolvesOffset and
  -- channelPendingUnmask themselves are declared earlier, alongside
  -- channelAnimating -- parseLights, defined before this point in the
  -- file, needs them as upvalues; see the comment there.)

  -- Clears every queued command and every learned assumption about the
  -- connected device. Called from Controls.IP_ADDRESS.EventHandler whenever
  -- the target actually changes -- without this, a command queued while
  -- pointed at one unit (e.g. an unreachable test address) sits in
  -- lightCmdQueue/nameQueue until connectivity resumes, then gets sent with
  -- TOP priority to whatever unit that turns out to be, even if it's a
  -- completely different physical device. Likewise, zone names, channel
  -- assignments, preset level/fade tables, and dimmer-presence assumptions
  -- all persist as plain Lua state across a reconnect unless explicitly
  -- cleared here.
  resetForNewTarget = function()
    -- Queues: discard outright -- nothing in them is valid for a new target
    lightCmdQueue = {}
    nameQueue     = {}

    -- Population tracking: none of it is valid for a new target either --
    -- Status must not read "OK" again until everything has freshly
    -- responded from whichever unit we're now connecting to. Full reset
    -- (both CAI and HTTP sides) -- unlike connect()'s own CAI-only reset
    -- (v1.2.0.32), an actual target change really does invalidate
    -- previously-fetched HTTP data too (names, dimmer setup, LIN scan,
    -- scrape all belonged to the OLD unit). connect(), called right after
    -- this by every caller, only re-does the CAI half on top -- but
    -- resetting fully here too means the display is already correct even
    -- before connect() runs.
    resetPopulationTracking()

    -- HTTP connection: force a clean reconnect rather than letting a stale
    -- in-flight request resolve against the old address, or a queued
    -- request go out to the new one before we've reset everything else
    if httpConnected then httpSock:Disconnect() end
    httpConnected    = false
    httpBusy         = false
    currentReqType   = "SCRAPE"
    currentApplyFn   = nil
    routineTicks     = 0  -- v1.2.0.41: fresh target restarts the LIGHTPOLL countdown from zero
    nanoTicks        = 0  -- v1.3: fresh target restarts the NANOHOST countdown from zero

    -- Learned dimmer configuration/state -- all specific to whichever unit
    -- we were last actually talking to
    zoneNames          = {}
    channelZone        = {}
    channelPresetLevel = {}
    channelPresetFade  = {}
    zoneCurrentPreset  = {}
    zoneFastPreset     = {}
    channelAnimating   = {}
    channelSimTarget   = {}
    channelSimRate     = {}
    channelSimLevel    = {}
    channelZeroStreak  = {}
    channelNoDimmer    = {}
    channelConfirmed   = {}
    channelInvolvesOffset = {}
    channelPendingUnmask  = {}
    qdcBoardCount      = nil
    offsetPending = {}; offsetTarget = {}; offsetGen = {}; offsetDebounceGen = {}
    presetPending = {}; presetTarget = {}; presetGen = {}

    -- Blank the visible controls too, so nothing from the previous unit
    -- lingers on screen during the reconnect window
    if Controls.Zone_Name then
      for i = 1, qdcZones do
        if Controls.Zone_Name[i] then
          Controls.Zone_Name[i].String = (i == 1 and "House") or (i == 2 and "Stage") or ("Zone "..i)
        end
      end
    end
    if Controls.Zone_Preset then
      for i = 1, #Controls.Zone_Preset do Controls.Zone_Preset[i].Boolean = false end
    end
    if Controls.Zone_Offset then
      for i = 1, qdcZones do
        Controls.Zone_Offset[i].Value = 0
        if Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i] then Controls.Zone_Offset_Text[i].String = "0" end
      end
    end
    if Controls.Channel_Level then
      for j = 1, qdcChannels do
        Controls.Channel_Level[j].Value = 0
        if Controls.Channel_Level_Text[j] then Controls.Channel_Level_Text[j].String = "" end
        if Controls.Channel_Zone[j]  then Controls.Channel_Zone[j].String = "" end
        if Controls.Channel_Present[j] then Controls.Channel_Present[j].Boolean = false end
      end
    end
    if Controls.QDC_Board_Count then Controls.QDC_Board_Count.String = "" end

    dbg("Reset all learned state and queues for new target")
  end

  -- v1.2.0.41: `waitZone`'s "is the self-initiated wait for this channel
  -- still genuinely live" question now has to check BOTH presetPending and
  -- offsetPending whenever the wait is preset-tagged, because
  -- beginPresetPending always sets both (selecting a preset resets the
  -- zone's offset to 0 on the real device, manual sec 5.9) -- checking only
  -- presetPending left a gap where the offset side was still genuinely
  -- pending confirmation. An offset-tagged wait only ever set offsetPending
  -- to begin with, so it alone is still the right (and only) check there.
  local function selfInitWaitLive(ch)
    local waitZone = channelWaitZone[ch]
    if not waitZone then return false end
    if channelWaitKind[ch] == "preset" then
      return presetPending[waitZone] or offsetPending[waitZone]
    elseif channelWaitKind[ch] == "offset" then
      return offsetPending[waitZone]
    end
    return false
  end

  -- v1.2.0.41: route every place that would otherwise unmask a channel
  -- (clear channelAnimating) through here. Per Steve's explicit request,
  -- once the local ramp is done and the zone-level flag(s) have genuinely
  -- cleared, a channel whose transition involved a non-zero offset at
  -- either end still doesn't trust the very next live poll -- real
  -- hardware can ack the protocol-level state fields slightly ahead of the
  -- physical dimmer output actually settling. That one extra poll is
  -- skipped (channelPendingUnmask, consumed once in parseLights), then
  -- trust resumes normally. Transitions with no offset involved at all
  -- (offset was 0 before and after) unmask immediately, exactly as before.
  local function finishChannelWait(ch)
    channelWaitZone[ch] = nil
    if channelInvolvesOffset[ch] then
      channelPendingUnmask[ch] = true  -- consumed by parseLights; channelAnimating stays true for now
    else
      channelAnimating[ch] = false
    end
  end

  startChannelAnim = function(ch, target, fadeSec, applyCompensation, zone, kind, involvesOffset)
    if target < 0 then target = 0 elseif target > 100 then target = 100 end
    if channelNoDimmer[ch] and target > 0 then
      -- We've seen 2+ unexpected 0% polls for this channel while expecting
      -- non-zero -- presumed no dimmer/power. Don't optimistically animate
      -- toward a target we don't believe will actually happen; that's
      -- exactly the ramp/reset/ramp/reset cycle this feature exists to
      -- avoid. Leave the meter at 0 (what the live poll has been showing)
      -- and let the next real non-zero poll be what clears the presumption.
      channelAnimating[ch] = false
      channelWaitZone[ch] = nil
      channelPendingUnmask[ch] = nil
      if Controls.Channel_Level[ch] then Controls.Channel_Level[ch].Value = 0 end
      if Controls.Channel_Level_Text[ch] then Controls.Channel_Level_Text[ch].String = "0%" end
      return
    end
    local start = Controls.Channel_Level[ch] and Controls.Channel_Level[ch].Value or target
    local distance = math.abs(target - start)

    -- v1.2.0.41 fix (extended in v1.2.0.36 via selfInitWaitLive, see above):
    -- v1.2.0.31 added a guard against a poll/flag-detected call
    -- (applyCompensation=true) landing on top of a still-active
    -- self-initiated wait (v1.2.0.30) -- but only inside the `distance==0`
    -- branch below. Steve confirmed the exact same symptom still happens
    -- for a self-initiated None press when a non-zero offset is active:
    -- turns out the redundant fast-path call (House/Stage flags detecting
    -- the same None transition, ~2s cycle) doesn't reliably land AFTER our
    -- own floor-clamped ~0.5s ramp has already reached 0 -- it can just as
    -- easily land WHILE that ramp is still mid-flight (distance ~= 0),
    -- which falls through to the *general* ramp-setup path further below.
    -- That path's own `else` clause unconditionally set
    -- `channelWaitZone[ch] = nil` whenever applyCompensation was true, with
    -- no check for a still-active self-initiated wait -- the identical bug,
    -- just unreachable by the v1.2.0.31 fix because it only patched the
    -- distance==0 case. Moving the check up here, before the distance==0
    -- branch, covers BOTH cases with one guard: a poll/flag-detected call
    -- that finds a self-initiated wait still genuinely pending (confirmed
    -- via the zone-level presetPending/offsetPending flag, not just the
    -- presence of channelWaitZone) is ignored outright -- no writes, no
    -- state changes -- regardless of whether it happened to arrive before
    -- or after our own ramp reached its target. Only real device
    -- confirmation (checked every meterTimer tick once the ramp reaches
    -- target) or that flag's own 15s failsafe may end the mask; the two
    -- calls compose, with the self-initiated one owning the mask lifecycle
    -- for its own animation's entire duration, not just its final instant.
    if applyCompensation and selfInitWaitLive(ch) then
      return -- ignored entirely -- the self-initiated ramp already in progress owns this channel
    end

    channelInvolvesOffset[ch] = involvesOffset and true or false

    if distance == 0 then
      -- Genuinely already showing the target -- either this is the
      -- self-initiated call itself (a fresh button press/drag landing
      -- exactly on the already-displayed value), or it's poll/flag-detected
      -- with no self-initiated wait in progress (the guard above already
      -- intercepted the case where one WAS still live). Still routed
      -- through finishChannelWait: if this transition involved an offset,
      -- the one-extra-poll-cycle settling guard still applies even though
      -- there's no distance to ramp -- a stale in-flight poll response
      -- could otherwise still carry a transitional reading for the offset
      -- side.
      channelSimLevel[ch]  = target
      channelSimTarget[ch] = target
      channelSimRate[ch]   = 0
      channelAnimating[ch] = true
      if Controls.Channel_Level[ch] then Controls.Channel_Level[ch].Value = target end
      if Controls.Channel_Level_Text[ch] then Controls.Channel_Level_Text[ch].String = string.format("%d%%", target) end
      finishChannelWait(ch)
      return
    end
    -- v1.2.0.18 fix: even an "instant" target (no fade data, e.g. None,
    -- which passes fadeSec=nil) now runs a brief floor-clamped animation
    -- rather than truly bypassing the system. The bypass was a real race:
    -- setting channelAnimating=false immediately opened a window where an
    -- HTTP response already in flight *before* this command was sent
    -- (single connection -- only one request outstanding at a time) could
    -- arrive carrying the OLD level, get applied straight through (since
    -- nothing was masking it), and briefly show the wrong value before our
    -- own command's response corrected it moments later -- meter pops back
    -- up, then pops back down. Keeping channelAnimating=true, even for
    -- just the ~0.5s floor, closes that window the same way every other
    -- transition is already protected.
    --
    -- v1.2.0.29 fix: DETECTION_LAG_COMPENSATION only makes sense for a
    -- change we found out about *late*, via polling -- there's no lag to
    -- compensate for when the change is our own button press or fader
    -- drag; we know about it instantly. Applying the compensation
    -- unconditionally made self-initiated offset changes (fixed 3s fade)
    -- finish roughly 2/3 early, unmasking the channel while the real
    -- device was still genuinely mid-transition -- the next live poll
    -- would then report the real, still-low level, popping the meter back
    -- down before a later poll finally showed the correct settled value.
    local effectiveFadeSec = fadeSec or 0
    if applyCompensation then
      effectiveFadeSec = effectiveFadeSec - DETECTION_LAG_COMPENSATION
    end
    if effectiveFadeSec < 0.5 then effectiveFadeSec = 0.5 end  -- floor: also covers explicit 0s and instant (nil) fades
    channelSimLevel[ch]  = start
    channelSimTarget[ch] = target
    channelSimRate[ch]   = distance / effectiveFadeSec  -- %/sec; VARIES per transition so the whole thing takes ~effectiveFadeSec seconds regardless of distance
    channelAnimating[ch] = true
    channelPendingUnmask[ch] = nil  -- v1.2.0.41: a fresh animation invalidates any leftover grace state from a prior one
    -- v1.2.0.30: for a self-initiated change (applyCompensation false),
    -- remember which zone-level pending flag must ALSO clear before this
    -- channel is allowed to trust live polls again -- our own local
    -- animation reaching its target doesn't mean the eCNA has actually
    -- confirmed anything yet. Poll/flag-detected changes (applyCompensation
    -- true) don't need this -- the confirmation IS the detection. Safe to
    -- clear unconditionally here (v1.2.0.41): the one case that made this
    -- unsafe -- a poll/flag-detected call landing on a still-live
    -- self-initiated wait -- is already intercepted and returned early,
    -- above, before either branch of this function body runs at all.
    if not applyCompensation and zone and kind then
      channelWaitZone[ch] = zone
      channelWaitKind[ch] = kind
    else
      channelWaitZone[ch] = nil
    end
  end

  -- v1.2.0.10 correction: field testing revealed the opposite of what was
  -- assumed in v1.2.0.9. None is essentially INSTANT ("as fast as the UI
  -- can update") when selected from any other preset. The ~3s that WAS
  -- attributed to None is actually the Offset control's own fade time --
  -- moving the offset takes ~3s to reach its new level from ANY preset,
  -- including None. So preset-button transitions (Up/Down/Mid1/Mid2) still
  -- use their configured Setup: QDC-400 Dimmers fade time, None-via-button
  -- is instant, and ANY offset adjustment (regardless of active preset)
  -- uses a fixed ~3s -- never the active preset's own fade time.
  local NONE_FADE_SECONDS   = nil  -- None (via preset button) has no configured fade data; startChannelAnim now floors this to a brief ~0.5s animation rather than a true instant bypass (see v1.2.0.18 fix), which still feels effectively immediate but closes a stale-poll race
  local OFFSET_FADE_SECONDS = 3    -- fixed duration for ANY offset change, field-measured ~3s, regardless of active preset

  -- Trigger local animation for every channel assigned to `zone` (1-based)
  -- for a PRESET BUTTON press or a poll-detected external preset change
  -- (Up/Down/Mid1/Mid2/None). `offsetVal` is the offset to combine with the
  -- new preset's level -- 0 for a fresh button press (manual §5.9: offset
  -- resets to 0 on a new preset selection), but the CURRENT offset when a
  -- poll detects the eCNA changed preset and offset together in the same
  -- update (e.g. a cinema server cue setting both at once) -- otherwise
  -- the channel would animate to the bare preset level first and only
  -- correct to the true combined level once a later poll overwrote it.
  -- `applyCompensation` should be true only for changes detected via
  -- polling or the fast flag-scrape path -- never for our own button press.
  -- `priorOffset` (v1.2.0.41): whatever offset was active immediately
  -- before this transition began, if known -- used only to decide whether
  -- the one-extra-poll-cycle settling guard applies (see
  -- channelInvolvesOffset above); defaults to offsetVal itself when not
  -- given (the fast-path caller has no separate "prior" signal).
  animatePresetChange = function(zone, presetState, offsetVal, applyCompensation, priorOffset)
    offsetVal = offsetVal or 0
    if priorOffset == nil then priorOffset = offsetVal end
    local involvesOffset = (offsetVal ~= 0) or (priorOffset ~= 0)
    local zone0 = zone - 1
    for ch = 1, qdcChannels do
      if channelZone[ch] == zone0 then
        if presetState ~= nil and presetState >= 0 and presetState <= 3 then
          local base = channelPresetLevel[ch] and channelPresetLevel[ch][presetState]
          local fade = channelPresetFade[ch] and channelPresetFade[ch][presetState]
          if base then
            startChannelAnim(ch, base + offsetVal, fade, applyCompensation, zone, "preset", involvesOffset)
          end
        else -- None: instant, absolute offset value (no preset level to add to)
          startChannelAnim(ch, offsetVal, NONE_FADE_SECONDS, applyCompensation, zone, "preset", involvesOffset)
        end
      end
    end
  end

  -- Trigger local animation for every channel assigned to `zone` (1-based)
  -- for an OFFSET adjustment (fader/text box, or a poll-detected external
  -- offset-only change). Manual §4.3.29/§5.9: offset is additive on top of
  -- the active preset's configured level (Up/Down/Mid1/Mid2), or the
  -- absolute level directly when the active preset is None -- but unlike a
  -- preset button press, this ALWAYS uses OFFSET_FADE_SECONDS, never the
  -- active preset's own configured fade time. `applyCompensation` should be
  -- true only for a poll-detected change -- never for our own fader drag
  -- or text box commit.
  animateOffsetChange = function(zone, offsetVal, applyCompensation)
    local zone0  = zone - 1
    local preset = zoneCurrentPreset[zone]
    for ch = 1, qdcChannels do
      if channelZone[ch] == zone0 then
        local target
        if preset ~= nil and preset >= 0 and preset <= 3 then
          local base = channelPresetLevel[ch] and channelPresetLevel[ch][preset]
          if base then target = base + offsetVal end
        else
          target = offsetVal  -- None (or not yet known): offset is the absolute level
        end
        if target then
          -- v1.2.0.41: this is by definition an offset change -- always
          -- treated as "involves offset" for the one-extra-poll-cycle
          -- settling guard, regardless of whether offsetVal itself happens
          -- to be 0 (e.g. dragging back down to 0 still means we started
          -- with a non-zero offset a moment ago).
          startChannelAnim(ch, target, OFFSET_FADE_SECONDS, applyCompensation, zone, "offset", true)
        end
      end
    end
  end

  -- Animation tick: advances every currently-animating channel toward its
  -- target by (rate * MTICK)%, clamped so it can't overshoot. Runs
  -- continuously at a fixed interval (no wall-clock dependency) whenever
  -- QDC lighting is enabled; cheap no-op when nothing is animating.
  if ENABLE_QDC then
    meterTimer = Timer.New()
    meterTimer.EventHandler = function()
      for ch = 1, qdcChannels do
        if channelAnimating[ch] then
          local cur    = channelSimLevel[ch]
          local target = channelSimTarget[ch]
          local step   = (channelSimRate[ch] or 20) * MTICK
          if cur < target then
            cur = math.min(target, cur + step)
          elseif cur > target then
            cur = math.max(target, cur - step)
          end
          channelSimLevel[ch] = cur
          if Controls.Channel_Level[ch] then Controls.Channel_Level[ch].Value = cur end
          if Controls.Channel_Level_Text[ch] then Controls.Channel_Level_Text[ch].String = string.format("%d%%", math.floor(cur + 0.5)) end
          -- v1.2.0.41: once channelPendingUnmask[ch] is set, this channel is
          -- purely waiting on parseLights to consume its one-extra-poll-
          -- cycle grace (see finishChannelWait) -- nothing left for this
          -- tick to decide (cur/target already both parked at the same
          -- value), and re-running the checks below would just clear
          -- channelAnimating on the very next tick, defeating the guard
          -- before a single live poll even has a chance to arrive.
          if cur == target and not channelPendingUnmask[ch] then
            local waitZone = channelWaitZone[ch]
            if waitZone then
              -- Self-initiated change: our local prediction has arrived at
              -- the target, but that doesn't mean the eCNA has actually
              -- confirmed it yet -- keep masking (parked at target) until
              -- the real zone-level pending flag(s) clear, which happens
              -- either on genuine confirmation or their own 15s failsafe.
              if not selfInitWaitLive(ch) then
                finishChannelWait(ch)  -- confirmed (or failsafe expired) -- may unmask now, or defer one more poll cycle if this transition involved an offset
              end
              -- else: stay masked, still parked at target, check again next tick
            else
              finishChannelWait(ch)  -- poll/flag-detected change -- ramp complete -- may unmask now, or defer one more poll cycle if this transition involved an offset
            end
          end
        end
      end
      meterTimer:Start(MTICK)
    end
    meterTimer:Start(MTICK)
  end

  -- v1.3: nanoHost timer extrapolation tick. Runs continuously at a fixed
  -- 1-second interval (no wall-clock dependency, same style as meterTimer
  -- above) whenever nanoHost is enabled. Two independent things happen here:
  -- (1) the four extrapolated counters, guarded exactly as before (no-op
  -- until valid, frozen/blanked while HostUp is false), now clamped to
  -- NANO_TIME_MAX so they can never exceed the device's own observed
  -- ceiling; (2) Time of Day, which is NOT gated by nanoValid/HostUp at all
  -- -- it's the Q-SYS Core's own clock (see state-block comment), always
  -- live regardless of nanoHost connectivity.
  --
  -- v1.3.0.4 BUG FIX: ASTim/AETim were ticking up independently of whether
  -- their own BSTim/BETim counterpart had actually reached 0 -- confirmed
  -- against a real side-by-side capture showing the device itself holding
  -- Time After Start at 0:00 while Time Before Start was still counting
  -- down (98:02), i.e. the "after" counter for a given event does not start
  -- moving until the matching "before" counter reaches 0. Ticking both
  -- independently let ASTim drift to a nonsensical nonzero value (2:21)
  -- while BSTim was still nonzero (98:03) -- a real device could never
  -- report that combination. Fixed by gating each up-counter's tick on its
  -- own down-counter having already reached exactly 0.
  --
  -- v1.3.0.27: forces an early nanoHost refresh, reusing httpRequest()'s
  -- existing NANOHOST poll tier (forcing nanoTicks straight to
  -- nanoPollEveryNTicks makes a fetch immediately due on the next check) --
  -- shared by both the Time Before Feature Start and Time Before Feature
  -- End triggers below.
  --
  -- v1.3.0.29: delay reduced from 5s to 4s, per Steve.
  --
  -- v1.3.0.32: delay reduced from 4s to 3s, per Steve.
  local function forceEarlyNanoHostRefresh(reason)
    Timer.CallAfter(function()
      nanoTicks = nanoPollEveryNTicks
    end, 3)
    dbg("NanoHost: " .. reason .. " -- forcing an early flag refresh in 3s")
  end

  if ENABLE_NANOHOST then
    nanoTickTimer = Timer.New()
    nanoTickTimer.EventHandler = function()
      if nanoValid and nanoHostUp then
        -- Check BEFORE decrementing -- the crossover tick (where BSTim/BETim
        -- reaches exactly 0) must show its own counter at 0:00 without
        -- ASTim/AETim already having jumped to 0:01 in that same tick; the
        -- "after" counter starts moving on the tick AFTER its "before"
        -- counterpart first reads 0, not the same one.
        local beforeStartWasZero = (nanoBSSec == 0)
        local beforeEndWasZero   = (nanoBESec == 0)
        -- v1.3.0.27: per Steve, 255:59 (NANO_TIME_MAX) on a "before" counter
        -- means the eCNA has no real countdown data yet -- NOT a genuine
        -- "255 minutes 59 seconds until this happens" duration. Ticking it
        -- down from there would fabricate a countdown that isn't real, so
        -- BSTim/BETim are frozen at the sentinel instead of decrementing
        -- whenever they're already sitting at it -- they'll only start
        -- counting down once an actual poll provides a real value below
        -- the sentinel. This also correctly keeps ASTim/AETim from ever
        -- starting either, since their own gating already depends on
        -- BSTim/BETim reaching exactly 0, which now can't happen from a
        -- frozen sentinel. The up-counters themselves are UNCHANGED -- they
        -- still count up and cap AT the sentinel as their normal ceiling
        -- (see clampNanoSec), never freeze.
        if nanoBSSec < NANO_TIME_MAX then
          nanoBSSec = clampNanoSec(nanoBSSec - NANO_TICK)
        end
        if beforeStartWasZero then nanoASSec = clampNanoSec(nanoASSec + NANO_TICK) end
        if nanoBESec < NANO_TIME_MAX then
          nanoBESec = clampNanoSec(nanoBESec - NANO_TICK)
        end
        if beforeEndWasZero then nanoAESec = clampNanoSec(nanoAESec + NANO_TICK) end
        if Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeStart then Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeStart.String = fmtMinSec(nanoBSSec) end
        if Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterStart  then Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterStart.String  = fmtMinSec(nanoASSec) end
        if Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeEnd   then Controls.NanoHost_TimeBeforeEnd.String   = fmtMinSec(nanoBESec) end
        if Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterEnd    then Controls.NanoHost_TimeAfterEnd.String    = fmtMinSec(nanoAESec) end
        -- v1.3.0.26/27: force an early nanoHost flag refresh around feature
        -- start/end, per Steve. Trigger point is each "before" counter
        -- reaching 0:01 (one tick before its real 0:00 crossover) rather
        -- than 0:00 itself, specifically because BSTim/BETim floor at 0 and
        -- STAY there -- checking "== 0" would fire on every single tick for
        -- as long as the feature remains in progress, not just once. "== 1"
        -- only occurs on exactly one tick per countdown (a strictly
        -- decreasing count can only equal 1 once before settling at 0), so
        -- this needs no separate one-shot guard/flag.
        if nanoBSSec == 1 then
          forceEarlyNanoHostRefresh("Time Before Feature Start reached 0:01")
        end
        if nanoBESec == 1 then
          forceEarlyNanoHostRefresh("Time Before Feature End reached 0:01")
        end
      end
      -- else: leave whatever parseNanoHost last displayed (blanked, if
      -- invalid/HostUp-false) exactly as it is -- nothing to extrapolate.
      if Controls.NanoHost_TimeOfDay then
        Controls.NanoHost_TimeOfDay.String = os.date("%m/%d/%Y %H:%M:%S")
      end
      nanoTickTimer:Start(NANO_TICK)
    end
    nanoTickTimer:Start(NANO_TICK)
  end

  -- HTTP socket handler: accumulates response, parses on close
  httpSock.EventHandler = function(sock, evt, err)
    if evt == TcpSocket.Events.Connected then
      httpConnected = true
      httpBuf = ""
      httpRequest()  -- send immediately on connect, identical to v1.0.0
    elseif evt == TcpSocket.Events.Data then
      httpBuf = httpBuf .. sock:Read(sock.BufferLength)
    elseif evt == TcpSocket.Events.Closed
        or evt == TcpSocket.Events.Reconnect
        or evt == TcpSocket.Events.Error then
      httpConnected = false
      httpBusy      = false
      dbg("HTTP Closed: buf=" .. #httpBuf .. " bytes, currentReqType=" .. currentReqType)
      if #httpBuf > 0 then
        local bodyStart = httpBuf:find("\r\n\r\n")
        if not bodyStart then bodyStart = httpBuf:find("\n\n") end
        if bodyStart then
          local body = httpBuf:sub(bodyStart + 4)
          if currentReqType == "NAME" then
            local ok, serr = pcall(function() currentApplyFn(body) end)
            if not ok then
              dbg("Name parse error: " .. (serr or "unknown"))
            end
            currentApplyFn = nil
          elseif currentReqType == "LIGHTCMD" then
            local ok, serr = pcall(parseLights, body)
            if not ok then dbg("Light cmd parse error: "..(serr or "")) end
          elseif currentReqType == "LIGHTPOLL" then
            local ok, serr = pcall(parseLights, body)
            if not ok then dbg("Light poll parse error: "..(serr or "")) end
          elseif currentReqType == "NANOHOST" then
            local ok, serr = pcall(parseNanoHost, body)
            if not ok then dbg("NanoHost parse error: "..(serr or "")) end
          else -- "SCRAPE"
            local ok, serr = pcall(scrape, body)
            if not ok then dbg("Scrape parse error: "..(serr or "")) end
          end
        else
          dbg("HTTP: body separator not found in " .. #httpBuf .. " bytes")
        end
        httpBuf = ""
      end
      -- Restart scrapeTimer from NOW so interval is measured from end of response
      scrapeTimer:Start(SCRAPE_RATE)
    end
  end

  -- Scrape timer: triggers HTTP request at SCRAPE_RATE interval
  scrapeTimer.EventHandler = function()
    local ok, err = pcall(httpRequest)
    if not ok then dbg("Scrape error: "..(err or "")) end
  end

  -- ── Startup ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
  -- Initialise legends, set defaults, start timers, connect
  Controls.Set_Program.Choices = {'1','2','3','4','5','6','7','8','9'}
  if Controls.TCP_PORT.String == "" then
    Controls.TCP_PORT.String = tostring(TCP_PORT)
  end
  for idx, name in ipairs(InFlagNames) do
    if Controls.Inputs[idx] then Controls.Inputs[idx].Legend = name end
  end
  if Controls.Macros then
    -- Macro button legends intentionally not set (text labels above buttons used instead)
  end
  -- Aux_Out button legends intentionally not set (text labels above buttons used instead)
  if Controls.Zone_Name then
    -- House/Stage are fixed (zones 1-2); Zone 3+ default until fetched from Setup.xml PgIdx=13
    if Controls.Zone_Name[1] then Controls.Zone_Name[1].String = "House" end
    if Controls.Zone_Name[2] then Controls.Zone_Name[2].String = "Stage" end
    for i = 3, qdcZones do
      if Controls.Zone_Name[i] then Controls.Zone_Name[i].String = "Zone "..i end
    end
  end
  -- v1.3: nanoHost LEDs start Red (unknown/not-yet-polled reads as inactive)
  -- except Cancel, whose reverse logic makes "unknown" correctly show Green
  -- (not cancelled) rather than a false Red "cancelled" alarm before the
  -- first real poll ever lands. The four extrapolated timers start blanked
  -- -- see blankNanoTimers' comment -- nanoValid is still false at this
  -- point, so nothing ticks yet. Time of Day is NOT blanked -- it's the
  -- Core's own clock, so it's correct from the very first tick regardless
  -- of nanoHost/connection state; nanoTickTimer below refreshes it every
  -- second from here on.
  if ENABLE_NANOHOST then
    setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_TicketSold, false)
    setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_InShow,     false)
    setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_PosOk,      false)
    setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_PosEnabled, false)
    setNanoFlag(Controls.NanoHost_HostUp,     false)
    setNanoFlagRev(Controls.NanoHost_Cancel,  false)
    blankNanoTimers()
    -- v1.3.0.17: row numbers never change (row 3 is always "3") -- set once
    -- here, before blankShowSchedule() hides every row until real data
    -- arrives.
    if Controls.NanoHost_Show_RowNum then
      for i = 1, MAX_SHOWS do
        if Controls.NanoHost_Show_RowNum[i] then Controls.NanoHost_Show_RowNum[i].String = tostring(i) end
      end
    end
    blankShowSchedule()
    if Controls.NanoHost_TimeOfDay then
      Controls.NanoHost_TimeOfDay.String = os.date("%m/%d/%Y %H:%M:%S")
    end
  end
  pollTimer:Start(POLL_RATE)
  scrapeTimer:Start(SCRAPE_RATE)
  connect()
  local ip = Controls.IP_ADDRESS.String
  if httpSock and isValidIP(ip) then httpSock:Connect(ip, 80) end
  dbg("Plugin started. port=" .. TCP_PORT)

end  -- if Controls